WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.680
[Amit Varma]: You're listening to the first episode of 2021 and a horrible year is behind us.

00:00:11.680 --> 00:00:16.040
[Amit Varma]: It's safe to say that 2020 changed the way we live our lives forever.

00:00:16.040 --> 00:00:17.240
[Amit Varma]: It changed the way we work.

00:00:17.240 --> 00:00:19.080
[Amit Varma]: It changed the way we spend our time.

00:00:19.080 --> 00:00:21.880
[Amit Varma]: It changed the way we relate to other people.

00:00:21.880 --> 00:00:26.640
[Amit Varma]: Most of all, it forced all of us to spend more time with ourselves and perhaps re-examine

00:00:26.640 --> 00:00:28.320
[Amit Varma]: what our priorities are.

00:00:28.320 --> 00:00:33.560
[Amit Varma]: There are many lessons we can draw from 2020 and this episode is about some of them.

00:00:33.560 --> 00:00:38.560
[Amit Varma]: But the most important one and perhaps the most obvious one is this, do not take anything

00:00:38.560 --> 00:00:39.560
[Amit Varma]: for granted.

00:00:39.560 --> 00:00:43.920
[Amit Varma]: Cherish all that is good in your life and don't be too disheartened by all the bad things

00:00:43.920 --> 00:00:44.920
[Amit Varma]: that happen.

00:00:44.920 --> 00:00:46.280
[Amit Varma]: This too shall end.

00:00:46.280 --> 00:00:54.800
[Amit Varma]: No matter how 2020 was for you, I hope 2021 will bring you happiness.

00:00:54.800 --> 00:00:57.240
[Unknown]: Welcome to the seen and the unseen.

00:00:57.240 --> 00:01:01.320
[Unknown]: Our weekly podcast on economics, politics, and behavioral science.

00:01:01.320 --> 00:01:07.280
[Amit Varma]: Please welcome your host, Amit Bharma.

00:01:07.280 --> 00:01:08.480
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to the seen and the unseen.

00:01:08.480 --> 00:01:14.480
[Amit Varma]: I wanted to spend this first episode of 2021 taking stock of what we learned in 2020.

00:01:14.480 --> 00:01:20.040
[Amit Varma]: To this effect, I invited my friends Shruti Rajgopalan and Alex Tabarrok onto the show.

00:01:20.040 --> 00:01:23.480
[Amit Varma]: They have both been frequent guests before on the seen and the unseen.

00:01:23.480 --> 00:01:29.400
[Amit Varma]: Shruti is a constitutional economist who works for the Mercatus Center and Alex is an economist

00:01:29.400 --> 00:01:34.440
[Amit Varma]: who is one of the two co-authors of the best blog in the world, Marginal Revolution.

00:01:34.440 --> 00:01:38.480
[Amit Varma]: He is also one of the brains behind the incredible Marginal Revolution University.

00:01:38.480 --> 00:01:40.720
[Amit Varma]: Here's how we structured this episode.

00:01:40.720 --> 00:01:46.200
[Amit Varma]: Shruti, Alex, and I each came prepared with a list of five lessons we think 2020 held

00:01:46.200 --> 00:01:47.280
[Amit Varma]: for us.

00:01:47.280 --> 00:01:51.640
[Amit Varma]: And during our free-flowing conversation, we actually came up with even more lessons

00:01:51.640 --> 00:01:53.440
[Amit Varma]: than the 15 you would expect.

00:01:53.440 --> 00:01:57.840
[Amit Varma]: You may not agree with us on all of these, but our aim was to be thought-provoking and

00:01:57.840 --> 00:02:03.320
[Amit Varma]: everything Shruti and Alex said certainly gave me ideas to process and mull over.

00:02:03.320 --> 00:02:09.680
[Amit Varma]: Before we get to the conversation, though, let's take a quick commercial break.

00:02:09.680 --> 00:02:14.160
[Amit Varma]: It's no surprise that over the 206 episodes of the seen and the unseen, I've had many

00:02:14.160 --> 00:02:18.160
[Amit Varma]: economists on the show, even when we are not talking about economics.

00:02:18.160 --> 00:02:23.440
[Amit Varma]: That's because, as I keep saying, economics is the study of human behavior, the tools

00:02:23.440 --> 00:02:27.880
[Amit Varma]: of economics can help us understand the world better, and even live our lives better.

00:02:27.880 --> 00:02:32.000
[Amit Varma]: So I'd like to introduce you today to a new podcast that I've been following.

00:02:32.000 --> 00:02:36.320
[Amit Varma]: Think Like an Economist is a podcast hosted by the famous economists, Betsy Stevenson

00:02:36.320 --> 00:02:37.840
[Amit Varma]: and Justin Wolfers.

00:02:37.840 --> 00:02:42.760
[Amit Varma]: In small bite-sized episodes of less than 20 minutes, they shed light on a number of

00:02:42.760 --> 00:02:43.760
[Amit Varma]: fascinating subjects.

00:02:43.760 --> 00:02:48.360
[Amit Varma]: For example, how can we live our lives without regrets?

00:02:48.360 --> 00:02:52.240
[Amit Varma]: Why the best drummer in a band should not necessarily be the guy doing the drumming?

00:02:52.240 --> 00:02:54.160
[Amit Varma]: Think of Paul McCartney and the Beatles.

00:02:54.160 --> 00:02:59.000
[Amit Varma]: Why it may often be difficult to forgive, but it is rational to do so.

00:02:59.000 --> 00:03:03.440
[Amit Varma]: Stevenson and Wolfers will be joined by guests like Janet Yellen of Federal Reserve fame

00:03:03.440 --> 00:03:06.600
[Amit Varma]: and two-time Basia Prize winner Tim Harford.

00:03:06.600 --> 00:03:10.320
[Amit Varma]: Think Like an Economist is available on all podcast apps.

00:03:10.320 --> 00:03:16.000
[Amit Varma]: And you can also go over to himalaya.com slash econ and enter the bonus code econ for a free

00:03:16.000 --> 00:03:18.240
[Amit Varma]: trial of some of the podcast premium features.

00:03:18.240 --> 00:03:20.280
[Amit Varma]: I'll put that link in the show notes.

00:03:20.280 --> 00:03:24.960
[Amit Varma]: And I have to say I love the name of the show because it's what I try to do so often.

00:03:24.960 --> 00:03:26.920
[Amit Varma]: Think Like an Economist.

00:03:26.920 --> 00:03:32.640
[Amit Varma]: Shruti and Alex, welcome to the scene and the unseen.

00:03:32.640 --> 00:03:33.640
[Guest 2]: Hi, Amit.

00:03:33.640 --> 00:03:34.640
[Amit Varma]: It's good to be here.

00:03:34.640 --> 00:03:37.400
[Amit Varma]: We are recording this towards the end of December.

00:03:37.400 --> 00:03:39.240
[Amit Varma]: It's been quite a crazy year.

00:03:39.240 --> 00:03:43.320
[Amit Varma]: We actually all of us recorded in the same room when I was visiting Delhi and you guys

00:03:43.320 --> 00:03:45.200
[Amit Varma]: were also there earlier this year.

00:03:45.200 --> 00:03:46.520
[Amit Varma]: And that seems so long away.

00:03:46.520 --> 00:03:48.920
[Amit Varma]: It seems like a different world and time.

00:03:48.920 --> 00:03:52.120
[Amit Varma]: So how have your years been, Shruti?

00:03:52.120 --> 00:03:53.120
[Amit Varma]: You go first.

00:03:53.120 --> 00:03:56.480
[Guest 2]: Given the circumstances, surprisingly good.

00:03:56.480 --> 00:04:00.720
[Guest 2]: You know, I mean, in the sense I have a job and we've been healthy, we've been able to

00:04:00.720 --> 00:04:03.320
[Guest 2]: socially distance and shelter in place.

00:04:03.320 --> 00:04:08.040
[Guest 2]: I have a kind of job that, you know, you can just immediately do from home seamlessly,

00:04:08.040 --> 00:04:09.040
[Guest 2]: right?

00:04:09.040 --> 00:04:10.720
[Guest 2]: The technology helps.

00:04:10.720 --> 00:04:15.200
[Guest 2]: If this had happened even 10, 12 years ago, I don't think I would have had access to broadband

00:04:15.200 --> 00:04:17.880
[Guest 2]: and online libraries and stuff like that.

00:04:17.880 --> 00:04:20.320
[Guest 2]: So given the circumstances, surprisingly good.

00:04:20.320 --> 00:04:22.560
[Guest 1]: Yeah, that's true for me as well.

00:04:22.560 --> 00:04:28.480
[Guest 1]: A little bit embarrassed to say because things have been going well, given what a terrible

00:04:28.480 --> 00:04:31.360
[Guest 1]: situation so many other people are in.

00:04:31.360 --> 00:04:34.760
[Guest 1]: You know, I was teaching online to begin with.

00:04:34.760 --> 00:04:39.960
[Guest 1]: So that has not disrupted my life too much.

00:04:39.960 --> 00:04:46.240
[Guest 1]: And I found myself kind of, oddly, I was asked to speak to the White House and to the Council

00:04:46.240 --> 00:04:50.520
[Guest 1]: of Economic Advisers to give them some advice on prizes.

00:04:50.520 --> 00:04:57.480
[Guest 1]: And I went to that talk, and it turned out to be me and Nobel Prize winner Michael Kramer

00:04:57.480 --> 00:04:58.680
[Guest 1]: talking to them.

00:04:58.680 --> 00:05:04.120
[Guest 1]: So we gave them some advice, and I was very sort of forthright and forceful, and Michael

00:05:04.120 --> 00:05:10.680
[Guest 1]: Kramer was more reserved and conservative, but that turned out to be a good team.

00:05:10.680 --> 00:05:16.400
[Guest 1]: And they asked us to start writing some reports for them, and Michael Kramer then pulled out

00:05:16.400 --> 00:05:21.440
[Guest 1]: his Rolodex and started calling all of his friends, like Susan Athey and Chris Snyder,

00:05:21.440 --> 00:05:28.320
[Guest 1]: all these top-notch economists all around the world to start writing and advising governments.

00:05:28.320 --> 00:05:34.680
[Guest 1]: So I found myself unexpectedly on this team, and it's been very intellectually stimulating

00:05:34.680 --> 00:05:35.680
[Guest 1]: for me.

00:05:35.680 --> 00:05:40.080
[Guest 1]: Again, I sort of hate to say that because so many other people, you know, it's been

00:05:40.080 --> 00:05:44.880
[Guest 1]: a terrible, terrible year, but at least intellectually, it's been stimulating for me.

00:05:44.880 --> 00:05:45.880
[Amit Varma]: Wow.

00:05:45.880 --> 00:05:46.880
[Amit Varma]: Okay.

00:05:46.880 --> 00:05:51.840
[Amit Varma]: That sounds like a much more impactful year than I think many others have had, certainly

00:05:51.840 --> 00:05:52.840
[Amit Varma]: me.

00:05:52.840 --> 00:05:58.600
[Amit Varma]: We know the kind of theme of the episode, five lessons from 2020, and at least as far

00:05:58.600 --> 00:06:03.800
[Amit Varma]: as, you know, my lessons are concerned, there are more things that I have had reason to

00:06:03.800 --> 00:06:08.400
[Amit Varma]: think about, you know, through the course of the year and not necessarily something

00:06:08.400 --> 00:06:14.600
[Amit Varma]: that wasn't true earlier or something that, you know, suddenly came to light in 2020 itself,

00:06:14.600 --> 00:06:19.240
[Amit Varma]: but just circumstances make you think about different things in particular ways.

00:06:19.240 --> 00:06:24.280
[Amit Varma]: So all my listeners, how we're going to do this is each of us have prepared five lessons

00:06:24.280 --> 00:06:27.120
[Amit Varma]: that 2020 holds for us in general.

00:06:27.120 --> 00:06:32.920
[Amit Varma]: These are our personal takes, and we'll go one by one in the sense, you know, first Alex

00:06:32.920 --> 00:06:36.840
[Amit Varma]: and Shruti, then me and rinse and repeat four more times.

00:06:36.840 --> 00:06:42.040
[Amit Varma]: And yeah, and if you're still with us, we'll have 15 such lessons.

00:06:42.040 --> 00:06:46.640
[Amit Varma]: So Alex, you know, because you joined the session last, it has been decided by those

00:06:46.640 --> 00:06:49.560
[Amit Varma]: who were here before you that you are first to go.

00:06:49.560 --> 00:06:50.560
[Guest 1]: Okay.

00:06:50.560 --> 00:06:59.040
[Guest 1]: So let me start with a bit of philosophy, and that is the omission-commission distinction.

00:06:59.040 --> 00:07:02.280
[Guest 1]: I think this needs to be destroyed because it's killing people.

00:07:02.280 --> 00:07:03.520
[Guest 1]: It's killing people.

00:07:03.520 --> 00:07:06.160
[Guest 1]: So what is the omission-commission distinction?

00:07:06.160 --> 00:07:11.800
[Guest 1]: This is basically the idea that killing somebody is worse than letting them die, right?

00:07:11.800 --> 00:07:16.920
[Guest 1]: Which kind of has some sense in some circumstances, but it's been overgeneralized, and I think

00:07:16.920 --> 00:07:18.960
[Guest 1]: it's creating a huge amount of problems.

00:07:18.960 --> 00:07:24.400
[Guest 1]: One of the first studies of this actually sort of accidentally, but good for our purposes,

00:07:24.400 --> 00:07:25.880
[Guest 1]: was on vaccines.

00:07:25.880 --> 00:07:31.200
[Guest 1]: So if you ask people, suppose there's some disease which kills, you know, 10 out of every

00:07:31.200 --> 00:07:36.880
[Guest 1]: hundred thousand people, and then there's a vaccine, and the vaccine can also have some

00:07:36.880 --> 00:07:37.880
[Guest 1]: side effects.

00:07:37.880 --> 00:07:39.320
[Guest 1]: It could also hurt people.

00:07:39.320 --> 00:07:44.600
[Guest 1]: That is the minimum, you know, death rate which you would accept to take the vaccine,

00:07:44.600 --> 00:07:45.600
[Guest 1]: right?

00:07:45.600 --> 00:07:49.120
[Guest 1]: So the disease kills 10 out of every hundred thousand.

00:07:49.120 --> 00:07:54.440
[Guest 1]: People are still not willing to take the vaccine even when it's like 2 out of 100,000, you

00:07:54.440 --> 00:07:55.440
[Guest 1]: know?

00:07:55.440 --> 00:08:01.040
[Guest 1]: They are much, much more hesitant to take the vaccine even when it has a lower death

00:08:01.040 --> 00:08:02.040
[Guest 1]: rate.

00:08:02.040 --> 00:08:09.600
[Guest 1]: And kind of the reason for that seems to be that if you choose the vaccine and your child

00:08:09.600 --> 00:08:14.440
[Guest 1]: or you or your spouse die, then you cause the death, right?

00:08:14.440 --> 00:08:15.860
[Guest 1]: It's sort of your fault.

00:08:15.860 --> 00:08:17.640
[Guest 1]: That's how people think about this.

00:08:17.640 --> 00:08:23.360
[Guest 1]: On the other hand, if you choose not to take the vaccine and you die from the disease,

00:08:23.360 --> 00:08:25.280
[Guest 1]: well, that was just bad luck.

00:08:25.280 --> 00:08:27.240
[Guest 1]: I mean, that's not your fault.

00:08:27.240 --> 00:08:29.000
[Guest 1]: You didn't make a decision.

00:08:29.000 --> 00:08:31.560
[Guest 1]: Of course, this is crazy, right?

00:08:31.560 --> 00:08:35.160
[Guest 1]: And this is a very bad kind of decision-making, right?

00:08:35.160 --> 00:08:42.480
[Guest 1]: To me, as a sort of consequentialist, utilitarian, cost-benefit economist, I'm going to say,

00:08:42.480 --> 00:08:48.120
[Guest 1]: look, take the vaccine so long as the death rate is less than 9, you know, less than 10

00:08:48.120 --> 00:08:49.760
[Guest 1]: out of every 100,000.

00:08:49.760 --> 00:08:50.760
[Guest 1]: You're better off.

00:08:50.760 --> 00:08:53.000
[Guest 1]: Just do the thing which makes you better off.

00:08:53.000 --> 00:08:54.580
[Guest 1]: And yet people don't do this.

00:08:54.580 --> 00:09:01.680
[Guest 1]: And we've seen this error apply not just to ordinary people who, you know, maybe, you

00:09:01.680 --> 00:09:05.560
[Guest 1]: know, they make mistakes or they're low educated.

00:09:05.560 --> 00:09:08.800
[Guest 1]: I don't actually think this is true, but you might think that, oh, maybe it's just people

00:09:08.800 --> 00:09:10.880
[Guest 1]: of low education make this mistake.

00:09:10.880 --> 00:09:14.480
[Guest 1]: No, our leaders make this mistake time and time again.

00:09:14.480 --> 00:09:21.520
[Guest 1]: So for example, we could have done challenge trials for a vaccine.

00:09:21.520 --> 00:09:28.600
[Guest 1]: So a challenge trial, as you probably know, is where you take a small group of people

00:09:28.600 --> 00:09:33.960
[Guest 1]: and some of them you give the vaccine, some of them you don't, and then you deliberately

00:09:33.960 --> 00:09:38.640
[Guest 1]: expose them all to the virus.

00:09:38.640 --> 00:09:45.860
[Guest 1]: The virtue of a challenge trial is with only about 100 people, you can very, very quickly

00:09:45.860 --> 00:09:49.920
[Guest 1]: find out whether the vaccine is working.

00:09:49.920 --> 00:09:51.360
[Guest 1]: Now we didn't do that.

00:09:51.360 --> 00:09:52.360
[Guest 1]: Why not?

00:09:52.360 --> 00:09:56.880
[Guest 1]: Because, well, if to do that, we have to expose people, we have somebody might die.

00:09:56.880 --> 00:10:02.140
[Guest 1]: Even though there were institutions like One Day Sooner who had got tens of thousands of

00:10:02.140 --> 00:10:06.760
[Guest 1]: people willing to do a challenge trial, nobody did one.

00:10:06.760 --> 00:10:08.000
[Guest 1]: So instead, what did we do?

00:10:08.000 --> 00:10:11.280
[Guest 1]: Well, we did a randomized controlled trial, which is good.

00:10:11.280 --> 00:10:16.800
[Guest 1]: But look, what we did, Pfizer and Moderna and so forth, they got 40,000 people, much

00:10:16.800 --> 00:10:21.960
[Guest 1]: bigger sample, gave half of them, gave 20,000 people the vaccine.

00:10:21.960 --> 00:10:25.320
[Guest 1]: And then he said, oh, just go off and do your thing, right?

00:10:25.320 --> 00:10:27.120
[Guest 1]: Just behave normally.

00:10:27.120 --> 00:10:30.360
[Guest 1]: And then what they found, of course, is the vaccine was highly effective.

00:10:30.360 --> 00:10:37.520
[Guest 1]: But look, 20,000 people were doing their own thing, and some of them got the virus.

00:10:37.520 --> 00:10:39.800
[Guest 1]: Some of them got COVID, right?

00:10:39.800 --> 00:10:45.000
[Guest 1]: So the omission-commission distinction, again, came here because we weren't willing to do

00:10:45.000 --> 00:10:50.800
[Guest 1]: the thing which was cheap and quick and fast because, oh, you've got to give them the virus.

00:10:50.800 --> 00:10:52.320
[Guest 1]: You're doing something bad.

00:10:52.320 --> 00:10:58.840
[Guest 1]: On the other hand, doing a randomized controlled trial in which 20,000 people were left exposed

00:10:58.840 --> 00:11:03.160
[Guest 1]: to get COVID, and a bunch of them did get COVID, well, that's okay because we're not

00:11:03.160 --> 00:11:04.900
[Guest 1]: causing them.

00:11:04.900 --> 00:11:06.720
[Guest 1]: That's an error of omission.

00:11:06.720 --> 00:11:12.160
[Guest 1]: We're not helping them, but we're not stopping them, you know, and we're not requiring them

00:11:12.160 --> 00:11:13.660
[Guest 1]: to get the virus.

00:11:13.660 --> 00:11:18.320
[Guest 1]: So again, this was just kind of crazy, I think, that we didn't do the sensible thing.

00:11:18.320 --> 00:11:19.940
[Guest 1]: And we saw this again and again.

00:11:19.940 --> 00:11:22.840
[Guest 1]: So it's very surprising.

00:11:22.840 --> 00:11:24.920
[Guest 1]: The military, right?

00:11:24.920 --> 00:11:29.840
[Guest 1]: Like the military, you would think that the military would be among the first people to

00:11:29.840 --> 00:11:32.640
[Guest 1]: sort of volunteer for things like this.

00:11:32.640 --> 00:11:34.240
[Guest 1]: But no, we couldn't do that.

00:11:34.240 --> 00:11:39.440
[Guest 1]: And again, when it comes to FDA approval, right, there's a very big asymmetry.

00:11:39.440 --> 00:11:45.920
[Guest 1]: We think that the disease, that's rampant, you know, right now, three and a half thousand

00:11:45.920 --> 00:11:48.680
[Guest 1]: people a day are dying in the United States.

00:11:48.680 --> 00:11:49.680
[Guest 1]: That's rampant.

00:11:49.680 --> 00:11:54.240
[Guest 1]: But we couldn't possibly approve a vaccine early.

00:11:54.240 --> 00:11:58.120
[Guest 1]: We have to do, you know, the FDA kept reassuring us.

00:11:58.120 --> 00:11:59.440
[Guest 1]: We're not cutting corners.

00:11:59.440 --> 00:12:02.200
[Guest 1]: Well, wait a second.

00:12:02.200 --> 00:12:03.560
[Guest 1]: There's a virus out there.

00:12:03.560 --> 00:12:04.560
[Guest 1]: There's a pandemic.

00:12:04.560 --> 00:12:08.720
[Guest 1]: Surely, there is a time in which you should be cutting corners, right?

00:12:08.720 --> 00:12:14.280
[Guest 1]: I mean, I mean, you know, there is a time and place for going slow, but there's also

00:12:14.280 --> 00:12:16.680
[Guest 1]: a time and place for cutting corners.

00:12:16.680 --> 00:12:17.680
[Guest 1]: That's how you get there fast.

00:12:17.680 --> 00:12:18.680
[Guest 1]: Right.

00:12:18.680 --> 00:12:19.680
[Guest 1]: That's you're on the racetrack.

00:12:19.680 --> 00:12:20.680
[Guest 1]: You're supposed to cut the corner.

00:12:20.680 --> 00:12:21.680
[Guest 1]: Right.

00:12:21.680 --> 00:12:27.080
[Guest 1]: But yet, you know, we had to reassure, oh, we can't be doing anything unsafe.

00:12:27.080 --> 00:12:28.680
[Guest 1]: And again, that seems crazy.

00:12:28.680 --> 00:12:30.800
[Guest 2]: So that's my lesson.

00:12:30.800 --> 00:12:33.200
[Guest 2]: It's almost like the seen and the unseen, right?

00:12:33.200 --> 00:12:35.160
[Guest 2]: Like, that's exactly what it is, right?

00:12:35.160 --> 00:12:38.880
[Guest 2]: We see certain types of deaths and we ignore other types of deaths.

00:12:38.880 --> 00:12:44.000
[Guest 2]: And I think the larger lesson of what Alex is saying, I think it goes beyond the pandemic.

00:12:44.000 --> 00:12:45.000
[Guest 2]: Right.

00:12:45.000 --> 00:12:48.600
[Guest 2]: It goes to all sorts of clinical trials like, you know, it takes like eight years and a

00:12:48.600 --> 00:12:52.720
[Guest 2]: billion dollars to get any new breakthrough through the FDA.

00:12:52.720 --> 00:12:58.640
[Guest 2]: So no wonder we don't have more, you know, life saving medication and vaccines, you know,

00:12:58.640 --> 00:13:03.320
[Guest 2]: available to poorer countries and things like that, because it's just so damn expensive

00:13:03.320 --> 00:13:06.640
[Guest 2]: to get these through the door in the developed world.

00:13:06.640 --> 00:13:13.280
[Guest 2]: And the other part also is like this bizarre misplaced sense of equity, like this one version

00:13:13.280 --> 00:13:21.720
[Guest 2]: of equity, which is only parentalism or, you know, some kind of paternalism where apparently

00:13:21.720 --> 00:13:26.640
[Guest 2]: people are not smart enough to take the risks that they wish to take.

00:13:26.640 --> 00:13:27.760
[Guest 2]: Right.

00:13:27.760 --> 00:13:34.360
[Guest 2]: Some of the vaccine trials are lower risk than getting on a skateboard, right, or bungee

00:13:34.360 --> 00:13:37.080
[Guest 2]: jumping or getting on a motorcycle.

00:13:37.080 --> 00:13:38.600
[Guest 2]: And we let people do that all the time.

00:13:38.600 --> 00:13:39.600
[Guest 2]: Right.

00:13:39.600 --> 00:13:44.280
[Guest 2]: So there's this very misplaced sense of, oh, of course, they're willing to take the risk,

00:13:44.280 --> 00:13:45.760
[Guest 2]: but they don't know better.

00:13:45.760 --> 00:13:47.080
[Guest 2]: That's why they're willing to take the risk.

00:13:47.080 --> 00:13:48.080
[Guest 2]: Right.

00:13:48.080 --> 00:13:49.080
[Guest 2]: They are too poor.

00:13:49.080 --> 00:13:50.640
[Guest 2]: And that's why they are forced to take the risk.

00:13:50.640 --> 00:13:51.640
[Guest 2]: You know, something like that.

00:13:51.640 --> 00:13:54.840
[Guest 2]: Like the moment you would say something about maybe the military should do this, they'd

00:13:54.840 --> 00:13:58.160
[Guest 2]: start talking about, you know, how there are more people from lower income families who

00:13:58.160 --> 00:13:59.160
[Guest 2]: join the military.

00:13:59.160 --> 00:14:01.040
[Guest 2]: And it's inherently unfair.

00:14:01.040 --> 00:14:04.620
[Guest 2]: And I'm sure there are a lot of people from poorer neighborhoods or people who genuinely

00:14:04.620 --> 00:14:08.480
[Guest 2]: believe in public service, firefighters, people in the military who would have been happy

00:14:08.480 --> 00:14:09.480
[Guest 2]: to do it.

00:14:09.480 --> 00:14:15.200
[Guest 2]: I know a couple of people in the UK who were part of the vaccine, the randomized trial.

00:14:15.200 --> 00:14:16.480
[Guest 2]: They were happy to do it.

00:14:16.480 --> 00:14:17.480
[Guest 2]: Right.

00:14:17.480 --> 00:14:20.560
[Guest 2]: They knew the risks involved and they didn't think it was insane.

00:14:20.560 --> 00:14:22.240
[Guest 2]: They were young, they were healthy, they were fit.

00:14:22.240 --> 00:14:23.600
[Guest 2]: They said, I'm single, I don't have kids.

00:14:23.600 --> 00:14:25.040
[Guest 2]: I think that's a good idea.

00:14:25.040 --> 00:14:30.840
[Guest 2]: So we do end up taking more risk when people think, but they don't want, you know, quote

00:14:30.840 --> 00:14:32.400
[Guest 2]: unquote blood on their hands.

00:14:32.400 --> 00:14:33.400
[Guest 2]: Right.

00:14:33.400 --> 00:14:34.400
[Guest 2]: So that's kind of what's going on.

00:14:34.400 --> 00:14:35.400
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

00:14:35.400 --> 00:14:39.000
[Amit Varma]: I mean, when Alex was, you know, describing the concept, the same phrase popped to my

00:14:39.000 --> 00:14:40.000
[Amit Varma]: mind.

00:14:40.000 --> 00:14:43.840
[Amit Varma]: This is the scene in the unseen in the sense that you have the scene effects of action,

00:14:43.840 --> 00:14:48.080
[Amit Varma]: but you don't see the unseen effects of inaction or at least you don't consider them.

00:14:48.080 --> 00:14:52.440
[Amit Varma]: You know, when we did that episode on COVID in April, Shruti, we also discussed how, you

00:14:52.440 --> 00:14:57.080
[Amit Varma]: know, the problem with any policy decision at a time like this is that the lives that

00:14:57.080 --> 00:15:03.760
[Amit Varma]: go because of it will be seen, but the lives that are saved will therefore be unseen.

00:15:03.760 --> 00:15:07.240
[Amit Varma]: And in a sense, the same logic, of course, applies to the FDA with the legendary delays

00:15:07.240 --> 00:15:12.360
[Amit Varma]: and all that, that, you know, they talk about the lives that they are saving by taking their

00:15:12.360 --> 00:15:16.560
[Amit Varma]: time, but you don't, you know, what is unseen is the lives that could have been saved had

00:15:16.560 --> 00:15:18.400
[Amit Varma]: they moved a little quicker.

00:15:18.400 --> 00:15:20.240
[Amit Varma]: And again, I agree on the voluntary thing.

00:15:20.240 --> 00:15:25.960
[Amit Varma]: I mean, that's really my one metric for thinking about policy or thinking about action in any

00:15:25.960 --> 00:15:28.480
[Amit Varma]: sphere is that how much of it is voluntary.

00:15:28.480 --> 00:15:33.080
[Amit Varma]: And when you have people actually signing up and volunteering for this trial, so it's

00:15:33.080 --> 00:15:37.680
[Amit Varma]: not like a decision that a government has to make that do we inflict this and, you know,

00:15:37.680 --> 00:15:41.160
[Amit Varma]: it's 10 deaths in one group of people versus 100 in another.

00:15:41.160 --> 00:15:44.960
[Amit Varma]: People are volunteering to be part of a trial aware of the risks.

00:15:44.960 --> 00:15:48.360
[Amit Varma]: So you know, why would you not just go for that?

00:15:48.360 --> 00:15:52.320
[Amit Varma]: So yeah, it's very resonant at different levels.

00:15:52.320 --> 00:15:54.520
[Amit Varma]: And Shruti, it's your turn now.

00:15:54.520 --> 00:15:59.480
[Guest 2]: Ah, so you know, one of the things that I learned this year is something I've not paid

00:15:59.480 --> 00:16:07.000
[Guest 2]: any attention to for the most part, except academically, which is tail risks, right?

00:16:07.000 --> 00:16:12.400
[Guest 2]: So these are very low probability events, but when they do happen, and it's uncertain

00:16:12.400 --> 00:16:17.280
[Guest 2]: if they will ever happen, they come at a very, very high cost, right?

00:16:17.280 --> 00:16:21.160
[Guest 2]: And so one way of thinking about this is the way, you know, the public choice way, which

00:16:21.160 --> 00:16:26.000
[Guest 2]: is governments are never going to act on these matters because, you know, these things may

00:16:26.000 --> 00:16:27.000
[Guest 2]: never happen.

00:16:27.000 --> 00:16:31.160
[Guest 2]: The prevention is so costly, it requires massive amount of coordination.

00:16:31.160 --> 00:16:35.760
[Guest 2]: And there's literally no interest group that is trying to get this going, right?

00:16:35.760 --> 00:16:39.360
[Guest 2]: On the other hand, there are so many urgent needs and there are so many interest groups,

00:16:39.360 --> 00:16:43.640
[Guest 2]: you know, whether it's sugar subsidy to, you know, stimulus payments to social security

00:16:43.640 --> 00:16:44.640
[Guest 2]: to education.

00:16:44.640 --> 00:16:49.800
[Guest 2]: There are so many interest groups lobbying for so many things that those things get prioritized

00:16:49.800 --> 00:16:52.480
[Guest 2]: and perhaps rightly so in the democratic process, right?

00:16:52.480 --> 00:16:54.280
[Guest 2]: Maybe this is how it's supposed to work.

00:16:54.280 --> 00:16:58.320
[Guest 2]: But I think this year has really taught us that we need to pay more attention to tail

00:16:58.320 --> 00:16:59.320
[Guest 2]: risks, right?

00:16:59.320 --> 00:17:01.120
[Guest 2]: And there have been people who've talked about this before.

00:17:01.120 --> 00:17:05.360
[Guest 2]: So, of course, Bill Gates has famously talked about, you know, pandemics and how we need

00:17:05.360 --> 00:17:10.320
[Guest 2]: to focus on, you know, some kind of not just pandemic prevention plan, but also pandemic

00:17:10.320 --> 00:17:13.340
[Guest 2]: action plan like vaccines and things like that.

00:17:13.340 --> 00:17:17.440
[Guest 2]: You know, there is Bill Norders, who won the Nobel Prize a few years ago, talked about

00:17:17.440 --> 00:17:19.960
[Guest 2]: the tail risks coming out of climate change, right?

00:17:19.960 --> 00:17:22.680
[Guest 2]: Something that we just literally pay no attention to.

00:17:22.680 --> 00:17:29.600
[Guest 2]: If you want to lose sleep tonight, you should ask Alex about asteroids hitting the Earth,

00:17:29.600 --> 00:17:34.920
[Guest 2]: solar flares killing our communication systems and other really terrifying.

00:17:34.920 --> 00:17:37.300
[Guest 2]: It's scary to talk to Alex about these things.

00:17:37.300 --> 00:17:41.160
[Guest 2]: But Alex has written about these sort of, you know, tail risks that no one pays attention

00:17:41.160 --> 00:17:42.160
[Guest 2]: to.

00:17:42.160 --> 00:17:44.120
[Guest 2]: They are a little bit apocalyptic.

00:17:44.120 --> 00:17:49.440
[Guest 2]: So I think it might make sense for the world to start thinking a little bit more about

00:17:49.440 --> 00:17:51.400
[Guest 2]: tail risks and paying attention.

00:17:51.400 --> 00:17:56.320
[Guest 2]: I don't think, you know, your standard democratic government process is a good way of doing

00:17:56.320 --> 00:17:57.320
[Guest 2]: it.

00:17:57.320 --> 00:18:01.800
[Guest 2]: I think, you know, maybe the multilateral United Nations coalition, you know, something

00:18:01.800 --> 00:18:06.200
[Guest 2]: like that, something that we developed post World War II to end a different kind of apocalyptic

00:18:06.200 --> 00:18:07.560
[Guest 2]: world, right?

00:18:07.560 --> 00:18:11.360
[Guest 2]: Something like that might be more suitable, where people who are a little bit removed

00:18:11.360 --> 00:18:16.940
[Guest 2]: from everyday politics, you know, with some level of, you know, government funding and

00:18:16.940 --> 00:18:21.240
[Guest 2]: backing exactly like the UN or the World Bank or something, you know, they are the people

00:18:21.240 --> 00:18:25.440
[Guest 2]: who are staffed and in charge of solely thinking about these kinds of problems.

00:18:25.440 --> 00:18:29.040
[Guest 2]: Right now, there are some risks to this because, you know, that can become its own lobbying

00:18:29.040 --> 00:18:31.560
[Guest 2]: effort, right, to get more money for these things.

00:18:31.560 --> 00:18:35.480
[Guest 2]: You might play up these apocalyptic situations and spread paranoia.

00:18:35.480 --> 00:18:41.240
[Guest 2]: But frankly, right now, we are thinking so little about tail risks that we might be better

00:18:41.240 --> 00:18:47.840
[Guest 2]: off if people did go with some scaremongering tactics, and if they did form a legitimate

00:18:47.840 --> 00:18:52.120
[Guest 2]: interest group or lobby to, you know, seriously lobby for these sorts of things.

00:18:52.120 --> 00:18:56.400
[Guest 2]: So I think, you know, climate change has gotten it going, but climate change, again, they

00:18:56.400 --> 00:19:01.240
[Guest 2]: are not so focused on tail risks, they are too focused on immediate marginal, you know,

00:19:01.240 --> 00:19:05.520
[Guest 2]: what should the emission level be at kind of discussion, they don't really focus on

00:19:05.520 --> 00:19:08.000
[Guest 2]: some of the really terrifying situations.

00:19:08.000 --> 00:19:12.220
[Guest 2]: So I think, you know, we could have a little bit more of that, and certainly on the question

00:19:12.220 --> 00:19:13.220
[Guest 2]: of pandemics.

00:19:13.220 --> 00:19:18.200
[Guest 2]: I mean, we're already hearing about a new mutation of the novel coronavirus, which is,

00:19:18.200 --> 00:19:22.080
[Guest 2]: you know, apparently spreads more rapidly, and we don't know anything about it yet.

00:19:22.080 --> 00:19:23.900
[Guest 2]: But apparently, these mutations are coming.

00:19:23.900 --> 00:19:27.360
[Guest 2]: So this is not the last pandemic we have seen, is my sense.

00:19:27.360 --> 00:19:31.960
[Guest 2]: And we could do this better if theoretically, we change the mental model to think about

00:19:31.960 --> 00:19:32.960
[Guest 2]: tail risks.

00:19:32.960 --> 00:19:39.000
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, just earlier today, you know, the government banned flights to India coming from to and

00:19:39.000 --> 00:19:40.000
[Unknown]: for the UK.

00:19:40.000 --> 00:19:41.000
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

00:19:41.000 --> 00:19:45.640
[Amit Varma]: And that kind of reminded me of Mahatma Gandhi's Hind Swaraj, in which he wrote about how railways

00:19:45.640 --> 00:19:48.640
[Amit Varma]: were responsible for spreading disease throughout India.

00:19:48.640 --> 00:19:50.600
[Amit Varma]: So no doubt, Gandhi would have approved of this.

00:19:50.600 --> 00:19:54.840
[Guest 1]: So I have a question for the two of you on a few hundred years too late on banning the

00:19:54.840 --> 00:19:55.840
[Amit Varma]: British.

00:19:55.840 --> 00:19:58.640
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, exactly.

00:19:58.640 --> 00:20:03.480
[Amit Varma]: So I kind of have a question for you on tail risks, which is that, when I put myself in

00:20:03.480 --> 00:20:08.840
[Amit Varma]: the shoes of a politician, and on the one hand, obviously, your imperatives are, you

00:20:08.840 --> 00:20:12.960
[Amit Varma]: know, aligned towards number one, satisfying the people who give you money, because that's

00:20:12.960 --> 00:20:16.380
[Amit Varma]: what you need to win elections, and those are the interest groups and so on.

00:20:16.380 --> 00:20:19.720
[Amit Varma]: And number two, you're catering to voters, and therefore you care about what they care

00:20:19.720 --> 00:20:22.460
[Amit Varma]: about, which is not the tail risks.

00:20:22.460 --> 00:20:25.400
[Amit Varma]: And you have limited state capacity.

00:20:25.400 --> 00:20:30.740
[Amit Varma]: As an individual politician, you have limited attentional bandwidth to devote to these matters.

00:20:30.740 --> 00:20:37.560
[Amit Varma]: So isn't it rational to ignore extremely low probable events like pandemics or and, you

00:20:37.560 --> 00:20:40.680
[Amit Varma]: know, I'd love to know more about asteroids hitting the earth as well.

00:20:40.680 --> 00:20:43.980
[Amit Varma]: But that seems to me to fall in the category of things we cannot control.

00:20:43.980 --> 00:20:45.600
[Amit Varma]: So I sweat over that.

00:20:45.600 --> 00:20:50.400
[Amit Varma]: But you know, when it comes to incentives, it's easy in hindsight to say that, you know,

00:20:50.400 --> 00:20:52.960
[Amit Varma]: politicians should have paid attention and all of that.

00:20:52.960 --> 00:20:55.440
[Amit Varma]: But is it realistic to expect that to happen?

00:20:55.440 --> 00:20:56.960
[Guest 2]: No, I completely agree with you.

00:20:56.960 --> 00:21:00.720
[Guest 2]: It's in fact rational for them not to pay attention to tail risk, which is why I think

00:21:00.720 --> 00:21:06.320
[Guest 2]: it's a lesson that we need to find something outside of democratic politics to pay attention

00:21:06.320 --> 00:21:07.320
[Guest 2]: to that.

00:21:07.320 --> 00:21:08.320
[Guest 2]: Right.

00:21:08.320 --> 00:21:12.040
[Guest 2]: We know that regular folks voting are not going to make this an important issue.

00:21:12.040 --> 00:21:14.720
[Guest 2]: They don't even make it an important issue when they're buying insurance.

00:21:14.720 --> 00:21:15.720
[Guest 2]: Right.

00:21:15.720 --> 00:21:18.440
[Guest 2]: It's really they have a lot of skin in the game.

00:21:18.440 --> 00:21:21.000
[Guest 2]: But so it's completely rational for politicians.

00:21:21.000 --> 00:21:23.560
[Guest 2]: And I think that's why this is such a big problem.

00:21:23.560 --> 00:21:27.960
[Guest 2]: And that's why even when someone like Bill Gates is willing to put his own money, right,

00:21:27.960 --> 00:21:32.320
[Guest 2]: is willing to find coalition partners, has a really big voice and a global platform and

00:21:32.320 --> 00:21:37.760
[Guest 2]: a megaphone, he gets very few takers when he does warn people about these kinds of risks.

00:21:37.760 --> 00:21:39.000
[Guest 2]: So we do need something.

00:21:39.000 --> 00:21:40.000
[Guest 2]: Right.

00:21:40.000 --> 00:21:41.000
[Guest 2]: And I agree with you.

00:21:41.000 --> 00:21:44.160
[Guest 2]: I don't think everyday politics is the obvious solution for this.

00:21:44.160 --> 00:21:47.920
[Guest 2]: Telling people that they should pay attention to something that they're rationally not going

00:21:47.920 --> 00:21:51.680
[Guest 2]: to gravitate towards has never been a good idea in any kind of politics.

00:21:51.680 --> 00:21:53.560
[Guest 1]: So there I completely agree with you.

00:21:53.560 --> 00:21:55.760
[Guest 1]: So I think there's a few things we can do.

00:21:55.760 --> 00:22:00.200
[Guest 1]: You have to find some you have to tie some private good to the public good.

00:22:00.200 --> 00:22:01.200
[Guest 1]: Right.

00:22:01.200 --> 00:22:05.720
[Guest 1]: So thinking about asteroids, for example, one of the things which is going to help us

00:22:05.720 --> 00:22:09.280
[Guest 1]: with the asteroids is if we have a bigger space program.

00:22:09.280 --> 00:22:10.280
[Guest 1]: Right.

00:22:10.280 --> 00:22:16.960
[Guest 1]: So there is a public good aspect to everything which Elon Musk and SpaceX are doing.

00:22:16.960 --> 00:22:22.280
[Guest 1]: The more capability we have to operate in space, the bigger the chance that we might

00:22:22.280 --> 00:22:28.120
[Guest 1]: be able to do something if we discovered an asteroid which was coming towards us.

00:22:28.120 --> 00:22:35.640
[Guest 1]: And by the way, just to give you the sleepless night, by some calculations, your probability

00:22:35.640 --> 00:22:41.200
[Guest 1]: of dying from an asteroid strike is about the same as your probability of dying in an

00:22:41.200 --> 00:22:42.880
[Guest 1]: airplane crash.

00:22:42.880 --> 00:22:45.480
[Guest 1]: Now you might wonder, well, how is that possible?

00:22:45.480 --> 00:22:49.120
[Guest 1]: Well, it's possible because if there's an asteroid strike, we're all dead.

00:22:49.120 --> 00:22:50.120
[Guest 1]: Right.

00:22:50.120 --> 00:22:53.280
[Guest 1]: Most of us are not going to die from an airplane crash.

00:22:53.280 --> 00:22:56.400
[Guest 1]: But if there's an asteroid strike, the whole planet is gone.

00:22:56.400 --> 00:23:00.800
[Guest 1]: So the probabilities are actually much higher than you might think.

00:23:00.800 --> 00:23:05.600
[Guest 1]: So we want to look for things with private goods which are going to help us to produce

00:23:05.600 --> 00:23:07.680
[Guest 1]: the public goods.

00:23:07.680 --> 00:23:15.040
[Guest 1]: Another related thing is the which keeps me up at night, actually, is the solar flares.

00:23:15.040 --> 00:23:20.720
[Guest 1]: You know, around 1890, this so-called Arrington event, we had a solar flare just at the beginning

00:23:20.720 --> 00:23:24.680
[Guest 1]: of the Internet of a time, the telegraph era.

00:23:24.680 --> 00:23:29.160
[Guest 1]: And that solar flare knocked out all the telegraph systems in the world.

00:23:29.160 --> 00:23:33.160
[Guest 1]: And if we had something similar today, it would knock out the Internet, it would knock

00:23:33.160 --> 00:23:34.680
[Guest 1]: out cars.

00:23:34.680 --> 00:23:38.680
[Guest 1]: You wouldn't be able to drive your car because of the electrical system.

00:23:38.680 --> 00:23:45.400
[Guest 1]: So there are things we can do today to protect our electrical systems, to protect the Internet,

00:23:45.400 --> 00:23:50.280
[Guest 1]: to shield them from this type of solar flare.

00:23:50.280 --> 00:23:56.960
[Guest 1]: And the way we might be able to do that is to attach some pork, right, to the public

00:23:56.960 --> 00:23:57.960
[Guest 1]: good.

00:23:57.960 --> 00:24:02.640
[Guest 1]: You know, here's an opportunity for firms to make some money, right, shielding all of

00:24:02.640 --> 00:24:04.780
[Guest 1]: our cables and so forth.

00:24:04.780 --> 00:24:12.720
[Guest 1]: So I think a greater awareness of these low probability events is extremely important.

00:24:12.720 --> 00:24:18.880
[Guest 1]: And the way to kind of approach it politically is to attach these private goods to producing

00:24:18.880 --> 00:24:22.760
[Guest 1]: something which has an externality, a public good externality.

00:24:22.760 --> 00:24:24.560
[Guest 2]: That's that's the end of the show.

00:24:24.560 --> 00:24:27.680
[Guest 2]: We are done after asteroids and solar flares.

00:24:27.680 --> 00:24:28.680
[Guest 2]: We can go home.

00:24:28.680 --> 00:24:33.600
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I mean, if they happen in the middle of this recording, that will be quite unlikely.

00:24:33.600 --> 00:24:36.720
[Amit Varma]: But I once wrote a column called unlikely is inevitable.

00:24:36.720 --> 00:24:41.140
[Amit Varma]: And this was part of the series of columns I did on poker, where, you know, people would

00:24:41.140 --> 00:24:45.660
[Amit Varma]: complain to me that, yeah, I got to one outers on the river, two hands in a row, that should

00:24:45.660 --> 00:24:48.960
[Amit Varma]: happen one in 4000 times, obviously, the game is rigged.

00:24:48.960 --> 00:24:51.840
[Amit Varma]: And I would just say that, no, no, the game is not rigged.

00:24:51.840 --> 00:24:56.360
[Amit Varma]: The thing is, if you consider the law of truly large numbers, then everything that in no

00:24:56.360 --> 00:25:01.740
[Amit Varma]: matter how unlikely it is to happen, given enough iterations of something, it will happen

00:25:01.740 --> 00:25:03.320
[Amit Varma]: at some point or the other.

00:25:03.320 --> 00:25:07.280
[Amit Varma]: So you know, it is unlikely that an asteroid will strike the earth.

00:25:07.280 --> 00:25:11.560
[Amit Varma]: But if we survive long enough, it is inevitable that at some point it will happen.

00:25:11.560 --> 00:25:15.120
[Amit Varma]: The only question is that will there be a solar flare right before that?

00:25:15.120 --> 00:25:17.760
[Amit Varma]: So we can't even tell each other an asteroid is coming.

00:25:17.760 --> 00:25:22.400
[Guest 2]: Actually, an asteroid is coming, there's no point telling each other, it'll be so quick,

00:25:22.400 --> 00:25:25.680
[Guest 2]: it'll be over before the broadband takes it across the world.

00:25:25.680 --> 00:25:30.160
[Amit Varma]: No, no, but you you want like a few days of drama, and you want all the religious Godmen

00:25:30.160 --> 00:25:34.640
[Amit Varma]: getting into the act and saying, do this, do that, and this is a punishment for, you

00:25:34.640 --> 00:25:36.720
[Amit Varma]: know, absence of virtue and all of that.

00:25:36.720 --> 00:25:40.800
[Amit Varma]: So you know, that little entertainment before we go.

00:25:40.800 --> 00:25:47.020
[Amit Varma]: And speaking of entertainment, my first lesson is kind of like I kind of divvied up five

00:25:47.020 --> 00:25:52.120
[Amit Varma]: lessons across the fields of entertainment, education, society, politics, and the personal,

00:25:52.120 --> 00:25:55.000
[Amit Varma]: because I figured I'll leave COVID and science to you guys.

00:25:55.000 --> 00:25:59.400
[Amit Varma]: And I'm not sure I'm, you know, I should really butt in there.

00:25:59.400 --> 00:26:04.160
[Amit Varma]: And here's my thought about entertainment, which is something that I kind of figured

00:26:04.160 --> 00:26:09.440
[Amit Varma]: out in a very personal way through the experience, in fact, of doing this podcast, that if you

00:26:09.440 --> 00:26:15.680
[Amit Varma]: go back in time, you know, entertainment and art until recently was essentially broadcasting,

00:26:15.680 --> 00:26:16.680
[Amit Varma]: right?

00:26:16.680 --> 00:26:22.640
[Amit Varma]: You had one person, maybe one artist or entertainer talking to many people, and often out of necessity,

00:26:22.640 --> 00:26:26.240
[Amit Varma]: because if you're going to be profitable, you achieve some kind of scale, you have to

00:26:26.240 --> 00:26:28.000
[Amit Varma]: kind of cater to the masses.

00:26:28.000 --> 00:26:33.480
[Amit Varma]: So very rarely are you going to have any one-on-one intimate form, which is why that whole mode

00:26:33.480 --> 00:26:36.640
[Amit Varma]: of radio broadcasting comes in where you talk in a particular way.

00:26:36.640 --> 00:26:41.560
[Amit Varma]: And there is an artifice to all of that, to the presentation and all of those things.

00:26:41.560 --> 00:26:43.700
[Amit Varma]: Now, a couple of aspects to this.

00:26:43.700 --> 00:26:49.480
[Amit Varma]: One of the things that I realized this year with the podcast was that one people seem

00:26:49.480 --> 00:26:53.980
[Amit Varma]: to feel this incredibly intimate connection to it.

00:26:53.980 --> 00:26:57.920
[Amit Varma]: And I didn't realize how much, and you know, one of the realizations I've had about

00:26:57.920 --> 00:27:02.520
[Amit Varma]: the medium, which I talk about in the course I teach on podcasting is that, you know, not

00:27:02.520 --> 00:27:07.880
[Amit Varma]: only is audio very different from other mediums because, you know, you're a passive audience

00:27:07.880 --> 00:27:11.160
[Amit Varma]: and you're listening at higher speeds and all that, but podcasting is very different

00:27:11.160 --> 00:27:14.760
[Amit Varma]: from radio because in radio you're broadcasting and talking to many people.

00:27:14.760 --> 00:27:19.320
[Amit Varma]: But when you listen to a podcast, you have a person's voice in your head and it is as

00:27:19.320 --> 00:27:21.600
[Amit Varma]: intimate as any medium can get.

00:27:21.600 --> 00:27:26.280
[Amit Varma]: And you know, all the podcasts that I listen to like Econ Talk or Tyler's podcast, you

00:27:26.280 --> 00:27:30.280
[Amit Varma]: know, you feel that connection to that person, you listen to that podcast for them.

00:27:30.280 --> 00:27:33.960
[Amit Varma]: And I sort of realized this when I opened up support for the seen and the unseen and

00:27:33.960 --> 00:27:38.560
[Amit Varma]: just saw the depth of emotion and that people kind of have for the show.

00:27:38.560 --> 00:27:42.600
[Amit Varma]: And even the 200th episode, I thought five hours of me talking about myself is intolerable,

00:27:42.600 --> 00:27:46.400
[Amit Varma]: but that's, you know, one of the most popular episodes this year.

00:27:46.400 --> 00:27:50.160
[Amit Varma]: And many people seem to have horror of horrors heard all five hours.

00:27:50.160 --> 00:27:54.600
[Amit Varma]: So well done Shruti on breaking that record as a host.

00:27:54.600 --> 00:27:58.200
[Amit Varma]: And another medium where I kind of noticed this because what's also happened is a lot

00:27:58.200 --> 00:28:03.840
[Amit Varma]: of us are sort of sitting home and consuming more content on the internet than we otherwise

00:28:03.840 --> 00:28:10.160
[Amit Varma]: would where we'll consume a lot of that content in passing is what I have seen on YouTube

00:28:10.160 --> 00:28:11.280
[Amit Varma]: in streaming.

00:28:11.280 --> 00:28:15.120
[Amit Varma]: And earlier I thought, okay, people are just streaming games or this, you know, stream

00:28:15.120 --> 00:28:16.880
[Amit Varma]: panel discussions and all of that.

00:28:16.880 --> 00:28:19.880
[Amit Varma]: And it's just, you're capturing something on video that has happened.

00:28:19.880 --> 00:28:25.520
[Amit Varma]: But some of the best streams out there are also, you know, achieve a similar level of

00:28:25.520 --> 00:28:27.760
[Amit Varma]: intimacy and personal connection.

00:28:27.760 --> 00:28:32.760
[Amit Varma]: Like one sort of development that I followed very closely is after the lockdown started,

00:28:32.760 --> 00:28:37.640
[Amit Varma]: I think towards the end of April, this guy called Samir Raina, who's a standup comedian,

00:28:37.640 --> 00:28:40.520
[Amit Varma]: 21 year old kid, he started with stream.

00:28:40.520 --> 00:28:43.480
[Amit Varma]: He was just throwing different things at the wall, trying different things, which is what

00:28:43.480 --> 00:28:45.040
[Amit Varma]: you should do as a creator.

00:28:45.040 --> 00:28:49.920
[Amit Varma]: And he started streaming on chess, an Indian grandmaster called Vidit Gujarati, who is

00:28:49.920 --> 00:28:51.480
[Amit Varma]: right now, India's number two.

00:28:51.480 --> 00:28:57.840
[Amit Varma]: He came across Samir Raina's channel and they got together, they played chess on the stream.

00:28:57.840 --> 00:29:01.840
[Amit Varma]: There's a young guy called Sagar Shah, who runs a magazine called Chess Base India.

00:29:01.840 --> 00:29:03.720
[Amit Varma]: And he's been doing stellar work for years.

00:29:03.720 --> 00:29:07.960
[Amit Varma]: And as a chess fan, I've kind of been noticing his stellar work, you know, for very small

00:29:07.960 --> 00:29:13.920
[Amit Varma]: audiences, but, you know, interviewing players, trying to demystify the game for new learners.

00:29:13.920 --> 00:29:18.360
[Amit Varma]: He came on the channel and then suddenly the whole streaming scene exploded.

00:29:18.360 --> 00:29:21.280
[Amit Varma]: Sameh helped all of them set up their own streams.

00:29:21.280 --> 00:29:25.480
[Amit Varma]: In fact, Chess Base India on YouTube has more than half a million subscribers.

00:29:25.480 --> 00:29:26.720
[Amit Varma]: It is insane.

00:29:26.720 --> 00:29:30.560
[Amit Varma]: And what they would do is they would call in these guest grandmasters, like, you know,

00:29:30.560 --> 00:29:33.720
[Amit Varma]: Magnus Carlsen and Vishy Anand have all appeared on these shows.

00:29:33.720 --> 00:29:35.520
[Amit Varma]: And they'd call in all these grandmasters.

00:29:35.520 --> 00:29:38.420
[Amit Varma]: And they'd also cover live events where they would do commentary.

00:29:38.420 --> 00:29:44.160
[Amit Varma]: And I remember one live event where they had like a three hour commentary on something.

00:29:44.160 --> 00:29:48.860
[Amit Varma]: And after that commentary was over and everybody was expected to go home, they spoke for three

00:29:48.860 --> 00:29:52.920
[Amit Varma]: more hours, where they spoke about their lives and how they got into the game and all of

00:29:52.920 --> 00:29:53.920
[Amit Varma]: that.

00:29:53.920 --> 00:29:55.400
[Amit Varma]: And I was watching till five in the morning.

00:29:55.400 --> 00:30:00.360
[Amit Varma]: It's like you come for the chess, you stay for the people, like in one of those broadcasts.

00:30:00.360 --> 00:30:02.360
[Amit Varma]: And it's really incredible how it panned out.

00:30:02.360 --> 00:30:04.440
[Amit Varma]: You have thousands of people watching.

00:30:04.440 --> 00:30:08.500
[Amit Varma]: And Sagar Shah who lives in Goregaon, by the way, I must get in touch with him one of these

00:30:08.500 --> 00:30:10.520
[Amit Varma]: days to tell him how much I like his work.

00:30:10.520 --> 00:30:15.240
[Amit Varma]: So Sagar, you know, his internet went five minutes before the stream was going to start.

00:30:15.240 --> 00:30:17.040
[Amit Varma]: So he kind of ran to office.

00:30:17.040 --> 00:30:18.280
[Amit Varma]: His office was two minutes away.

00:30:18.280 --> 00:30:22.240
[Amit Varma]: He ran to office holding his laptop and his camera and all his equipment.

00:30:22.240 --> 00:30:25.960
[Amit Varma]: And then when the show is getting over at four, you know, there is this dialogue about

00:30:25.960 --> 00:30:30.880
[Amit Varma]: how is he going to get home because, you know, there are dogs on the lane outside apparently

00:30:30.880 --> 00:30:32.560
[Amit Varma]: and he's scared of them.

00:30:32.560 --> 00:30:35.740
[Amit Varma]: And all his viewers get very worried for him.

00:30:35.740 --> 00:30:39.880
[Amit Varma]: And then at one point he says, okay, I will shut the stream and I will start Instagram

00:30:39.880 --> 00:30:45.560
[Amit Varma]: live and he Instagram live his whole walk from his office to his home.

00:30:45.560 --> 00:30:47.940
[Amit Varma]: And I don't think there were any dogs on the way.

00:30:47.940 --> 00:30:53.800
[Amit Varma]: And this kind of intimate connection which forms between creators and viewers is something

00:30:53.800 --> 00:30:58.800
[Amit Varma]: that obviously it's been there before in various forms and it's kind of been creeping up.

00:30:58.800 --> 00:31:04.960
[Amit Varma]: But it's something that I really noticed a lot of only sort of during this specific year.

00:31:04.960 --> 00:31:09.560
[Amit Varma]: And obviously it's enabled by technology and it's something interesting and very beautiful

00:31:09.560 --> 00:31:14.480
[Amit Varma]: and something that I hadn't kind of thought of earlier that, you know, no longer are you

00:31:14.480 --> 00:31:18.800
[Amit Varma]: broadcasting to many people that even if you are effectively broadcasting to many people

00:31:18.800 --> 00:31:23.360
[Amit Varma]: and you have, you know, thousands watching your stream, you feel that intimate connection

00:31:23.360 --> 00:31:26.280
[Amit Varma]: with the artist and you know, all of that.

00:31:26.280 --> 00:31:31.080
[Amit Varma]: So for me, that was, you know, one of the things that surprised and delighted me.

00:31:31.080 --> 00:31:32.680
[Guest 1]: Yeah, I think you're right, Amit.

00:31:32.680 --> 00:31:40.720
[Guest 1]: And I think the classic case, not that I would know anything about it, but would be OnlyFans,

00:31:40.720 --> 00:31:43.320
[Guest 1]: which is the kind of porn.

00:31:43.320 --> 00:31:45.040
[Guest 1]: What is this?

00:31:45.040 --> 00:31:46.040
[Guest 1]: OnlyFans.

00:31:46.040 --> 00:31:48.960
[Guest 1]: So what is that?

00:31:48.960 --> 00:31:55.640
[Guest 1]: It is a huge exploding, basically soft porn or pornographic streaming.

00:31:55.640 --> 00:31:57.640
[Guest 2]: But it's exactly what Amit is talking about.

00:31:57.640 --> 00:31:58.640
[Guest 2]: It's live.

00:31:58.640 --> 00:31:59.640
[Guest 1]: Yeah.

00:31:59.640 --> 00:32:00.640
[Guest 1]: Yeah.

00:32:00.640 --> 00:32:01.640
[Guest 1]: Live.

00:32:01.640 --> 00:32:02.640
[Guest 1]: Yeah.

00:32:02.640 --> 00:32:03.640
[Guest 1]: Yeah.

00:32:03.640 --> 00:32:04.640
[Guest 1]: Yeah.

00:32:04.640 --> 00:32:05.640
[Guest 1]: Yeah.

00:32:05.640 --> 00:32:06.640
[Guest 1]: But it's exactly what Amit is talking about in that there's a very personal connection.

00:32:06.640 --> 00:32:13.920
[Guest 1]: So a big OnlyFan account might have, you know, a thousand or five thousand subscribers, right?

00:32:13.920 --> 00:32:18.640
[Guest 1]: Which at ten dollars a month, you know, can be a lot of money.

00:32:18.640 --> 00:32:26.680
[Guest 1]: But it has succeeded, as far as I've been told, precisely because it's establishing

00:32:26.680 --> 00:32:28.160
[Guest 1]: this personal connection.

00:32:28.160 --> 00:32:31.600
[Guest 1]: So a lot of it is not actually pornographic.

00:32:31.600 --> 00:32:41.120
[Guest 1]: A lot of it is lonely men speaking with attractive women and having them talk about their lives

00:32:41.120 --> 00:32:45.680
[Guest 1]: and just having these women just, you know, converse.

00:32:45.680 --> 00:32:47.480
[Guest 1]: So a lot of it is conversation.

00:32:47.480 --> 00:32:55.080
[Guest 1]: And I think the question is how much this is due to the pandemic, that there's a lot

00:32:55.080 --> 00:32:56.360
[Guest 1]: of loneliness.

00:32:56.360 --> 00:33:03.080
[Guest 1]: You know, a lot of people are cut off from friends and family and how much will go away.

00:33:03.080 --> 00:33:06.520
[Guest 1]: But how much of these innovations will may also last?

00:33:06.520 --> 00:33:07.520
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

00:33:07.520 --> 00:33:11.720
[Amit Varma]: And this also, you know, in a related sense, speaks to Kevin Kelly's concept of a thousand

00:33:11.720 --> 00:33:15.500
[Amit Varma]: true fans, which he wrote about in an essay like more than a decade ago.

00:33:15.500 --> 00:33:19.400
[Amit Varma]: What is finally happening where you can have a newsletter where you just have a thousand

00:33:19.400 --> 00:33:24.200
[Amit Varma]: people subscribing, but at a hundred dollars a year, that's still, you know, a reasonable

00:33:24.200 --> 00:33:28.000
[Amit Varma]: amount of money, if I might use that euphemism.

00:33:28.000 --> 00:33:30.480
[Amit Varma]: So I find all this, you know, so fascinating.

00:33:30.480 --> 00:33:35.560
[Amit Varma]: It changes the world for creators, but it also, you know, changes the world for fans

00:33:35.560 --> 00:33:36.560
[Guest 2]: in a sense.

00:33:36.560 --> 00:33:41.600
[Guest 2]: You know, I'm almost envious of the people who can like watch chess and discuss it for

00:33:41.600 --> 00:33:43.680
[Guest 2]: six hours and things like that.

00:33:43.680 --> 00:33:48.500
[Guest 2]: Because my first reaction to anything like that is that just sounds exhausting to me.

00:33:48.500 --> 00:33:53.240
[Guest 2]: And that's probably because, you know, in one sense, I'm a different generation technologically,

00:33:53.240 --> 00:33:54.240
[Guest 2]: right?

00:33:54.240 --> 00:33:56.440
[Guest 2]: I'm the generation of the written word.

00:33:56.440 --> 00:33:57.880
[Guest 2]: And even that was really hard to get.

00:33:57.880 --> 00:34:02.460
[Guest 2]: You had to Xerox the written word and then sort of hold on to it and then read whatever

00:34:02.460 --> 00:34:03.460
[Guest 2]: you had to read.

00:34:03.460 --> 00:34:07.480
[Guest 2]: So this idea that you can have like lots and lots of stuff happening at the same time and

00:34:07.480 --> 00:34:12.680
[Guest 2]: you can interact with people and you learn necessarily by talking to people, that was

00:34:12.680 --> 00:34:16.920
[Guest 2]: never an option growing up in India for me trying to read the kinds of things I wanted

00:34:16.920 --> 00:34:17.920
[Guest 2]: to read.

00:34:17.920 --> 00:34:18.920
[Guest 2]: Right.

00:34:18.920 --> 00:34:23.880
[Guest 2]: So the reliance has always been to go by myself and read or something like that.

00:34:23.880 --> 00:34:28.920
[Guest 2]: And we all fall back into our usual patterns when something bad happens.

00:34:28.920 --> 00:34:32.400
[Guest 2]: And the upside to COVID has been, I think I've read the most this year since probably

00:34:32.400 --> 00:34:33.400
[Guest 2]: graduate school.

00:34:33.400 --> 00:34:39.320
[Guest 2]: But on the other hand, I have probably missed every cool social phenomenon of community

00:34:39.320 --> 00:34:43.960
[Guest 2]: viewing and people are watching things at the same time and people are, you know, like

00:34:43.960 --> 00:34:49.360
[Guest 2]: when a show launches or they're playing video games or whatever, board games simultaneously

00:34:49.360 --> 00:34:50.360
[Guest 2]: and things.

00:34:50.360 --> 00:34:57.040
[Guest 2]: And I sound terrible, but I have no interest in any of that and I don't gravitate towards

00:34:57.040 --> 00:34:58.040
[Guest 2]: it.

00:34:58.040 --> 00:35:00.600
[Guest 2]: But at the same time, now that you talk about it, I feel like maybe I'm missing out on something

00:35:00.600 --> 00:35:05.200
[Guest 1]: sitting by myself, having my notes in these books.

00:35:05.200 --> 00:35:11.080
[Guest 1]: There's also a negative aspect to this, which a lot of people have talked about, is that

00:35:11.080 --> 00:35:17.960
[Guest 1]: without broadcasting, the society is becoming much more divided and there's less of a common

00:35:17.960 --> 00:35:20.680
[Guest 1]: consensus about even what the facts are.

00:35:20.680 --> 00:35:28.280
[Guest 1]: As we know, I saw recently a list of the top 10 streamers on YouTube and I did not recognize

00:35:28.280 --> 00:35:35.200
[Guest 1]: a single name, right, and I'm pretty connected, you know, as far as a middle-aged man might

00:35:35.200 --> 00:35:36.200
[Guest 1]: be.

00:35:36.200 --> 00:35:40.560
[Guest 1]: But, you know, it's not like I'd heard the names but just didn't know, you know, hadn't,

00:35:40.560 --> 00:35:42.720
[Guest 1]: you know, bought their album or something like that.

00:35:42.720 --> 00:35:45.320
[Guest 1]: I did not recognize a single name.

00:35:45.320 --> 00:35:49.880
[Guest 1]: And these were all people with, you know, 10 million subscribers or something like that,

00:35:49.880 --> 00:35:52.500
[Guest 1]: you know, or lots of subscribers.

00:35:52.500 --> 00:35:57.480
[Guest 1]: And so we are becoming, you know, you can now find your own facts, right?

00:35:57.480 --> 00:36:02.880
[Guest 1]: It's very easy to go out into the world and no matter how crazy your view is, you can

00:36:02.880 --> 00:36:06.920
[Guest 1]: find lots of people who are supporting and encouraging you.

00:36:06.920 --> 00:36:12.880
[Guest 1]: And one thing which, very surprisingly, has been found in the behavioral economics literature,

00:36:12.880 --> 00:36:19.080
[Guest 1]: right, is that when you get a bunch of people, let's call them crazy people, they're not

00:36:19.080 --> 00:36:24.920
[Guest 1]: necessarily good, but you get a bunch of people together, okay, they become even crazier,

00:36:24.920 --> 00:36:25.920
[Guest 1]: right?

00:36:25.920 --> 00:36:28.800
[Guest 1]: Everybody sort of wants to be in the middle, as it were.

00:36:28.800 --> 00:36:34.840
[Guest 1]: And so you get these people together, they hear, oh, maybe my view is not as crazy as

00:36:34.840 --> 00:36:39.680
[Guest 1]: I thought, therefore I should move even further, you know, they all support one another.

00:36:39.680 --> 00:36:45.360
[Guest 1]: And so you get these communities, you know, the anti-vaxxers are one community, you know,

00:36:45.360 --> 00:36:51.040
[Guest 1]: the election was stolen is another community, the UFO people, that's a community.

00:36:51.040 --> 00:36:58.560
[Guest 1]: It doesn't matter how crazy your view is, you can find a group out there who will, you

00:36:58.560 --> 00:37:03.880
[Guest 1]: know, send you reports or emails and send you Facebook, look at this, how do you explain,

00:37:03.880 --> 00:37:10.280
[Guest 1]: you know, how the towers on 9-11, you know, why did they fall and steel is supposed to,

00:37:10.280 --> 00:37:14.800
[Guest 1]: you know, it's not supposed to melt and, you know, there must have been an inside job.

00:37:14.800 --> 00:37:17.120
[Guest 2]: Any kind of crazy view can be supported now.

00:37:17.120 --> 00:37:21.880
[Guest 2]: And they all think they are Copernicus, right, that they are the first people to discover

00:37:21.880 --> 00:37:22.880
[Guest 2]: this.

00:37:22.880 --> 00:37:26.800
[Guest 2]: And we are the establishment who just doesn't believe anything.

00:37:26.800 --> 00:37:30.440
[Amit Varma]: Everyone on Twitter is an expert in whatever hashtag is trending that day.

00:37:30.440 --> 00:37:34.800
[Amit Varma]: And I'll actually, you know, because Alex sort of almost segued into one of my other

00:37:34.800 --> 00:37:36.400
[Amit Varma]: lessons, let's invert the order.

00:37:36.400 --> 00:37:39.680
[Amit Varma]: So I'll go with my second lesson now, and then we'll just invert it.

00:37:39.680 --> 00:37:42.680
[Amit Varma]: So the narrative flow seems smooth to the listener.

00:37:42.680 --> 00:37:47.360
[Amit Varma]: And my second lesson is about narratives, which is that one of the things that you know,

00:37:47.360 --> 00:37:52.760
[Amit Varma]: we knew it before, but I think this year has helped make it even more stark is that reality

00:37:52.760 --> 00:37:53.960
[Amit Varma]: doesn't really matter.

00:37:53.960 --> 00:37:57.000
[Amit Varma]: You know, narratives are everything.

00:37:57.000 --> 00:37:59.680
[Amit Varma]: And there are all kinds of crazy narratives out there.

00:37:59.680 --> 00:38:06.520
[Amit Varma]: And much as you know, we lived in a less connected, less democratic in the sense of ease of entry,

00:38:06.520 --> 00:38:10.240
[Amit Varma]: you know, with the means of production not available to everyone in the 80s and 90s.

00:38:10.240 --> 00:38:14.720
[Amit Varma]: At least what we had when I was growing up where you had a handful of mainstream publications

00:38:14.720 --> 00:38:17.720
[Amit Varma]: was you had a broad consensus on the truth.

00:38:17.720 --> 00:38:22.240
[Amit Varma]: One you no longer have that because everyone is producing their own stuff, which is great.

00:38:22.240 --> 00:38:30.920
[Amit Varma]: But do what it then does is it leads to everybody living in a web of shared interconnected realities.

00:38:30.920 --> 00:38:34.800
[Amit Varma]: And we've seen some crazy stories this year is like, of course, there are all these stories

00:38:34.800 --> 00:38:39.080
[Amit Varma]: about how vaccines are a Bill Gate plot for surveillance and all of that.

00:38:39.080 --> 00:38:43.320
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, when SSR died, Sushant Singh Rajput, by the way, Alex was an Indian film

00:38:43.320 --> 00:38:47.040
[Amit Varma]: star who tragically took his own life earlier this year.

00:38:47.040 --> 00:38:50.760
[Amit Varma]: And that should have opened up a healthy dialogue on mental health and all of that.

00:38:50.760 --> 00:38:55.800
[Amit Varma]: But instead, what it did was it led to this bunch of crazy conspiracy theories, not only

00:38:55.800 --> 00:39:00.260
[Amit Varma]: about his alleged murder by some politicians, but there were people who said that he created

00:39:00.260 --> 00:39:01.760
[Amit Varma]: the vaccine for COVID.

00:39:01.760 --> 00:39:05.440
[Amit Varma]: And because politicians wanted COVID to continue, they bumped him off.

00:39:05.440 --> 00:39:09.320
[Amit Varma]: There was another theory on Twitter floating about that said that he created this video

00:39:09.320 --> 00:39:13.600
[Amit Varma]: game called Foggy, which had just been launched by the star called Akshay Kumar.

00:39:13.600 --> 00:39:15.440
[Amit Varma]: So Akshay Kumar had him bumped off.

00:39:15.440 --> 00:39:19.160
[Amit Varma]: So all these crazy theories were kind of floating around.

00:39:19.160 --> 00:39:23.840
[Amit Varma]: And which also kind of leads to a related question that, listen, I know we need narratives

00:39:23.840 --> 00:39:24.840
[Amit Varma]: to explain the world.

00:39:24.840 --> 00:39:29.440
[Amit Varma]: The world is complex and really impossible to make sense of in its entirety.

00:39:29.440 --> 00:39:32.160
[Amit Varma]: So we need these simple narratives to make sense of the world.

00:39:32.160 --> 00:39:37.880
[Amit Varma]: But people increasingly seem drawn towards these really outlandish narratives, which,

00:39:37.880 --> 00:39:42.520
[Amit Varma]: you know, and that attraction is something that I'm not sure I understand.

00:39:42.520 --> 00:39:48.400
[Amit Varma]: And the other thing that I kind of, you know, that we, I think all of us know, but often

00:39:48.400 --> 00:39:54.080
[Amit Varma]: it is just better to be in denial of it, is that we all live in our own constructed worlds.

00:39:54.080 --> 00:39:59.240
[Amit Varma]: In a sense, everyone is a character in someone else's imaginary universe.

00:39:59.240 --> 00:40:04.720
[Guest 2]: And that can be a very scary and lonely thought, you know, honestly, like this whole Sushant

00:40:04.720 --> 00:40:09.040
[Guest 2]: Singh Rajput thing and the other things, I think it's like, you know, people who gather

00:40:09.040 --> 00:40:13.400
[Guest 2]: around an accident that happens, you know, somewhere on a road in India.

00:40:13.400 --> 00:40:14.400
[Guest 2]: No one helps.

00:40:14.400 --> 00:40:15.400
[Guest 2]: They're just watching.

00:40:15.400 --> 00:40:19.200
[Guest 2]: It's like a way to pass 10 minutes of the traffic jam and then they move on.

00:40:19.200 --> 00:40:21.160
[Guest 2]: I think a lot of it is that, right?

00:40:21.160 --> 00:40:25.440
[Guest 2]: I don't think people are seriously making decisions in their life based on this.

00:40:25.440 --> 00:40:29.960
[Guest 2]: It's about as much as I am making decisions in my life, watching Tony Soprano.

00:40:29.960 --> 00:40:34.800
[Guest 2]: You know, there is something very fascinating about watching like a mob movie or, you know,

00:40:34.800 --> 00:40:39.440
[Guest 2]: Martin Scorsese and blow is flying all over the place and goodfellas, but that doesn't

00:40:39.440 --> 00:40:42.120
[Guest 2]: mean I'm doing anything stronger than caffeine.

00:40:42.120 --> 00:40:44.840
[Guest 2]: So I think there is something fascinating about it.

00:40:44.840 --> 00:40:51.080
[Guest 2]: I think what's happening with the internet is more your earlier point, which is broadcasting

00:40:51.080 --> 00:40:52.880
[Guest 2]: has become intimate, right?

00:40:52.880 --> 00:40:57.880
[Guest 2]: TV news channels with their graphics and their access to, you know, you literally in Sushant

00:40:57.880 --> 00:41:00.280
[Guest 2]: Singh Rajput's bedroom and his balcony.

00:41:00.280 --> 00:41:04.440
[Guest 2]: So now you feel like you're watching something and you're very intimately involved in it

00:41:04.440 --> 00:41:08.120
[Guest 2]: in a way that earlier maybe you would have read about it in a newspaper, thought about

00:41:08.120 --> 00:41:10.200
[Guest 2]: it for a couple of minutes and moved on.

00:41:10.200 --> 00:41:14.040
[Guest 2]: So I don't think it is that people are changing in any particular way.

00:41:14.040 --> 00:41:18.840
[Guest 2]: I think it's just now they're consuming real life events like entertainment, right?

00:41:18.840 --> 00:41:24.040
[Guest 2]: I knew people who had the popcorn ready when the Trump Biden debate was going on.

00:41:24.040 --> 00:41:26.200
[Guest 2]: Nobody took it as a presidential debate.

00:41:26.200 --> 00:41:31.880
[Guest 2]: The first thing I learned about the debate, because I didn't watch it, is the fly on Mike

00:41:31.880 --> 00:41:34.480
[Guest 2]: Pence's hair, right?

00:41:34.480 --> 00:41:36.280
[Guest 2]: Because this whole thing is nuts.

00:41:36.280 --> 00:41:37.280
[Guest 2]: Nobody's listening.

00:41:37.280 --> 00:41:40.640
[Guest 2]: They catch up on what happened in the debate on SNL, right?

00:41:40.640 --> 00:41:42.280
[Guest 2]: That's people's source of information.

00:41:42.280 --> 00:41:46.720
[Guest 2]: It's Colbert and SNL and Trevor Noah and things like that.

00:41:46.720 --> 00:41:48.800
[Guest 2]: So I think we're taking it too seriously.

00:41:48.800 --> 00:41:52.240
[Guest 2]: I don't think people really live their regular lives like that.

00:41:52.240 --> 00:41:58.080
[Guest 2]: They have just converted information, facts, science and broadcasting into entertainment.

00:41:58.080 --> 00:42:00.800
[Guest 2]: And we're all part of it, right?

00:42:00.800 --> 00:42:05.720
[Guest 2]: In one sense, like Alex does MRU videos, which are perfect on economics, but they're entertaining.

00:42:05.720 --> 00:42:06.720
[Guest 2]: They have jokes.

00:42:06.720 --> 00:42:07.720
[Guest 2]: They have graphics.

00:42:07.720 --> 00:42:11.840
[Guest 2]: We're all trying to turn the content we put out there as entertainment.

00:42:11.840 --> 00:42:17.560
[Guest 2]: And now we can't blame people, you know, in one sense for thinking of this as entertainment

00:42:17.560 --> 00:42:20.600
[Guest 2]: and getting carried away by it and then just moving on with their life.

00:42:20.600 --> 00:42:26.960
[Guest 2]: And in the process, maybe inadvertently support some kind of crazy TV news channel or conspiracy

00:42:26.960 --> 00:42:29.480
[Guest 2]: theory or Internet meme or something like that.

00:42:29.480 --> 00:42:30.600
[Guest 2]: But I wouldn't take it too seriously.

00:42:30.600 --> 00:42:33.180
[Guest 2]: I think regular folks have been exactly the same.

00:42:33.180 --> 00:42:37.180
[Guest 2]: They have always been in 2020 as they were in any other year.

00:42:37.180 --> 00:42:39.680
[Guest 2]: You know, when you talk to them like in the real world.

00:42:39.680 --> 00:42:41.960
[Guest 1]: I hope you're right, Trudy, but I don't know.

00:42:41.960 --> 00:42:43.600
[Guest 1]: Here's something which I worry about.

00:42:43.600 --> 00:42:50.160
[Guest 1]: I think about, you know, like, why was Hitler, you know, so successful?

00:42:50.160 --> 00:42:55.040
[Guest 1]: And when you look at Hitler today, you know, news footage or something like that, he just

00:42:55.040 --> 00:43:03.640
[Guest 1]: looks comic, you know, he just looks foolish and kind of like, how could people take this

00:43:03.640 --> 00:43:04.640
[Guest 1]: guy seriously?

00:43:04.640 --> 00:43:08.040
[Guest 1]: He was supposed to be, you know, this great orator and he looks kind of silly.

00:43:08.040 --> 00:43:14.360
[Guest 1]: And I think, you know, my theory is that a lot of what happened was we got radio and

00:43:14.360 --> 00:43:19.920
[Guest 1]: television and cinema all at the same kind of time or all very close together.

00:43:19.920 --> 00:43:21.760
[Guest 1]: And our brains could not handle it.

00:43:21.760 --> 00:43:27.720
[Guest 1]: OK, so we literally thought that these people were sort of gods, because, you know, even

00:43:27.720 --> 00:43:32.720
[Guest 1]: though you understand when you see, you know, an actor on the movie screen that they're

00:43:32.720 --> 00:43:37.440
[Guest 1]: not really 100 foot tall, your brain just thinks, oh, this is a god.

00:43:37.440 --> 00:43:39.880
[Guest 1]: They're 100 foot tall, right?

00:43:39.880 --> 00:43:46.800
[Guest 1]: And so I think these dictators were in part a response to this new media.

00:43:46.800 --> 00:43:49.360
[Guest 1]: And the new media just broke people's brains.

00:43:49.360 --> 00:43:58.380
[Guest 1]: And eventually we kind of got used to it and learned, I hope, I think, to clamp down on

00:43:58.380 --> 00:44:02.920
[Guest 1]: some of these feelings and to take things with a bit more grain of salt and you get

00:44:02.920 --> 00:44:07.400
[Guest 1]: used to them and you've seen it, you know, a hundred or a thousand times, and maybe then

00:44:07.400 --> 00:44:11.720
[Guest 1]: you begin to see, oh, this is not a god, you know, you get used to it.

00:44:11.720 --> 00:44:19.340
[Guest 1]: But I think the Internet and social media are a new media challenge that is breaking

00:44:19.340 --> 00:44:21.280
[Guest 1]: our brains.

00:44:21.280 --> 00:44:30.720
[Guest 1]: And the difficulty now is can we get through this period for a long enough time to be vaccinated,

00:44:30.720 --> 00:44:31.720
[Guest 1]: right?

00:44:31.720 --> 00:44:34.680
[Guest 1]: To be vaccinated against the new social media, right?

00:44:34.680 --> 00:44:41.360
[Guest 1]: We need time for our brains to become inured to this intimacy, right?

00:44:41.360 --> 00:44:45.240
[Guest 1]: This industry that Ahmed was talking about, oh, Donald Trump is my friend.

00:44:45.240 --> 00:44:47.560
[Guest 1]: You know, he speaks to me, right?

00:44:47.560 --> 00:44:53.760
[Guest 1]: I mean, I see, you know, and his family, you know, Ivanka and, you know, whatever the other

00:44:53.760 --> 00:44:57.560
[Guest 1]: ones are called, you know, they're part of my family or whatever.

00:44:57.560 --> 00:45:01.640
[Guest 1]: And we just need time to become inured to it.

00:45:01.640 --> 00:45:07.720
[Guest 1]: And maybe the new generation, like, I think my kids are a little bit more, you know, this

00:45:07.720 --> 00:45:14.520
[Guest 1]: is like Batman, you know, they grew up in the darkness, you know, right?

00:45:14.520 --> 00:45:15.520
[Guest 1]: But I don't know.

00:45:15.520 --> 00:45:16.520
[Guest 1]: I'm not sure.

00:45:16.520 --> 00:45:21.880
[Guest 1]: And I think I like really worry, for example, about China, right?

00:45:21.880 --> 00:45:28.200
[Guest 1]: Like the Communist Party in China is very, very bad, but what would a populist politician

00:45:28.200 --> 00:45:29.480
[Guest 1]: look like?

00:45:29.480 --> 00:45:34.120
[Guest 1]: And would a populist, you know, launch a war against Taiwan or something like that?

00:45:34.120 --> 00:45:35.120
[Guest 2]: Or India.

00:45:35.120 --> 00:45:37.360
[Guest 1]: Or India, of course, exactly.

00:45:37.360 --> 00:45:44.320
[Guest 1]: So just the way social media breaks our brains and can we live for long enough to become

00:45:44.320 --> 00:45:45.320
[Guest 1]: inured to it?

00:45:45.320 --> 00:45:51.880
[Guest 1]: I think that's a question, especially as it's getting the new media are hitting us faster

00:45:51.880 --> 00:45:53.520
[Guest 1]: and faster and faster.

00:45:53.520 --> 00:46:00.200
[Guest 1]: So we already are challenged by social media and, you know, virtual reality is just around

00:46:00.200 --> 00:46:01.200
[Guest 1]: the corner.

00:46:01.200 --> 00:46:02.200
[Amit Varma]: Wow.

00:46:02.200 --> 00:46:04.560
[Amit Varma]: And here I was thinking that we need a vaccine against COVID.

00:46:04.560 --> 00:46:09.280
[Amit Varma]: But even after that comes, we need a vaccine against social media who can inoculate us

00:46:09.280 --> 00:46:10.280
[Amit Varma]: from Twitter.

00:46:10.280 --> 00:46:17.200
[Amit Varma]: So, Shruti, since we inverted the order, it is now your turn to share your second lesson

00:46:17.200 --> 00:46:18.200
[Amit Varma]: with us.

00:46:18.200 --> 00:46:19.200
[Guest 2]: Yeah.

00:46:19.200 --> 00:46:25.120
[Guest 2]: You know, I've been thinking a lot about intergenerational tradeoffs right now.

00:46:25.120 --> 00:46:30.040
[Guest 2]: As an economist, I would typically think about this in the context of public debt, right?

00:46:30.040 --> 00:46:35.840
[Guest 2]: This is the classic example that governments tend to overspend because they know not only

00:46:35.840 --> 00:46:41.400
[Guest 2]: is it they're able to spread the cause differently from the people who benefit in the present,

00:46:41.400 --> 00:46:42.400
[Guest 2]: but also inter-temporally.

00:46:42.400 --> 00:46:43.400
[Guest 2]: Right.

00:46:43.400 --> 00:46:48.880
[Guest 2]: So all the older people today are going to get their, you know, big welfare checks and

00:46:48.880 --> 00:46:49.880
[Guest 2]: things like that.

00:46:49.880 --> 00:46:54.120
[Guest 2]: But we're actually borrowing from the future and the future happens to be in kindergarten

00:46:54.120 --> 00:46:55.120
[Guest 2]: right now.

00:46:55.120 --> 00:46:56.120
[Guest 2]: Right.

00:46:56.120 --> 00:46:57.360
[Guest 2]: But the future cannot vote.

00:46:57.360 --> 00:47:02.400
[Guest 2]: And therefore, you know, it's pretty easy to pass on this this huge debt burden to them.

00:47:02.400 --> 00:47:05.840
[Guest 2]: And this is, you know, I mean, this is a very classic George Mason thing.

00:47:05.840 --> 00:47:11.320
[Guest 2]: I mean, James Buchanan, Dick Wagner, they've done the pioneering work on debt deficits

00:47:11.320 --> 00:47:13.240
[Guest 2]: and democratic politics in one sense.

00:47:13.240 --> 00:47:14.240
[Guest 2]: Right.

00:47:14.240 --> 00:47:17.460
[Guest 2]: How this intergenerational tradeoff works and really all the standard constraints one

00:47:17.460 --> 00:47:21.440
[Guest 2]: would imagine in democratic politics disappear once debt is in the picture.

00:47:21.440 --> 00:47:26.240
[Guest 2]: And I've been thinking about that in the context of COVID because this pandemic is a little

00:47:26.240 --> 00:47:27.240
[Guest 2]: bit like debt.

00:47:27.240 --> 00:47:28.240
[Guest 2]: Right.

00:47:28.240 --> 00:47:33.720
[Guest 2]: It is a big cost and, you know, high fatality rates and things like that with a generation

00:47:33.720 --> 00:47:35.480
[Guest 2]: above 65 years.

00:47:35.480 --> 00:47:36.480
[Guest 2]: Right.

00:47:36.480 --> 00:47:40.880
[Guest 2]: And almost all the costs are being imposed to benefit this group.

00:47:40.880 --> 00:47:45.240
[Guest 2]: I mean, when I say this group, just please note that I'm saying that academically.

00:47:45.240 --> 00:47:46.240
[Guest 2]: Right.

00:47:46.240 --> 00:47:48.280
[Guest 2]: This group is my parents and my grandparents and things.

00:47:48.280 --> 00:47:50.000
[Guest 2]: So, you know, it's not like random people.

00:47:50.000 --> 00:47:51.320
[Guest 2]: And I understand that.

00:47:51.320 --> 00:47:57.440
[Guest 2]: But it is still a different group which benefits from all the major lockdowns and, you know,

00:47:57.440 --> 00:48:02.640
[Guest 2]: like socialist policies, the FDA policies, and maybe not all of them, but, you know,

00:48:02.640 --> 00:48:05.680
[Guest 2]: the vaccine distribution plan that's coming in place and things like that.

00:48:05.680 --> 00:48:11.080
[Guest 2]: And the group that's in one sense, the unseen group which is suffering the most is the kids

00:48:11.080 --> 00:48:12.440
[Guest 2]: because of school closures.

00:48:12.440 --> 00:48:13.440
[Guest 2]: Right.

00:48:13.440 --> 00:48:16.200
[Guest 2]: Especially really young kids from poorer backgrounds.

00:48:16.200 --> 00:48:17.200
[Guest 2]: Right.

00:48:17.200 --> 00:48:22.720
[Guest 2]: A year lost in their life is going to have very big consequences for their mental development

00:48:22.720 --> 00:48:25.120
[Guest 2]: and their, you know, education developments.

00:48:25.120 --> 00:48:29.720
[Guest 2]: There is good research out there that even one year of education lost has, you know,

00:48:29.720 --> 00:48:34.920
[Guest 2]: reasonable impact, a significant impact on lifetime earnings and things like that and

00:48:34.920 --> 00:48:36.880
[Guest 2]: building of human capital.

00:48:36.880 --> 00:48:41.400
[Guest 2]: And even though over and over again, it's been shown that children are not at risk at

00:48:41.400 --> 00:48:46.040
[Guest 2]: all or, you know, at such low risk that it could be the flu or, you know, any one of

00:48:46.040 --> 00:48:47.040
[Guest 2]: the other things.

00:48:47.040 --> 00:48:50.600
[Guest 2]: I mean, they're at higher risk from air pollution in Delhi than from COVID, you know, in those

00:48:50.600 --> 00:48:56.160
[Guest 2]: particular age groups, in one sense, that we really should have made effort as a society

00:48:56.160 --> 00:49:01.480
[Guest 2]: to keep, you know, schools open and maybe find another way to mitigate the costs on

00:49:01.480 --> 00:49:02.480
[Guest 2]: the older generation.

00:49:02.480 --> 00:49:06.560
[Guest 2]: But once again, all the incentives are stacked against that because these kids don't vote

00:49:06.560 --> 00:49:07.880
[Guest 2]: for a very long time.

00:49:07.880 --> 00:49:08.880
[Guest 2]: Right.

00:49:08.880 --> 00:49:14.120
[Guest 2]: So one lesson for me, and I'm only being partly facetious because I'm laughing, but I do want

00:49:14.120 --> 00:49:19.600
[Guest 2]: to think about this seriously, I mean, I think I would seriously consider reducing the voting

00:49:19.600 --> 00:49:24.240
[Guest 2]: age, right, to maybe like 14 or something like that.

00:49:24.240 --> 00:49:28.200
[Guest 2]: Like, I think the voting age right now is too high.

00:49:28.200 --> 00:49:32.360
[Guest 2]: And even if it's 18, people don't start voting at 18, they're in college, they just got,

00:49:32.360 --> 00:49:36.120
[Guest 2]: you know, a privilege of driving and drinking and things like that, or, you know, being

00:49:36.120 --> 00:49:38.560
[Guest 2]: able to buy a chainsaw if you live in the United States.

00:49:38.560 --> 00:49:39.560
[Guest 2]: Right.

00:49:39.560 --> 00:49:43.500
[Guest 2]: So now we really want to think about getting them started younger.

00:49:43.500 --> 00:49:45.920
[Guest 2]: Maybe they will think more about democratic politics.

00:49:45.920 --> 00:49:48.400
[Guest 2]: Maybe they need an interest group backing them.

00:49:48.400 --> 00:49:54.280
[Guest 2]: We are really missing a very big lobby that has student interests in mind.

00:49:54.280 --> 00:49:55.280
[Guest 2]: Right.

00:49:55.280 --> 00:49:58.400
[Guest 2]: So there are lobbies that pretend to have student interests in mind, like schoolteachers,

00:49:58.400 --> 00:49:59.400
[Guest 2]: but they really don't.

00:49:59.400 --> 00:50:00.400
[Guest 2]: They're their own lobby.

00:50:00.400 --> 00:50:04.640
[Guest 2]: In fact, all the COVID closures are to protect the teachers, not the students.

00:50:04.640 --> 00:50:05.640
[Guest 2]: Right.

00:50:05.640 --> 00:50:08.440
[Guest 2]: Because the teachers who are of a certain age and might get infected.

00:50:08.440 --> 00:50:13.520
[Guest 2]: So as outrageous as this sounds, I don't see adults making amazing decisions.

00:50:13.520 --> 00:50:16.260
[Guest 2]: So I don't think age has anything to do with it.

00:50:16.260 --> 00:50:21.600
[Guest 2]: But I do think, you know, there's some merit in maybe a start voting younger because some

00:50:21.600 --> 00:50:27.840
[Guest 2]: of these intergenerational trade-offs might become a little less skewed, you know, against

00:50:27.840 --> 00:50:30.720
[Guest 2]: the future, against the children, as it may.

00:50:30.720 --> 00:50:35.960
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, the idea of lowering the voting age is so counterintuitive that, you know, one

00:50:35.960 --> 00:50:37.560
[Amit Varma]: reflexively thinks, what the hell?

00:50:37.560 --> 00:50:38.960
[Amit Varma]: So I'm going to.

00:50:38.960 --> 00:50:43.440
[Amit Varma]: So whenever I hear counterintuitive ideas, I'm kind of don't react to it immediately,

00:50:43.440 --> 00:50:44.720
[Amit Varma]: take some time to process it.

00:50:44.720 --> 00:50:48.720
[Amit Varma]: Though it does strike me that one, you are, of course, absolutely right, that adults make

00:50:48.720 --> 00:50:49.720
[Amit Varma]: the worst decisions.

00:50:49.720 --> 00:50:54.080
[Amit Varma]: And, and it's not like adults are particularly mature, you know, when you are a young person,

00:50:54.080 --> 00:50:57.360
[Amit Varma]: you think that, oh, people in their forties have everything figured out.

00:50:57.360 --> 00:51:01.840
[Amit Varma]: And then you reach your forties and you realize that everyone is winging it, including you.

00:51:01.840 --> 00:51:06.880
[Amit Varma]: But my other question there would be that 14 year olds wouldn't necessarily be an interest

00:51:06.880 --> 00:51:12.760
[Amit Varma]: group for their own interests as regards their future selves, because, you know, it might

00:51:12.760 --> 00:51:17.640
[Amit Varma]: be a bit much for them to, to expect them also to think about future trade-offs and

00:51:17.640 --> 00:51:18.640
[Amit Varma]: all of that.

00:51:18.640 --> 00:51:22.960
[Amit Varma]: The intuitive solutions that, oh, social security is good, it will take care of all of us, just

00:51:22.960 --> 00:51:27.840
[Amit Varma]: like my parents are doing now, is probably more attractive.

00:51:27.840 --> 00:51:31.680
[Amit Varma]: But then, I mean, I realized that, as I say this, I'm in danger of condescending to 14

00:51:31.680 --> 00:51:32.680
[Amit Varma]: year olds.

00:51:32.680 --> 00:51:37.080
[Amit Varma]: And perhaps the world would be a better place if 14 year olds instead of 60 year olds ran

00:51:37.080 --> 00:51:38.080
[Amit Varma]: it.

00:51:38.080 --> 00:51:39.080
[Amit Varma]: But yeah, that's my instinctive.

00:51:39.080 --> 00:51:42.900
[Guest 2]: You know, 14 year old kids can run a paper route, right?

00:51:42.900 --> 00:51:46.440
[Amit Varma]: So I mean, if that is still a thing, it's not a thing anymore.

00:51:46.440 --> 00:51:48.400
[Guest 2]: But let me give you a different example.

00:51:48.400 --> 00:51:51.200
[Guest 2]: They can shovel snow, it's snow season here.

00:51:51.200 --> 00:51:53.000
[Guest 2]: They can walk my dogs, right?

00:51:53.000 --> 00:51:55.320
[Guest 2]: My dogs are the most important things in my life.

00:51:55.320 --> 00:51:57.960
[Guest 2]: And I trust them with 16 year old kids, right?

00:51:57.960 --> 00:51:59.480
[Guest 2]: And they're very responsible.

00:51:59.480 --> 00:52:04.280
[Guest 2]: So in one sense, just like adults, I think even with kids, and I don't have any, so maybe

00:52:04.280 --> 00:52:07.600
[Guest 2]: I'm a little overly optimistic about this.

00:52:07.600 --> 00:52:10.520
[Guest 2]: Chris has raised teenagers already, so he can tell us more.

00:52:10.520 --> 00:52:14.640
[Guest 2]: But my sense is when people need to be informed about something, they get informed about it,

00:52:14.640 --> 00:52:15.640
[Guest 2]: right?

00:52:15.640 --> 00:52:19.120
[Guest 2]: Right now, we have no guarantee that adults are informed about these policies either.

00:52:19.120 --> 00:52:23.880
[Guest 2]: My hunch is not that the moment they get the right to vote earlier, they will immediately

00:52:23.880 --> 00:52:25.600
[Guest 2]: inform themselves.

00:52:25.600 --> 00:52:28.480
[Guest 2]: But I do think lobbies will get created.

00:52:28.480 --> 00:52:31.840
[Guest 2]: Interest groups will get created that will cater to that group, right?

00:52:31.840 --> 00:52:38.000
[Guest 2]: Above 50, above 60 age group, there might be something like AARP for kids, you know,

00:52:38.000 --> 00:52:42.080
[Guest 2]: that actually sends them brochures that they don't need and informs them about things and

00:52:42.080 --> 00:52:46.040
[Guest 2]: tells them how to vote and gives them some discounts in Teen Vogue or something.

00:52:46.040 --> 00:52:47.040
[Guest 2]: I don't know.

00:52:47.040 --> 00:52:49.080
[Guest 1]: Here's a way of generalizing a little bit.

00:52:49.080 --> 00:52:57.400
[Guest 1]: I mean, I think it's true that the space of institutions, including democratic institutions

00:52:57.400 --> 00:53:02.120
[Guest 1]: that we know, is a very small part of the potential space.

00:53:02.120 --> 00:53:07.400
[Guest 1]: And we ought to have more experimentation in governance systems.

00:53:07.400 --> 00:53:13.920
[Guest 1]: And like to generalize what Trudy said, how about we have a distribution of votes such

00:53:13.920 --> 00:53:18.920
[Guest 1]: that 18-year-olds get, you know, five votes and it decreases over time.

00:53:18.920 --> 00:53:23.520
[Guest 1]: So every decade, you get, you know, one fewer vote, you know, so 60-year-olds only get one

00:53:23.520 --> 00:53:24.840
[Guest 1]: vote, right?

00:53:24.840 --> 00:53:29.600
[Guest 1]: And when you immediately hear this, Amit, as you said, well, this is totally crazy.

00:53:29.600 --> 00:53:33.680
[Guest 1]: But if you think about it a little bit, I mean, it makes a lot of sense in that young

00:53:33.680 --> 00:53:39.520
[Guest 1]: people, they're the most affected by any decisions because they're going to live the longest,

00:53:39.520 --> 00:53:40.520
[Guest 1]: right?

00:53:40.520 --> 00:53:44.000
[Guest 1]: So they have the most incentive to think long-term.

00:53:44.000 --> 00:53:48.480
[Guest 1]: Maybe you're right that they don't have the ability, but maybe 18-year-olds or 20-year-olds.

00:53:48.480 --> 00:53:50.800
[Guest 1]: But they have the most incentive to think long-term.

00:53:50.800 --> 00:53:55.240
[Guest 1]: On the other hand, you know, the 70- or 80-year-olds, even the really lucky ones, they're not going

00:53:55.240 --> 00:53:57.880
[Guest 1]: to be around for that much longer.

00:53:57.880 --> 00:54:02.200
[Guest 1]: Now maybe the counter-argument is that they have the wisdom, you know, or they think about

00:54:02.200 --> 00:54:05.080
[Guest 1]: their kids more and, you know, and so forth.

00:54:05.080 --> 00:54:08.580
[Guest 1]: So I don't know which one of these arguments is correct.

00:54:08.580 --> 00:54:15.300
[Guest 1]: But it's interesting to me that what seems like a very radical position that votes should

00:54:15.300 --> 00:54:20.360
[Guest 1]: be weighted according to age with people who are younger getting a greater weight, it seems

00:54:20.360 --> 00:54:25.920
[Guest 1]: like very, very different from anything we've ever done, and yet perfectly sensible.

00:54:25.920 --> 00:54:28.320
[Guest 1]: I mean, there's nothing obviously wrong with it.

00:54:28.320 --> 00:54:32.760
[Guest 1]: And I think if we had that system, suppose for random reasons that we had started with

00:54:32.760 --> 00:54:38.420
[Guest 1]: that system, if then you were to argue, no, no, no, no, everyone should just get one vote

00:54:38.420 --> 00:54:41.560
[Guest 1]: and that's it, people would say, are you crazy?

00:54:41.560 --> 00:54:42.560
[Guest 1]: That's a stupid system.

00:54:42.560 --> 00:54:47.040
[Guest 1]: Why would you give everybody just one vote?

00:54:47.040 --> 00:54:51.480
[Guest 1]: So it seems like there's a lot of room for different types of governance systems.

00:54:51.480 --> 00:54:56.560
[Guest 1]: We're seeing this a little bit in blockchain, new ways of governing systems.

00:54:56.560 --> 00:55:02.600
[Guest 1]: But more generally, I would like to see a lot more experimentation in collective governance.

00:55:02.600 --> 00:55:06.760
[Guest 1]: Buchanan and Talek started some of this, but we don't see very much of it.

00:55:06.760 --> 00:55:13.800
[Guest 1]: You know, we developed our democratic institutions in, you know, late 1700s, 1800s, and haven't

00:55:13.800 --> 00:55:15.360
[Guest 1]: really changed them since then.

00:55:15.360 --> 00:55:19.320
[Guest 2]: But you know, just in the vein of this whole experimentation thing.

00:55:19.320 --> 00:55:21.520
[Guest 2]: So I started with a really radical position.

00:55:21.520 --> 00:55:25.200
[Guest 2]: Now, let me give you a maybe more palatable version of that.

00:55:25.200 --> 00:55:30.320
[Guest 2]: I don't think it is that outrageous to have kids involved in, say, referendum questions,

00:55:30.320 --> 00:55:36.400
[Guest 2]: right, that involve schools or, you know, legalizing marijuana or, you know, legalizing,

00:55:36.400 --> 00:55:39.480
[Guest 2]: you know, whatever is the driving or drinking age and things like that.

00:55:39.480 --> 00:55:43.200
[Guest 2]: I think they have the most skin in the game and they should have a seat at the table,

00:55:43.200 --> 00:55:44.880
[Guest 2]: weighted or otherwise, right?

00:55:44.880 --> 00:55:51.080
[Guest 2]: I think it would be a great idea to experiment and have children in India vote in the panchayati

00:55:51.080 --> 00:55:54.000
[Guest 2]: raj elections, for instance, right?

00:55:54.000 --> 00:55:59.200
[Guest 2]: Because that is where you're really thinking about long run public goods building the infrastructure,

00:55:59.200 --> 00:56:00.200
[Guest 2]: right?

00:56:00.200 --> 00:56:03.680
[Guest 2]: You know, they are the people who run the local schools, right?

00:56:03.680 --> 00:56:08.680
[Guest 2]: And that might be a good way to break the stronghold of the teachers union who are paid

00:56:08.680 --> 00:56:10.640
[Guest 2]: by the government and propped up by the government.

00:56:10.640 --> 00:56:15.760
[Guest 2]: And maybe, you know, we can get 14 year old kids to start voting in panchayati raj elections

00:56:15.760 --> 00:56:18.080
[Guest 2]: or on specific referendum questions.

00:56:18.080 --> 00:56:23.000
[Guest 2]: So I think that's, you know, maybe a little better than like, you know, overall stepping

00:56:23.000 --> 00:56:27.720
[Guest 2]: away from one individual, one vote systems that we have and maybe experiment on particular

00:56:27.720 --> 00:56:28.720
[Guest 2]: issues.

00:56:28.720 --> 00:56:32.880
[Guest 2]: Of course, there's agenda sitting in a question of which issue gets what age group to vote.

00:56:32.880 --> 00:56:35.960
[Guest 2]: And there's a whole public choice literature about that.

00:56:35.960 --> 00:56:38.200
[Guest 2]: But I do think there is merit in experimentation.

00:56:38.200 --> 00:56:43.840
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, no, you know, I was chatting on a panel discussion a few days ago about cricket, where,

00:56:43.840 --> 00:56:48.600
[Amit Varma]: you know, I was telling people who are sort of, you know, purists of test cricket, cricket

00:56:48.600 --> 00:56:54.080
[Amit Varma]: tragics, as it were, who hate 2020 cricket that listen, if 2020 cricket had come first,

00:56:54.080 --> 00:56:58.280
[Amit Varma]: you would think that the idea of playing a sport over five days is completely absurd.

00:56:58.280 --> 00:57:03.480
[Amit Varma]: So you have the, yeah, so you have the anchoring effect of an existing format.

00:57:03.480 --> 00:57:07.800
[Amit Varma]: And similarly, if 14 year olds were allowed to vote today, and you were to propose that

00:57:07.800 --> 00:57:12.840
[Amit Varma]: no, we should, you know, lift the age to 18, there would be outrage and scandal everywhere.

00:57:12.840 --> 00:57:17.440
[Amit Varma]: So you know, whenever we encounter what appears to be a radical idea, we should just think

00:57:17.440 --> 00:57:23.120
[Amit Varma]: about, you know, are we being anchored by an earlier and old normal, as it were.

00:57:23.120 --> 00:57:26.840
[Amit Varma]: And at this point, I'll tell you a little personal anecdote, and it will seem irrelevant,

00:57:26.840 --> 00:57:28.800
[Amit Varma]: but I'll tell you why I am telling it.

00:57:28.800 --> 00:57:33.280
[Amit Varma]: So when I was 18 or so, because of Punjabi genes and all that I had a beard, so I had

00:57:33.280 --> 00:57:37.920
[Amit Varma]: grown this big beard when I was 18, and I went to play the Maharashtra Junior Chess

00:57:37.920 --> 00:57:41.400
[Amit Varma]: Championships in a city called Aurangabad.

00:57:41.400 --> 00:57:43.600
[Amit Varma]: And this was in the early 1990s.

00:57:43.600 --> 00:57:48.840
[Amit Varma]: And after six rounds, I was the sole leader, having beaten the local favorites also.

00:57:48.840 --> 00:57:51.520
[Amit Varma]: So the next day, it was a nine round tournament.

00:57:51.520 --> 00:57:55.880
[Amit Varma]: So the next day, their main English newspaper, some local newspaper, not one of the national

00:57:55.880 --> 00:58:00.480
[Amit Varma]: ones, but it was the biggest English newspaper then, had me on their front page, a photograph

00:58:00.480 --> 00:58:05.320
[Amit Varma]: of me with my beard, had me on my front page, not the sports page, the front page, with

00:58:05.320 --> 00:58:10.400
[Amit Varma]: the headline, is this man really under 20, which was what Juniors was.

00:58:10.400 --> 00:58:13.560
[Amit Varma]: And you know, it's actually a valid, though I was, of course, legit.

00:58:13.560 --> 00:58:15.580
[Amit Varma]: And I showed my birth certificate and all that.

00:58:15.580 --> 00:58:19.740
[Amit Varma]: But it is actually a scam in many parts of Northern India, because people want to play

00:58:19.740 --> 00:58:21.840
[Amit Varma]: for under 19 and under 16.

00:58:21.840 --> 00:58:25.280
[Amit Varma]: They hedge their edge, like there's a, you know, they fake their age, and they have fake

00:58:25.280 --> 00:58:26.280
[Amit Varma]: certificates.

00:58:26.280 --> 00:58:30.800
[Amit Varma]: There is, in fact, a joke about the Pakistani cricket player, Shahid Afridi, who was 17

00:58:30.800 --> 00:58:32.160
[Amit Varma]: for 10 years.

00:58:32.160 --> 00:58:36.600
[Amit Varma]: And it strikes me that if you actually, you know, had this kind of proportional, the weightages

00:58:36.600 --> 00:58:42.240
[Amit Varma]: for younger people, where a 14 year old gets five votes, then you would have a similar

00:58:42.240 --> 00:58:43.840
[Guest 2]: scam kind of cropping up.

00:58:43.840 --> 00:58:47.880
[Guest 2]: Actually, you know, that way, maybe we can shoot, kill two birds with one stone, and

00:58:47.880 --> 00:58:51.640
[Guest 2]: the government has better incentive to register births in India.

00:58:51.640 --> 00:58:56.480
[Guest 2]: And just throwing this out there, that if the birth certificate becomes such a big issue.

00:58:56.480 --> 00:59:02.080
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, and as if that process cannot get corrupted, and as if you don't have a state capacity

00:59:02.080 --> 00:59:05.280
[Amit Varma]: problem, but I guess blockchain could be a solution down the line.

00:59:05.280 --> 00:59:08.640
[Guest 2]: But you know, going back to the thing you said, which is this radical, you know, we

00:59:08.640 --> 00:59:12.400
[Guest 2]: get anchored to particular systems, and then anything else sounds crazy.

00:59:12.400 --> 00:59:18.080
[Guest 2]: I think we should take a leaf out of like Ambedkar's book, like, introducing universal

00:59:18.080 --> 00:59:24.560
[Guest 2]: adult franchise in India in 1950, is one of the most outrageous things that the world

00:59:24.560 --> 00:59:26.440
[Guest 2]: has ever heard of, right?

00:59:26.440 --> 00:59:29.000
[Guest 2]: And literally, nobody thought it would work, right?

00:59:29.000 --> 00:59:33.600
[Guest 2]: Everyone said, this is going to be bad, 90% of your population is illiterate.

00:59:33.600 --> 00:59:37.000
[Guest 2]: How are illiterate people going to even know the name to put on the ballot?

00:59:37.000 --> 00:59:41.480
[Guest 2]: And you know, I mean, we've moved to a system of symbols, and hence the lotus and the hand

00:59:41.480 --> 00:59:44.800
[Guest 2]: and they like, they managed to solve every single problem.

00:59:44.800 --> 00:59:49.800
[Guest 2]: India is a very thriving democracy in terms of voting, right?

00:59:49.800 --> 00:59:54.480
[Guest 2]: India votes in overwhelming numbers, one of the highest voter turnouts in the world, repeatedly

00:59:54.480 --> 00:59:57.480
[Guest 2]: across all levels of election, local to national.

00:59:57.480 --> 01:00:03.400
[Guest 2]: So this thing that was called the most outrageous experiment to ever be conducted, right?

01:00:03.400 --> 01:00:07.440
[Guest 2]: You're handing women the right to vote, along with everyone else, right?

01:00:07.440 --> 01:00:10.680
[Guest 2]: How are we going to verify women who are in purdah?

01:00:10.680 --> 01:00:12.840
[Guest 2]: They're going to cover their face, right?

01:00:12.840 --> 01:00:16.600
[Guest 2]: How do we register their name, Mrs. so and so or by their own name?

01:00:16.600 --> 01:00:18.760
[Guest 2]: It is these crazy questions that popped up.

01:00:18.760 --> 01:00:22.400
[Guest 2]: They're all there in Ornishani's book, and you know, we can read about it.

01:00:22.400 --> 01:00:24.480
[Guest 2]: But it was an outrageous experiment.

01:00:24.480 --> 01:00:27.000
[Guest 2]: And now we just completely take it for granted, right?

01:00:27.000 --> 01:00:32.360
[Guest 2]: So maybe we should be like Ambedkar and push for some really, really outrageous experiments,

01:00:32.360 --> 01:00:33.360
[Guest 2]: right?

01:00:33.360 --> 01:00:38.040
[Guest 2]: And have, you know, illiterate people, young people, 14 year olds, why not?

01:00:38.040 --> 01:00:39.280
[Amit Varma]: Fascinating, fascinating.

01:00:39.280 --> 01:00:44.200
[Amit Varma]: And even do ultrasound on babies still in the womb to figure out their voting preferences.

01:00:44.200 --> 01:00:45.200
[Guest 2]: Technology can.

01:00:45.200 --> 01:00:46.200
[Amit Varma]: That's illegal in India.

01:00:46.200 --> 01:00:47.200
[Amit Varma]: Anything.

01:00:47.200 --> 01:00:48.200
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, indeed.

01:00:48.200 --> 01:00:53.240
[Amit Varma]: So, Alex, let's, let's move on to your second lesson.

01:00:53.240 --> 01:00:55.400
[Amit Varma]: We're only on the second lesson.

01:00:55.400 --> 01:00:57.080
[Unknown]: Oh, my gosh.

01:00:57.080 --> 01:00:58.640
[Guest 1]: I brought snacks.

01:00:58.640 --> 01:00:59.640
[Guest 1]: Yeah.

01:00:59.640 --> 01:01:00.640
[Guest 1]: Yeah.

01:01:00.640 --> 01:01:07.280
[Guest 1]: Second is something which Mark Andreessen, the venture capitalist, but also the writer

01:01:07.280 --> 01:01:13.600
[Guest 1]: of the first web browser, he said a few years ago, software is eating the world.

01:01:13.600 --> 01:01:15.800
[Guest 1]: And I think that's true in a lot of circumstances.

01:01:15.800 --> 01:01:21.880
[Guest 1]: But what is particular, what we're seeing now is software is eating the biological world

01:01:21.880 --> 01:01:26.880
[Guest 1]: because these mRNA vaccines, it's really incredible.

01:01:26.880 --> 01:01:28.080
[Guest 1]: It's software.

01:01:28.080 --> 01:01:36.680
[Guest 1]: Here's an amazing fact is that the virus was coded, you know, by Chinese scientists, something

01:01:36.680 --> 01:01:43.680
[Guest 1]: like January 13th, and was sent to the people in the United States got it at Moderna.

01:01:43.680 --> 01:01:49.200
[Guest 1]: And they developed a vaccine literally within two days.

01:01:49.200 --> 01:01:55.080
[Guest 1]: And so the digital virus got to the United States before the actual virus did.

01:01:55.080 --> 01:01:59.160
[Guest 1]: You know, maybe there's some dispute about when exactly it came, but the digital virus

01:01:59.160 --> 01:02:02.240
[Guest 1]: moved around the world very, very quickly.

01:02:02.240 --> 01:02:03.240
[Guest 1]: Right.

01:02:03.240 --> 01:02:11.360
[Guest 1]: And so Moderna, who has developed this vaccine, they never even looked at the virus itself.

01:02:11.360 --> 01:02:12.360
[Guest 1]: Right.

01:02:12.360 --> 01:02:16.760
[Guest 1]: So they didn't get any samples, you know, they just looked at the code.

01:02:16.760 --> 01:02:23.040
[Guest 1]: So they read the code and then they figured out, OK, here is a here's the protein which

01:02:23.040 --> 01:02:24.720
[Guest 1]: we're going to go after.

01:02:24.720 --> 01:02:33.320
[Guest 1]: And in the computer, they designed the vaccine, the mRNA vaccine, and then essentially what

01:02:33.320 --> 01:02:38.320
[Guest 1]: happens is that that vaccine is printed.

01:02:38.320 --> 01:02:44.120
[Guest 1]: So on previous vaccines, you know, we grew them in these vats.

01:02:44.120 --> 01:02:45.320
[Guest 1]: Right.

01:02:45.320 --> 01:02:51.240
[Guest 1]: And that's actually part of the danger, because one, if you're dealing with the actual virus,

01:02:51.240 --> 01:02:57.840
[Guest 1]: it could contaminate and get out and infect the vaccine itself.

01:02:57.840 --> 01:03:04.680
[Guest 1]: And two, when you are growing things, there is a opportunity for bacterial infection.

01:03:04.680 --> 01:03:07.040
[Guest 1]: And it's very complicated, always very.

01:03:07.040 --> 01:03:08.040
[Guest 1]: It's like it's like cooking.

01:03:08.040 --> 01:03:09.040
[Guest 1]: It's like making a souffle.

01:03:09.040 --> 01:03:10.040
[Guest 1]: Right.

01:03:10.040 --> 01:03:15.400
[Guest 1]: So the old way of making a vaccine was like making a souffle and you get just one element

01:03:15.400 --> 01:03:18.320
[Guest 1]: wrong and the souffle collapses.

01:03:18.320 --> 01:03:25.040
[Guest 1]: In the new style, the mRNA vaccines, you're more or less printing the vaccine.

01:03:25.040 --> 01:03:30.920
[Guest 1]: And then when you inject it into the body, you're actually not injecting the vaccine

01:03:30.920 --> 01:03:34.760
[Guest 1]: per se, you're injecting instructions.

01:03:34.760 --> 01:03:42.240
[Guest 1]: And the body's cells pick up those instructions and they use that to generate the so-called

01:03:42.240 --> 01:03:48.240
[Guest 1]: spike protein, which then the body is alerted to, oh, this is a foreign, gets a sneak peek

01:03:48.240 --> 01:03:49.240
[Guest 1]: at it.

01:03:49.240 --> 01:03:50.480
[Guest 1]: This is a foreign invader.

01:03:50.480 --> 01:03:56.560
[Guest 1]: And so the body's immune system learns how to attack the spike protein so that when it's

01:03:56.560 --> 01:04:01.800
[Guest 1]: actually challenged by the real virus, the body has built up its defenses.

01:04:01.800 --> 01:04:09.560
[Guest 1]: So what we have done, in effect, is this is what we we knew we were getting there when

01:04:09.560 --> 01:04:12.960
[Guest 1]: we had the human genome project.

01:04:12.960 --> 01:04:16.420
[Guest 1]: We've always talked about, well, we're going to we have the blueprint and now we're going

01:04:16.420 --> 01:04:17.420
[Guest 1]: to read the code.

01:04:17.420 --> 01:04:18.640
[Guest 1]: This is the code.

01:04:18.640 --> 01:04:24.320
[Guest 1]: But this is a really a tremendous example of this in practice.

01:04:24.320 --> 01:04:26.880
[Guest 1]: We read the code of the virus.

01:04:26.880 --> 01:04:30.800
[Guest 1]: We created a code for the vaccine.

01:04:30.800 --> 01:04:36.000
[Guest 1]: We inject that into the body and then the body produces its own defenses by reading

01:04:36.000 --> 01:04:37.000
[Guest 1]: this code.

01:04:37.000 --> 01:04:41.920
[Guest 1]: And we're going to be able to do that for many, many other things, because everything

01:04:41.920 --> 01:04:48.240
[Guest 1]: that goes on in the body involves creating a protein, right?

01:04:48.240 --> 01:04:52.520
[Guest 1]: Creating some kind of machine, which is basically what proteins are.

01:04:52.520 --> 01:05:00.200
[Guest 1]: And there's a system for reading the DNA or the RNA, the messenger RNA, and creating these

01:05:00.200 --> 01:05:01.200
[Guest 1]: proteins.

01:05:01.200 --> 01:05:04.360
[Guest 1]: And so everything which goes on in the body is creating these proteins.

01:05:04.360 --> 01:05:12.040
[Guest 1]: So one of the things which Moderna is working on, for example, is to target the messenger

01:05:12.040 --> 01:05:19.460
[Guest 1]: RNA to the type of cells which you need to read it and create a new protein.

01:05:19.460 --> 01:05:22.920
[Guest 1]: So one of the things that they're working on is you have a heart attack.

01:05:22.920 --> 01:05:25.840
[Guest 1]: You need to develop new heart muscle.

01:05:25.840 --> 01:05:34.440
[Guest 1]: So if you can have a mRNA and you inject it and so that it's read by the heart muscle

01:05:34.440 --> 01:05:39.880
[Guest 1]: cells, and then they're told, create this protein for building blood vessels, for building

01:05:39.880 --> 01:05:41.800
[Guest 1]: more muscle, right?

01:05:41.800 --> 01:05:46.040
[Guest 1]: So you can instruct the body to fix itself.

01:05:46.040 --> 01:05:48.100
[Guest 1]: And we're going to see a lot more of this.

01:05:48.100 --> 01:05:55.220
[Guest 1]: And so I think that one of the unexpected or one of the unintended consequences of this

01:05:55.220 --> 01:06:03.320
[Guest 1]: is that we've advanced the mRNA technology and more and more biology is going to be understood

01:06:03.320 --> 01:06:05.160
[Guest 1]: as software.

01:06:05.160 --> 01:06:10.800
[Guest 1]: And we're going to be able to program that software to do things which are going to save

01:06:10.800 --> 01:06:12.700
[Amit Varma]: lives and improve health.

01:06:12.700 --> 01:06:14.640
[Amit Varma]: It almost feels magical, right?

01:06:14.640 --> 01:06:19.200
[Amit Varma]: And I remember an old Douglas Adams quote where he's talking about religion and, you

01:06:19.200 --> 01:06:23.520
[Amit Varma]: know, how one of the things that religion tries to do through ritual and spectacle in

01:06:23.520 --> 01:06:28.640
[Amit Varma]: these grand churches and all of that is institute a sense of awe and wonder in the person.

01:06:28.640 --> 01:06:33.560
[Amit Varma]: And Adams's point was that, you know, when I first understood how natural selection works,

01:06:33.560 --> 01:06:36.640
[Amit Varma]: the science of it, that is what filled me with awe and wonder.

01:06:36.640 --> 01:06:41.040
[Amit Varma]: And that's what this kind of science does, you know, like, although I'm utterly ignorant

01:06:41.040 --> 01:06:45.360
[Amit Varma]: of the science, I was skeptical of a vaccine coming so far simply because there had never

01:06:45.360 --> 01:06:47.120
[Amit Varma]: been a coronavirus vaccine before.

01:06:47.120 --> 01:06:52.000
[Amit Varma]: There were other vaccines for the flus, which are not caused by coronaviruses, but never

01:06:52.000 --> 01:06:53.900
[Amit Varma]: a vaccine for the coronavirus.

01:06:53.900 --> 01:06:56.200
[Amit Varma]: And we've seen how long the HIV vaccine has been.

01:06:56.200 --> 01:07:00.400
[Amit Varma]: They've been trying to get an HIV vaccine out, which is also, you know, addressing a

01:07:00.400 --> 01:07:01.840
[Amit Varma]: virus and they failed to do that.

01:07:01.840 --> 01:07:06.280
[Amit Varma]: So to have this happen within a period of months and almost, you know, with a software

01:07:06.280 --> 01:07:12.160
[Amit Varma]: update as it were, instead of, you know, working with old clunky hardware seems to me magical.

01:07:12.160 --> 01:07:17.960
[Amit Varma]: And it also seems to me that this also tells us that we are old clunky hardware and that

01:07:17.960 --> 01:07:23.160
[Amit Varma]: we are creating this incredible software, which can, you know, although people, you

01:07:23.160 --> 01:07:28.000
[Amit Varma]: know, would talk about, talk in alarmist tones about the existential threat to humanity from

01:07:28.000 --> 01:07:29.000
[Amit Varma]: it.

01:07:29.000 --> 01:07:33.680
[Amit Varma]: I think it's, it's incredible because it can just, you know, our hardware is what it is,

01:07:33.680 --> 01:07:40.480
[Amit Varma]: but our software can improve our lives in such incredible ways.

01:07:40.480 --> 01:07:44.800
[Guest 2]: You know, this brings me to something that was one of my lessons, but I think this is

01:07:44.800 --> 01:07:47.000
[Guest 2]: a nice point to add this in.

01:07:47.000 --> 01:07:53.560
[Guest 2]: Like one of the things I've learned is science is on its path to solving these problems.

01:07:53.560 --> 01:07:57.520
[Guest 2]: The problem is economic illiteracy, right?

01:07:57.520 --> 01:07:59.640
[Guest 2]: So this is your lesson three, therefore.

01:07:59.640 --> 01:08:04.280
[Guest 2]: This is my lesson three, but it works perfectly well without, it follows perfectly from what

01:08:04.280 --> 01:08:08.020
[Guest 2]: Alex is saying, because just think about this, right?

01:08:08.020 --> 01:08:14.740
[Guest 2]: By late Jan, we have already coded and sequenced the vaccine, right?

01:08:14.740 --> 01:08:18.760
[Guest 2]: Everything else is an enormous failure in the understanding of costs and benefits and

01:08:18.760 --> 01:08:20.800
[Guest 2]: allocation and delivery, right?

01:08:20.800 --> 01:08:25.280
[Guest 2]: I mean, I'm in this at December right now, we're just shy of Christmas.

01:08:25.280 --> 01:08:29.200
[Guest 2]: I don't expect to get the vaccine because I'm young and healthy and, you know, not an

01:08:29.200 --> 01:08:34.240
[Guest 2]: essential worker or anything before the end of spring, maybe even halfway through summer,

01:08:34.240 --> 01:08:37.120
[Guest 2]: depending on when Virginia gets its act together.

01:08:37.120 --> 01:08:43.320
[Guest 2]: It would have by then been maybe 17, 18 months since we actually had the scientific answer,

01:08:43.320 --> 01:08:44.320
[Guest 2]: right?

01:08:44.320 --> 01:08:49.360
[Guest 2]: And all the other problems are things like, you know, the omission commission bias that

01:08:49.360 --> 01:08:50.360
[Guest 2]: Alex talked about.

01:08:50.360 --> 01:08:54.920
[Guest 2]: You know, one thing, Alex, I don't know if you mentioned this here or before, but, you

01:08:54.920 --> 01:08:57.840
[Guest 2]: know, the FDA is supposed to be bureaucratic, right?

01:08:57.840 --> 01:09:05.600
[Guest 2]: Like, I mean, their entire job is to slow down things so that they get the mandate during

01:09:05.600 --> 01:09:09.040
[Guest 2]: a global pandemic, which is also an emergency.

01:09:09.040 --> 01:09:13.520
[Guest 2]: They just don't know how to speed it up because every protocol in their book is to slow things

01:09:13.520 --> 01:09:18.800
[Guest 2]: down and make them safer and consider every, you know, one side of the trade off alone.

01:09:18.800 --> 01:09:21.400
[Guest 2]: That's the job we gave them to do, right?

01:09:21.400 --> 01:09:27.280
[Guest 2]: So we don't get more Ford Pinto equivalents in the, you know, medical world or whatever.

01:09:27.280 --> 01:09:31.640
[Guest 2]: And now we're telling them act fast and we just don't have an alternative.

01:09:31.640 --> 01:09:37.840
[Guest 2]: FDA's emergency procedures are slower than their regular procedures, believe it or not,

01:09:37.840 --> 01:09:38.840
[Guest 2]: right?

01:09:38.840 --> 01:09:45.880
[Guest 2]: FDA's emergency procedures stop labs from innovating private labs from testing, right?

01:09:45.880 --> 01:09:51.160
[Guest 2]: So if they hadn't declared an emergency, then we might have had better testing in the United

01:09:51.160 --> 01:09:55.280
[Guest 2]: States than we actually did after the FDA declared the emergency, right?

01:09:55.280 --> 01:10:01.200
[Guest 2]: So there are just these bizarre institutions we've created that have no, I mean, it's not

01:10:01.200 --> 01:10:05.680
[Guest 2]: clear they're good on science, but let's assume they're good on the science, but they're certainly

01:10:05.680 --> 01:10:07.920
[Guest 2]: not good on the economics, right?

01:10:07.920 --> 01:10:13.120
[Guest 2]: We had such a big and political problem with masks in the United States, because initially

01:10:13.120 --> 01:10:20.600
[Guest 2]: Dr. Fauci and others, right, they said masks are not necessary because they were worried

01:10:20.600 --> 01:10:24.720
[Guest 2]: that there won't be enough masks for, you know, frontline workers.

01:10:24.720 --> 01:10:28.640
[Guest 2]: That is a failure in understanding demand and supply.

01:10:28.640 --> 01:10:30.880
[Guest 2]: You know, that is not a failure in communication.

01:10:30.880 --> 01:10:32.720
[Guest 2]: And that is certainly not a failure.

01:10:32.720 --> 01:10:38.400
[Guest 2]: I mean, you could just call Alex Tabarrok or watch like one of the MRU videos and they

01:10:38.400 --> 01:10:43.480
[Guest 2]: will tell you, I have made a video on price gouging and how supply is forthcoming, right?

01:10:43.480 --> 01:10:50.160
[Guest 2]: Like ask anyone who knows Econ 101 and they will tell you that if you tell people masks

01:10:50.160 --> 01:10:53.960
[Guest 2]: are essential, supply of masks is going to be forthcoming.

01:10:53.960 --> 01:10:56.600
[Guest 2]: There is no inelastic demand curve for that.

01:10:56.600 --> 01:11:03.880
[Guest 2]: So my big lesson is we are not teaching enough people outside of, you know, professional

01:11:03.880 --> 01:11:08.320
[Guest 2]: academic economists, or maybe we will go to business school and take a couple of sequences.

01:11:08.320 --> 01:11:10.840
[Guest 2]: We don't teach them enough economics, right?

01:11:10.840 --> 01:11:14.720
[Guest 2]: And the follow up to that is we certainly don't teach them enough ethics, right?

01:11:14.720 --> 01:11:18.800
[Guest 2]: To think about these broader questions of, you know, how we choose solve the trolley

01:11:18.800 --> 01:11:23.000
[Guest 2]: problem or how do we solve a challenge trial problem or something like that, which I also

01:11:23.000 --> 01:11:24.360
[Guest 2]: think is essential.

01:11:24.360 --> 01:11:30.320
[Guest 2]: And economics could have, you know, just having basic understanding of how supply chains work

01:11:30.320 --> 01:11:36.320
[Guest 2]: and the world works would have gotten us this vaccine a hell of a lot sooner than it actually

01:11:36.320 --> 01:11:37.320
[Guest 2]: happened.

01:11:37.320 --> 01:11:38.320
[Guest 1]: Yeah.

01:11:38.320 --> 01:11:43.120
[Guest 1]: The failure to do cost benefit analysis, even very simple cost benefit analysis is unbelievable.

01:11:43.120 --> 01:11:44.760
[Guest 1]: And it affected even economists.

01:11:44.760 --> 01:11:50.520
[Guest 1]: I've just been shocked, actually, the debates that I have had with fellow economists who

01:11:50.520 --> 01:11:56.600
[Guest 1]: in the face of thousands of people dying are still saying, well, maybe the, you know, FDA

01:11:56.600 --> 01:11:59.000
[Guest 1]: waiting three weeks, you know, maybe that's OK.

01:11:59.000 --> 01:12:04.160
[Guest 1]: We still need to do peer review and like just not being able to, you know, run some simple

01:12:04.160 --> 01:12:10.040
[Guest 1]: numbers and do the cost benefit analysis, run the numbers, you know, and a lot of economists

01:12:10.040 --> 01:12:14.680
[Guest 1]: even have not been able to do that, with some exceptions, like Paul Romer has been great

01:12:14.680 --> 01:12:16.080
[Guest 1]: right from the very beginning.

01:12:16.080 --> 01:12:20.760
[Guest 1]: He ran the numbers on testing and said, look, this is insane.

01:12:20.760 --> 01:12:26.200
[Guest 1]: We're losing trillions of dollars in wealth and we could save this with billions of dollars

01:12:26.200 --> 01:12:27.200
[Guest 1]: investment in testing.

01:12:27.200 --> 01:12:30.280
[Guest 1]: And he was saying that, you know, practically from day one.

01:12:30.280 --> 01:12:32.040
[Guest 1]: So a few economists have been good.

01:12:32.040 --> 01:12:37.960
[Guest 1]: You know, when I spoke with people in Congress, you know, I told them, you know, like I'm

01:12:37.960 --> 01:12:41.560
[Guest 1]: a fairly conservative kind of free market economist.

01:12:41.560 --> 01:12:43.360
[Guest 1]: You know, I don't say this very often.

01:12:43.360 --> 01:12:45.600
[Guest 1]: In fact, I've never said this before.

01:12:45.600 --> 01:12:51.120
[Guest 1]: But now is the time to throw money at the problem.

01:12:51.120 --> 01:12:54.720
[Guest 1]: And you know, it's not like some genius insight here.

01:12:54.720 --> 01:12:59.640
[Guest 1]: The insight was, you know, the U.S. economy is losing hundreds of billions of dollars

01:12:59.640 --> 01:13:01.720
[Guest 1]: every single month.

01:13:01.720 --> 01:13:04.520
[Guest 1]: And we have trillions on one side and billions on the other.

01:13:04.520 --> 01:13:06.400
[Guest 1]: That's a very simple cost benefit analysis.

01:13:06.400 --> 01:13:09.180
[Guest 1]: We need to invest in vaccines.

01:13:09.180 --> 01:13:11.360
[Guest 1]: We need to invest in testing.

01:13:11.360 --> 01:13:15.040
[Guest 1]: And this is going to save lives and it's going to save money at the same time.

01:13:15.040 --> 01:13:21.880
[Guest 1]: And yet that was just incredibly hard even to get that simple message across.

01:13:21.880 --> 01:13:26.240
[Guest 1]: You know, we've got sticker shock when the Kramer and I and the team were saying we ought

01:13:26.240 --> 01:13:31.080
[Guest 1]: to be spending, you know, $100 billion on vaccines.

01:13:31.080 --> 01:13:35.000
[Guest 1]: And people were going, you can't say $100 billion, that's just going to freak people

01:13:35.000 --> 01:13:36.000
[Guest 1]: out.

01:13:36.000 --> 01:13:37.440
[Guest 1]: You know, sticker shock.

01:13:37.440 --> 01:13:42.440
[Guest 1]: And so fortunately, we did Operation Warp Speed, which was very, very good.

01:13:42.440 --> 01:13:47.320
[Guest 1]: You know, Operation Warp Speed is really the only bright spot in the Trump administration's

01:13:47.320 --> 01:13:50.320
[Guest 1]: response to the pandemic.

01:13:50.320 --> 01:13:51.960
[Guest 1]: But it still was too small.

01:13:51.960 --> 01:13:53.200
[Guest 1]: And we told them it was too small.

01:13:53.200 --> 01:13:57.840
[Guest 1]: I mean, again, I want to say I'm grateful, I really am grateful for Operation Warp Speed

01:13:57.840 --> 01:14:05.400
[Guest 1]: and Peter Marks at the FDA and Perna, General Perna, and Slowy, and all those guys have

01:14:05.400 --> 01:14:11.000
[Guest 1]: done great, better than anybody else in the world, in fact, as Europe is now finding out.

01:14:11.000 --> 01:14:12.480
[Guest 1]: But we should have done more.

01:14:12.480 --> 01:14:14.520
[Guest 1]: And it was obvious that we should have done more.

01:14:14.520 --> 01:14:15.520
[Guest 2]: Yeah.

01:14:15.520 --> 01:14:21.000
[Guest 2]: And, you know, so one part is like just Operation Warp Speed and like getting like the big numbers

01:14:21.000 --> 01:14:25.320
[Guest 2]: and those kinds of, you know, someone needs to do this analysis and get it across sort

01:14:25.320 --> 01:14:26.320
[Guest 2]: of thing.

01:14:26.320 --> 01:14:27.320
[Guest 2]: Right.

01:14:27.320 --> 01:14:29.440
[Guest 2]: But a lot of it is even like baby stuff.

01:14:29.440 --> 01:14:30.440
[Guest 2]: Right.

01:14:30.440 --> 01:14:33.320
[Guest 2]: I mean, we're having a run on toilet paper in the United States.

01:14:33.320 --> 01:14:36.200
[Guest 2]: It's like, you know, you're in Soviet Union or something.

01:14:36.200 --> 01:14:37.960
[Guest 2]: The whole thing is nuts.

01:14:37.960 --> 01:14:42.200
[Guest 2]: It's just a complete misunderstanding of, you know, very basic things like, you know,

01:14:42.200 --> 01:14:46.920
[Guest 2]: people struggling to get a mask, people struggling to get hand sanitizer, you know, not being

01:14:46.920 --> 01:14:47.920
[Guest 2]: able to move about.

01:14:47.920 --> 01:14:51.880
[Guest 2]: I bought hand sanitizer in a gallon size and I sent it to our friend Mario Rizzo in New

01:14:51.880 --> 01:14:57.080
[Guest 2]: York City because they had all sorts of like price gouging laws where nobody could sell

01:14:57.080 --> 01:15:00.060
[Guest 2]: hand sanitizer in reasonable quantities.

01:15:00.060 --> 01:15:04.360
[Guest 2]: So this is just like I mean, it's so basic.

01:15:04.360 --> 01:15:09.040
[Guest 2]: If a student of mine in my principal's class did not know the answers to this question,

01:15:09.040 --> 01:15:11.080
[Guest 2]: they would probably fail the class.

01:15:11.080 --> 01:15:12.080
[Guest 2]: Right.

01:15:12.080 --> 01:15:18.000
[Guest 2]: And these are the people at the highest levels of government and policy and technology who

01:15:18.000 --> 01:15:22.280
[Guest 2]: are making decisions who are allowed to do this, not just with other people's money,

01:15:22.280 --> 01:15:24.080
[Guest 2]: but with other people's lives.

01:15:24.080 --> 01:15:25.080
[Guest 2]: Right.

01:15:25.080 --> 01:15:26.960
[Guest 2]: And it permeates everything.

01:15:26.960 --> 01:15:28.920
[Guest 2]: It's like, you know, I mean, we have Emily Oster.

01:15:28.920 --> 01:15:33.280
[Guest 2]: She has this great sub stack on, you know, COVID and its impact on children and school

01:15:33.280 --> 01:15:39.300
[Guest 2]: closures and things like that, just massive amount of evidence on the costs on the one

01:15:39.300 --> 01:15:44.640
[Guest 2]: side because of the loss of learning, especially disproportionately falling on the poor and

01:15:44.640 --> 01:15:48.980
[Guest 2]: the benefits of, you know, allowing a little bit of, you know, opening of schools and maybe

01:15:48.980 --> 01:15:51.800
[Guest 2]: closing something else down instead.

01:15:51.800 --> 01:15:55.160
[Guest 2]: What shocks me is these are non starters in the United States.

01:15:55.160 --> 01:15:57.880
[Guest 2]: There are just no takers for these conversations.

01:15:57.880 --> 01:15:58.880
[Guest 2]: Right.

01:15:58.880 --> 01:16:01.960
[Guest 2]: It's like even in India, opening schools right now is dead on arrival.

01:16:01.960 --> 01:16:05.480
[Guest 2]: No one will even consider it, but you can go to a movie theater.

01:16:05.480 --> 01:16:06.480
[Guest 2]: Right.

01:16:06.480 --> 01:16:08.160
[Guest 2]: Because that's 25 percent occupancy.

01:16:08.160 --> 01:16:09.360
[Guest 2]: Movie theaters are allowed.

01:16:09.360 --> 01:16:14.440
[Guest 2]: So the whole thing just seems a little bit like, you know, odd to me that these people

01:16:14.440 --> 01:16:16.220
[Guest 2]: don't get these basic concepts.

01:16:16.220 --> 01:16:21.560
[Guest 2]: Not only do they not know cost benefit analysis, as Alex pointed out, they don't even know

01:16:21.560 --> 01:16:26.920
[Guest 2]: that cost benefit analysis should be done to guide the decision.

01:16:26.920 --> 01:16:27.920
[Guest 2]: Right.

01:16:27.920 --> 01:16:32.000
[Guest 2]: What you do is you pick up the phone and call Michael Kramer and Alex Tabarrok and say,

01:16:32.000 --> 01:16:34.520
[Guest 2]: hey, you guys seem like you know how to do this thing.

01:16:34.520 --> 01:16:36.240
[Guest 2]: Why don't you do it for us?

01:16:36.240 --> 01:16:38.120
[Guest 2]: But the instinct is just not to do it.

01:16:38.120 --> 01:16:43.680
[Guest 2]: The second thing I want to say here is there is this extreme reaction to profit.

01:16:43.680 --> 01:16:44.680
[Guest 2]: Right.

01:16:44.680 --> 01:16:51.680
[Guest 2]: Like just people making money, that is enough for progressives in the United States to shut

01:16:51.680 --> 01:16:53.600
[Guest 2]: every good idea down.

01:16:53.600 --> 01:16:58.960
[Guest 2]: We are OK delaying the vaccine, but we don't want a big pharma company to profit.

01:16:58.960 --> 01:16:59.960
[Guest 2]: And I'm sort of the opposite.

01:16:59.960 --> 01:17:00.960
[Guest 2]: Right.

01:17:00.960 --> 01:17:04.560
[Guest 2]: I'm like, can we make them more profit so that I can get it tomorrow instead of getting

01:17:04.560 --> 01:17:06.800
[Guest 2]: the vaccine six months from now?

01:17:06.800 --> 01:17:10.400
[Guest 2]: But this somehow like almost like I don't know what it is.

01:17:10.400 --> 01:17:18.640
[Guest 2]: It's like some visceral biological reaction against profit making by somebody else where

01:17:18.640 --> 01:17:24.120
[Guest 2]: even ideas that would benefit oneself, like they will cut their nose to spite their face.

01:17:24.120 --> 01:17:25.640
[Guest 2]: By they, I mean the New York Times.

01:17:25.640 --> 01:17:26.640
[Guest 2]: Right.

01:17:26.640 --> 01:17:31.680
[Guest 2]: Like that's how bad the narrative and the commentary is when it discusses things like,

01:17:31.680 --> 01:17:36.640
[Guest 2]: you know, should you give someone a subsidy or a short contract or some just complete

01:17:36.640 --> 01:17:39.440
[Guest 2]: misunderstanding of what is at stake?

01:17:39.440 --> 01:17:43.680
[Guest 2]: You know, do we really need to prevent them from making a few extra dollars or a few extra

01:17:43.680 --> 01:17:48.400
[Guest 2]: million dollars if we can save, you know, so many lives, every life, by the way?

01:17:48.400 --> 01:17:50.880
[Guest 2]: You know, the rough estimate is like nine to ten million dollars.

01:17:50.880 --> 01:17:54.160
[Guest 2]: I think Alex will know this number better with Operation Warp Speed.

01:17:54.160 --> 01:17:55.160
[Guest 2]: Right.

01:17:55.160 --> 01:17:58.520
[Guest 2]: But what's the, you know, economists reduce the human life.

01:17:58.520 --> 01:17:59.760
[Guest 2]: We're always called reductive.

01:17:59.760 --> 01:18:00.760
[Guest 2]: Right.

01:18:00.760 --> 01:18:07.200
[Guest 2]: But they reduce it to a pretty large and meaningful number that tells you that we must act very,

01:18:07.200 --> 01:18:08.200
[Guest 2]: very fast.

01:18:08.200 --> 01:18:11.260
[Guest 2]: So those are the sorts of things that have just annoyed me.

01:18:11.260 --> 01:18:16.200
[Guest 2]: And I have become more of an economic imperialist than I ever was before this.

01:18:16.200 --> 01:18:17.200
[Guest 2]: And I come from George Mason.

01:18:17.200 --> 01:18:18.640
[Guest 2]: So I was already there.

01:18:18.640 --> 01:18:19.640
[Guest 2]: Right.

01:18:19.640 --> 01:18:22.080
[Guest 2]: But I'm really I have gone nuts in my head over this.

01:18:22.080 --> 01:18:23.400
[Guest 2]: This just really bothers me.

01:18:23.400 --> 01:18:24.400
[Guest 1]: Yeah.

01:18:24.400 --> 01:18:29.920
[Guest 1]: Riffing off Mencken, I said, progressivism, the haunting fear that someone somewhere is

01:18:29.920 --> 01:18:30.920
[Guest 1]: making a profit.

01:18:30.920 --> 01:18:31.920
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

01:18:31.920 --> 01:18:33.880
[Amit Varma]: So, I mean, I have a couple of thoughts.

01:18:33.880 --> 01:18:37.640
[Amit Varma]: One, I'd like to clarify to the listeners that when we use all these numbers, when Alex

01:18:37.640 --> 01:18:42.680
[Amit Varma]: says that, you know, hundreds of billions were lost by the economy every month, these

01:18:42.680 --> 01:18:43.680
[Amit Varma]: are not just numbers.

01:18:43.680 --> 01:18:45.040
[Amit Varma]: We're not just talking about money.

01:18:45.040 --> 01:18:49.040
[Amit Varma]: These have economics, economics as humanitarian consequences.

01:18:49.040 --> 01:18:52.600
[Amit Varma]: This is lives being lost, futures being stunted.

01:18:52.600 --> 01:18:55.880
[Amit Varma]: It's humanitarian all the way, which is why, you know, one of the reasons I call Indira

01:18:55.880 --> 01:19:01.000
[Amit Varma]: Gandhi such a monster was not just what she did during the emergency and the forced sterilizations

01:19:01.000 --> 01:19:05.280
[Amit Varma]: and all that, but the disastrous economics which kept millions of people in India in

01:19:05.280 --> 01:19:07.800
[Amit Varma]: poverty for decades longer than necessary.

01:19:07.800 --> 01:19:11.560
[Amit Varma]: And some of that came down from this mindset, like about profit.

01:19:11.560 --> 01:19:15.760
[Amit Varma]: You know, Nehru once famously said to JRD Tata, quote, do not speak to me of profit.

01:19:15.760 --> 01:19:17.080
[Amit Varma]: It is a dirty word.

01:19:17.080 --> 01:19:18.080
[Amit Varma]: Stop quote.

01:19:18.080 --> 01:19:19.080
[Amit Varma]: And this brings me to my question.

01:19:19.080 --> 01:19:22.560
[Amit Varma]: Now, one reason people do think of profit in these terms is because they think of the

01:19:22.560 --> 01:19:27.000
[Amit Varma]: world in zero-sum ways, which our brains are wired to do because we have evolved in times

01:19:27.000 --> 01:19:28.000
[Amit Varma]: of scarcity.

01:19:28.000 --> 01:19:33.920
[Amit Varma]: And it's rational to think in terms of zero-sum ways that, you know, if somebody else gets

01:19:33.920 --> 01:19:37.720
[Amit Varma]: something, that means I can't, and therefore it's that kind of an equation.

01:19:37.720 --> 01:19:40.920
[Amit Varma]: And you see the same thing playing out where people are complaining about all the companies

01:19:40.920 --> 01:19:43.140
[Amit Varma]: that have profited during the pandemic.

01:19:43.140 --> 01:19:46.000
[Amit Varma]: But the bottom line is, how do you make a profit in a free market?

01:19:46.000 --> 01:19:49.320
[Amit Varma]: You know, one way, of course, is you use the coercive power of the state and you become

01:19:49.320 --> 01:19:51.600
[Amit Varma]: a crony and you use those privileges.

01:19:51.600 --> 01:19:55.400
[Amit Varma]: But in a free market where you aren't being a crony, the only way to make a profit is

01:19:55.400 --> 01:19:57.340
[Amit Varma]: to make people better off.

01:19:57.340 --> 01:19:59.000
[Amit Varma]: It is a positive sum game.

01:19:59.000 --> 01:20:01.880
[Amit Varma]: You make their lives better off in some way, and you'll make a profit.

01:20:01.880 --> 01:20:05.040
[Amit Varma]: And like you said, you know, if they were allowed to make more profit, they'd work harder

01:20:05.040 --> 01:20:06.800
[Amit Varma]: at serving society.

01:20:06.800 --> 01:20:12.080
[Amit Varma]: As it were, to me, profit is much more, much more effective than philanthropy in that sense.

01:20:12.080 --> 01:20:16.480
[Amit Varma]: So my question here is that, sure, I get your lament that economic illiteracy remains a

01:20:16.480 --> 01:20:19.080
[Amit Varma]: problem even if the science works out.

01:20:19.080 --> 01:20:21.560
[Amit Varma]: You know, what do we do about the economic illiteracy?

01:20:21.560 --> 01:20:24.540
[Amit Varma]: But isn't that almost an insurmountable problem?

01:20:24.540 --> 01:20:29.640
[Amit Varma]: Because our brains are wired to think in ways which mitigate against, you know, like many

01:20:29.640 --> 01:20:34.760
[Amit Varma]: of the concepts that we know explain the world, like the positive sum nature of voluntary

01:20:34.760 --> 01:20:39.080
[Amit Varma]: exchange, like spontaneous order, are deeply unintuitive.

01:20:39.080 --> 01:20:43.200
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, people simply, you know, resist accepting those kind of truths.

01:20:43.200 --> 01:20:47.280
[Amit Varma]: And even trained economists will often, you know, revert back to the way their brains

01:20:47.280 --> 01:20:48.400
[Amit Varma]: are hardwired.

01:20:48.400 --> 01:20:50.680
[Amit Varma]: So is that more of a lament than a lesson?

01:20:50.680 --> 01:20:54.920
[Guest 2]: No, you know, I'm an optimist, and this might be because of my choice of profession.

01:20:54.920 --> 01:20:58.840
[Guest 2]: But I have taught principles microeconomics less than Alex has.

01:20:58.840 --> 01:21:02.560
[Guest 2]: He's written a book that I have taught, but I have taught that book.

01:21:02.560 --> 01:21:06.960
[Guest 2]: And you can literally see the wheels turning in the class, right, when you explain how

01:21:06.960 --> 01:21:11.400
[Guest 2]: choice is made on the margin or the world is not a zero sum game or, you know, the gains

01:21:11.400 --> 01:21:12.400
[Guest 2]: from trade.

01:21:12.400 --> 01:21:17.000
[Guest 2]: I teach comparative advantage and literally like their brain explodes when that production

01:21:17.000 --> 01:21:19.680
[Guest 2]: possibility frontier like goes out.

01:21:19.680 --> 01:21:25.080
[Guest 2]: I don't think of myself as anyone with exceptional capacity or my students were certainly not

01:21:25.080 --> 01:21:27.360
[Guest 2]: people of above average intelligence.

01:21:27.360 --> 01:21:31.480
[Guest 2]: They were just regular college students, you know, trying to get through whatever one of

01:21:31.480 --> 01:21:33.680
[Guest 2]: their basic one on one courses.

01:21:33.680 --> 01:21:34.680
[Guest 2]: They got it.

01:21:34.680 --> 01:21:38.920
[Guest 2]: It is unintuitive, but that means it needs to be taught right.

01:21:38.920 --> 01:21:43.680
[Guest 2]: Even 12 times 12 was unintuitive until I learned what it was.

01:21:43.680 --> 01:21:49.040
[Guest 2]: So I think this whole like I know the zero sum game thing, but there is we don't think

01:21:49.040 --> 01:21:51.140
[Guest 2]: of economics as a science.

01:21:51.140 --> 01:21:54.500
[Guest 2]: We don't think it has value in anything beyond making money.

01:21:54.500 --> 01:22:00.040
[Guest 2]: And I think that is just a fundamental misunderstanding of, you know, I don't know if this is the

01:22:00.040 --> 01:22:01.760
[Guest 2]: it does.

01:22:01.760 --> 01:22:02.920
[Guest 2]: Alex, how does the book begin?

01:22:02.920 --> 01:22:06.520
[Guest 2]: Does it say economics is the science of living a better life?

01:22:06.520 --> 01:22:08.440
[Guest 2]: What does it say?

01:22:08.440 --> 01:22:12.800
[Guest 2]: Starts with the example of the quotation before.

01:22:12.800 --> 01:22:15.640
[Guest 2]: Economics is all about getting the most out of economics is all about getting the most

01:22:15.640 --> 01:22:16.640
[Guest 2]: out of life.

01:22:16.640 --> 01:22:17.640
[Guest 2]: Right.

01:22:17.640 --> 01:22:18.640
[Guest 2]: So it's not about making money.

01:22:18.640 --> 01:22:22.040
[Guest 2]: It's not like the scientific abstract thing, though there are abstract concepts.

01:22:22.040 --> 01:22:28.560
[Guest 2]: If I can teach it right and I'm not Isaac Newton to like do any of like genius level

01:22:28.560 --> 01:22:29.560
[Guest 2]: things.

01:22:29.560 --> 01:22:34.400
[Guest 2]: And if my students can learn it, then it can be done.

01:22:34.400 --> 01:22:36.200
[Guest 2]: We just need to start them younger.

01:22:36.200 --> 01:22:37.200
[Guest 1]: Yeah.

01:22:37.200 --> 01:22:38.200
[Guest 1]: I mean, Trudy is right.

01:22:38.200 --> 01:22:39.200
[Guest 1]: Of course, Trudy can teach.

01:22:39.200 --> 01:22:42.160
[Guest 1]: She was a great teacher, as are you know that.

01:22:42.160 --> 01:22:48.160
[Guest 1]: But there is another problem, and that is that we have collectivized decision making

01:22:48.160 --> 01:22:53.520
[Guest 1]: so much that actually teaching people economics is sort of the second best solution in a way

01:22:53.520 --> 01:22:58.080
[Guest 1]: that we have to because we are making so many decisions collectively.

01:22:58.080 --> 01:23:03.120
[Guest 1]: And that is now our reflex, right, to think that every single decision, well, we got to

01:23:03.120 --> 01:23:04.120
[Guest 1]: talk about it.

01:23:04.120 --> 01:23:07.160
[Guest 1]: You know, we have to subject this to the democratic process.

01:23:07.160 --> 01:23:11.120
[Guest 1]: We got to everyone has to have their take on Twitter and so forth.

01:23:11.120 --> 01:23:16.680
[Guest 1]: Well, in the past, we wouldn't debate price gouging because people would just raise their

01:23:16.680 --> 01:23:17.680
[Guest 1]: prices.

01:23:17.680 --> 01:23:24.440
[Guest 1]: You know, if you have a free market, you know, things happen without as if guided by an invisible

01:23:24.440 --> 01:23:25.960
[Guest 1]: hand, shall we say.

01:23:25.960 --> 01:23:26.960
[Guest 1]: Right.

01:23:26.960 --> 01:23:31.720
[Guest 1]: But the problem is, is that now the invisible hand needs permission.

01:23:31.720 --> 01:23:34.240
[Guest 1]: It needs permission to do just about anything.

01:23:34.240 --> 01:23:38.880
[Guest 1]: We have locked the invisible hand in a cage and sometimes we'll say, OK, we'll let it

01:23:38.880 --> 01:23:42.980
[Guest 1]: out, you know, and we'll let it do its magic here.

01:23:42.980 --> 01:23:45.280
[Guest 1]: But before we do that, we got to have a debate about it.

01:23:45.280 --> 01:23:47.740
[Guest 1]: We got to talk about it, blah, blah, blah, blah, blah.

01:23:47.740 --> 01:23:51.780
[Guest 1]: We have to have some, you know, some voting and everyone gets their say.

01:23:51.780 --> 01:23:59.360
[Guest 1]: And so and this is the problem with when you collectivize in particular innovation, nobody,

01:23:59.360 --> 01:24:01.960
[Guest 1]: very few people are in favor of innovation.

01:24:01.960 --> 01:24:02.960
[Guest 1]: Right.

01:24:02.960 --> 01:24:06.520
[Guest 1]: Because innovation always disrupts rents.

01:24:06.520 --> 01:24:11.200
[Guest 1]: It disrupts the ordinary way of doing things, the old way of doing things, the way which

01:24:11.200 --> 01:24:13.720
[Guest 1]: is satisfied people in the past.

01:24:13.720 --> 01:24:17.760
[Guest 1]: And innovation benefits only a small number of people at the very beginning.

01:24:17.760 --> 01:24:21.760
[Guest 1]: And that small number of people, they get rich, you know, like Jeff Bezos, something

01:24:21.760 --> 01:24:22.880
[Guest 1]: like that.

01:24:22.880 --> 01:24:28.000
[Guest 1]: And then over time, everyone benefits, as we've discovered in the pandemic, as we've

01:24:28.000 --> 01:24:34.960
[Guest 1]: all had to rely on Amazon trucks delivering us goods and services to survive.

01:24:34.960 --> 01:24:38.040
[Guest 1]: But if you had to put that up to a vote, it would never have passed.

01:24:38.040 --> 01:24:40.280
[Guest 1]: You know, I give the example of Uber, right?

01:24:40.280 --> 01:24:47.040
[Guest 1]: Uber was very wise in scaling up extremely quickly and starting before anybody had a

01:24:47.040 --> 01:24:48.400
[Guest 1]: chance to vote on this.

01:24:48.400 --> 01:24:49.400
[Guest 1]: Right.

01:24:49.400 --> 01:24:54.920
[Guest 1]: So if you would ask people, do you think it's a good idea that strangers in a car should

01:24:54.920 --> 01:24:59.400
[Guest 1]: be able to pick other people up, other strangers and give them a ride?

01:24:59.400 --> 01:25:00.400
[Guest 1]: You know what?

01:25:00.400 --> 01:25:01.400
[Guest 1]: What?

01:25:01.400 --> 01:25:06.560
[Guest 1]: Our mothers always told us was the one thing our mother kept telling us.

01:25:06.560 --> 01:25:08.520
[Guest 1]: Never get in a car with a stranger.

01:25:08.520 --> 01:25:15.800
[Guest 1]: You know, if a stranger offers you a ride, say no and run away as quickly as you can.

01:25:15.800 --> 01:25:20.800
[Guest 1]: Now you want to make it so that anybody can stop and give you a ride just because you

01:25:20.800 --> 01:25:22.640
[Guest 1]: get a message on your phone.

01:25:22.640 --> 01:25:23.680
[Guest 1]: That's crazy.

01:25:23.680 --> 01:25:27.840
[Guest 1]: If we had had to put Uber up to a vote, Uber would never have won.

01:25:27.840 --> 01:25:28.840
[Guest 1]: Right.

01:25:28.840 --> 01:25:32.600
[Guest 1]: And there's a huge amount of innovations like that, like aspirin would never have gotten

01:25:32.600 --> 01:25:35.640
[Guest 1]: through the FDA process today.

01:25:35.640 --> 01:25:36.920
[Guest 1]: Right.

01:25:36.920 --> 01:25:44.920
[Guest 1]: And so we have collectivized decision making so much that now we have to teach people economics

01:25:44.920 --> 01:25:47.920
[Guest 1]: so that we might hope to get some decent decisions.

01:25:47.920 --> 01:25:52.840
[Guest 1]: But I would also and we should do that and I want to do that, but we should also let's

01:25:52.840 --> 01:26:00.200
[Guest 1]: leave more decisions to individual choice and the market and let's collectivize fewer

01:26:00.200 --> 01:26:01.200
[Guest 2]: decisions.

01:26:01.200 --> 01:26:05.120
[Guest 2]: But Alex, even that insight that one must collectivize fewer decisions come from having

01:26:05.120 --> 01:26:10.720
[Guest 2]: an understanding of the market that you can have, you know, in the right institutional

01:26:10.720 --> 01:26:13.160
[Guest 2]: setting, self-interest aligned with social interest.

01:26:13.160 --> 01:26:17.520
[Guest 2]: That idea itself is not intuitive to anyone outside of economics.

01:26:17.520 --> 01:26:20.320
[Amit Varma]: No, it can also come from a basic moral compass.

01:26:20.320 --> 01:26:26.080
[Amit Varma]: For example, one thing I want to kind of clarify for my listeners is that when Alex is speaking

01:26:26.080 --> 01:26:30.680
[Amit Varma]: against collectivized decision making, and I agree with him entirely, he is not saying

01:26:30.680 --> 01:26:33.820
[Amit Varma]: that an autocrat or a dictator make the decision instead.

01:26:33.820 --> 01:26:39.160
[Amit Varma]: What he is saying is leave it to individual choice, respect individual choice, and things

01:26:39.160 --> 01:26:40.400
[Amit Varma]: will work out.

01:26:40.400 --> 01:26:44.240
[Amit Varma]: Individuals can make decisions for themselves on what they want to do.

01:26:44.240 --> 01:26:48.920
[Amit Varma]: And those kinds of voluntary interaction in the marketplace can help and to give a very

01:26:48.920 --> 01:26:53.560
[Amit Varma]: brief econ 101 for people who are wondering why we are not against price gouging.

01:26:53.560 --> 01:26:57.200
[Amit Varma]: You know, what would happen if you put a price control on masks, for example, if you say

01:26:57.200 --> 01:26:59.880
[Amit Varma]: masks are important, therefore, they should not be too expensive.

01:26:59.880 --> 01:27:03.260
[Amit Varma]: Therefore, they should only be like 30 rupees each or whatever.

01:27:03.260 --> 01:27:07.400
[Amit Varma]: What would instantly happen is that your existing supply of masks would be sold out on a first

01:27:07.400 --> 01:27:10.960
[Amit Varma]: come first serve basis, leading to an immediate scarcity.

01:27:10.960 --> 01:27:16.080
[Amit Varma]: What would then further happen is that, you know, a higher price would be an incentive

01:27:16.080 --> 01:27:21.000
[Amit Varma]: to potential manufacturers to put masks out there for that evil word profit, which would

01:27:21.000 --> 01:27:24.440
[Amit Varma]: benefit everybody because your supply of masks would go up.

01:27:24.440 --> 01:27:28.280
[Amit Varma]: But that information and that incentive would no longer be there because who's going to

01:27:28.280 --> 01:27:29.760
[Amit Varma]: make mass for 30 bucks.

01:27:29.760 --> 01:27:34.440
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, even that supply would kind of not get filled up.

01:27:34.440 --> 01:27:35.440
[Guest 2]: We concur.

01:27:35.440 --> 01:27:39.480
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, so on that note of concurrence, let's take a quick commercial break.

01:27:39.480 --> 01:27:48.280
[Amit Varma]: And then when we come back, we shall go through the rest of our 84 lessons from 2020.

01:27:48.280 --> 01:27:52.400
[Amit Varma]: As many of you know, I'll soon be coming out with a four volume anthology of the seen and

01:27:52.400 --> 01:27:58.040
[Amit Varma]: the unseen books organized around the themes of politics, history, economics, and society

01:27:58.040 --> 01:27:59.040
[Amit Varma]: and culture.

