[Amit Varma]: Maybe they could solve your problem too.

01:28:52.520 --> 01:28:57.360
[Amit Varma]: Welcome back to the seen and the unseen Shruti Rajgopal and Alex Tabarrok and I are sharing

01:28:57.360 --> 01:29:03.120
[Amit Varma]: five lessons each which we learned from 2020 or which we think 2020 holds for us.

01:29:03.120 --> 01:29:05.880
[Amit Varma]: And we are through seven of them, there are eight more to go.

01:29:05.880 --> 01:29:09.680
[Amit Varma]: And of course, it's entirely natural for Shruti and Alex to do this because they are professional

01:29:09.680 --> 01:29:10.680
[Amit Varma]: educators.

01:29:10.680 --> 01:29:12.840
[Amit Varma]: I on the other hand, I'm a bit of a pretender.

01:29:12.840 --> 01:29:15.320
[Amit Varma]: So I hope you're not too bored by my lesson.

01:29:15.320 --> 01:29:18.880
[Amit Varma]: You know, since we are mixing the order up like this, I'll kind of go next because it

01:29:18.880 --> 01:29:22.760
[Amit Varma]: follows from what both of you were talking about earlier.

01:29:22.760 --> 01:29:26.480
[Amit Varma]: And it is outrageously enough given that you guys are the educators.

01:29:26.480 --> 01:29:30.680
[Amit Varma]: It's about education, but it's been something that I've been thinking about for a while.

01:29:30.680 --> 01:29:34.520
[Amit Varma]: And this lesson is not one of the standard lessons that people are learning about education

01:29:34.520 --> 01:29:39.640
[Amit Varma]: from 2020 about, you know, whether online education is good or bad or whatever.

01:29:39.640 --> 01:29:45.320
[Amit Varma]: It is just that, you know, there is like Shruti, you spoke about, you know, how one of the

01:29:45.320 --> 01:29:51.640
[Amit Varma]: things that plagues America, for example, is these outdated institutions like the FDA.

01:29:51.640 --> 01:29:56.240
[Amit Varma]: And we've also spoken before this of the anchoring effects of old normals.

01:29:56.240 --> 01:30:01.960
[Amit Varma]: And it strikes me that the way education is designed is it's a complete misfit for the

01:30:01.960 --> 01:30:02.960
[Amit Varma]: modern world.

01:30:02.960 --> 01:30:08.760
[Amit Varma]: Like our education system essentially was, uh, you know, designed in the 19th century

01:30:08.760 --> 01:30:13.760
[Amit Varma]: and all it's, you know, everything that it kind of does in the sense that you have so

01:30:13.760 --> 01:30:17.960
[Amit Varma]: many classes or standards or grades, you know, you go from class one to class 10, these are

01:30:17.960 --> 01:30:19.840
[Amit Varma]: the subjects you learn.

01:30:19.840 --> 01:30:21.800
[Amit Varma]: Everybody just goes one year at a time.

01:30:21.800 --> 01:30:26.640
[Amit Varma]: Students of the same age study together, what the subjects are, the way that they are taught,

01:30:26.640 --> 01:30:32.640
[Amit Varma]: the entire structure of, uh, that system, I think is open to questioning because, you

01:30:32.640 --> 01:30:37.560
[Amit Varma]: know, the premises that existed when that system was designed, they don't really exist

01:30:37.560 --> 01:30:41.880
[Amit Varma]: right now, you know, and we know that higher education, for example, works for signaling,

01:30:41.880 --> 01:30:46.160
[Amit Varma]: but does it work for knowledge necessarily like, you know, in India, for example, I'd

01:30:46.160 --> 01:30:49.640
[Amit Varma]: done an episode on education with Karthik Muralidharan where he said that the Indian

01:30:49.640 --> 01:30:54.560
[Amit Varma]: education system is designed to sort and not teach is good for sorting versus teaching.

01:30:54.560 --> 01:30:56.260
[Amit Varma]: We're not really teaching anything.

01:30:56.260 --> 01:31:01.120
[Amit Varma]: And this is reflected in the supply demand mismatch that yes, there is a jobs crisis,

01:31:01.120 --> 01:31:06.040
[Amit Varma]: but regardless of that, there is an issue that very often companies cannot find trained

01:31:06.040 --> 01:31:12.760
[Amit Varma]: workers while you have these tens of thousands of graduates and even PhDs who are coming

01:31:12.760 --> 01:31:17.520
[Amit Varma]: out of Indian universities who do not have the skills to do anything useful in the world,

01:31:17.520 --> 01:31:21.600
[Amit Varma]: at least not given to them by education on their own, they might pick up stuff, you know,

01:31:21.600 --> 01:31:26.080
[Amit Varma]: so you have hundreds of PhDs applying for the single vacancy of a peon.

01:31:26.080 --> 01:31:30.040
[Amit Varma]: And this alone indicates that there is, you know, a savage problem here.

01:31:30.040 --> 01:31:34.800
[Amit Varma]: And what I find is that many of the new online startups that are starting are again mimicking

01:31:34.800 --> 01:31:39.720
[Amit Varma]: this old model of education that, you know, someone like a by juices basically focusing

01:31:39.720 --> 01:31:44.280
[Amit Varma]: on what your school syllabus is and just teaching you to perform better at school.

01:31:44.280 --> 01:31:48.720
[Amit Varma]: And you know, it is few to many, by few to many, I mean, it's a few people teaching many

01:31:48.720 --> 01:31:49.720
[Amit Varma]: people.

01:31:49.720 --> 01:31:52.680
[Amit Varma]: And to me, a good market should work differently.

01:31:52.680 --> 01:31:57.800
[Amit Varma]: What I think is that over a period of time, and this is a problem to solve for young entrepreneurs

01:31:57.800 --> 01:32:02.700
[Amit Varma]: who might be listening to this, I think we need a new model that incentivizes those who

01:32:02.700 --> 01:32:06.700
[Amit Varma]: have knowledge to impart it to those who need that knowledge.

01:32:06.700 --> 01:32:11.600
[Amit Varma]: And we also therefore need to create a mechanism of filtering, anybody should be able to teach

01:32:11.600 --> 01:32:16.400
[Amit Varma]: anything if they feel they are able to, anybody should be able to kind of, you know, learn

01:32:16.400 --> 01:32:17.440
[Amit Varma]: from them.

01:32:17.440 --> 01:32:20.360
[Amit Varma]: And that's the way that we'll actually learn useful things.

01:32:20.360 --> 01:32:24.220
[Amit Varma]: Like if I might be controversial, you know, whenever I hear about these outrageous college

01:32:24.220 --> 01:32:29.360
[Amit Varma]: loans in the USA, and all this talk of forgiving them and all of that, you know, from my vantage

01:32:29.360 --> 01:32:33.520
[Amit Varma]: point in India, it just seems to me that listen, if you've there's something wrong with the

01:32:33.520 --> 01:32:38.520
[Amit Varma]: market if education is so expensive, that you have to take a loan and you cannot pay

01:32:38.520 --> 01:32:39.520
[Amit Varma]: it back.

01:32:39.520 --> 01:32:44.360
[Amit Varma]: Also, if what you are learning does not actually give you real world skills for you to earn

01:32:44.360 --> 01:32:50.240
[Amit Varma]: the money very fast, that you spent learning it, something is broken in that whole system,

01:32:50.240 --> 01:32:55.080
[Amit Varma]: and is possibly beyond my education to beyond my understanding to figure out where it is

01:32:55.080 --> 01:32:57.360
[Amit Varma]: broken and how it can be fixed.

01:32:57.360 --> 01:33:01.040
[Amit Varma]: But you know, it seems clear to me that many of these things that we take for granted that

01:33:01.040 --> 01:33:05.120
[Amit Varma]: this is how learning and education should be structured, is something that we at least

01:33:05.120 --> 01:33:06.800
[Amit Varma]: need to think about seriously.

01:33:06.800 --> 01:33:10.080
[Amit Varma]: And you guys are the professionals, so what do you feel about this?

01:33:10.080 --> 01:33:11.080
[Guest 1]: I think you're right.

01:33:11.080 --> 01:33:15.880
[Guest 1]: And I think it's much even it's a really deep, deep, deep seeded problem.

01:33:15.880 --> 01:33:17.920
[Guest 1]: Because here's the truth.

01:33:17.920 --> 01:33:21.800
[Guest 1]: The private schools are really not much better.

01:33:21.800 --> 01:33:24.600
[Guest 1]: That's the amazing thing, you know, I'll speak about the United States, but this is true

01:33:24.600 --> 01:33:25.600
[Guest 1]: for India as well.

01:33:25.600 --> 01:33:29.800
[Guest 1]: Yes, they're a little bit better about teaching, reading, writing arithmetic, you know, if

01:33:29.800 --> 01:33:33.080
[Guest 1]: you have a choice, whatever it's done in the private school.

01:33:33.080 --> 01:33:39.920
[Guest 1]: But in terms of innovation, in terms of using these new techniques, in teaching in a different

01:33:39.920 --> 01:33:45.120
[Guest 1]: way, in teaching things which are more relevant to work, the private schools are no better.

01:33:45.120 --> 01:33:51.240
[Guest 1]: So this is the case, I think, where something is so deep seeded, that the market, you know,

01:33:51.240 --> 01:33:53.220
[Guest 1]: hasn't solved this problem.

01:33:53.220 --> 01:33:57.000
[Guest 1]: Let me just give you a few examples, which have occurred to me, is like something I think

01:33:57.000 --> 01:34:01.940
[Guest 1]: schools should teach is like memorization techniques, right?

01:34:01.940 --> 01:34:05.680
[Guest 1]: This is probably something, Amit, you got from playing cards, right?

01:34:05.680 --> 01:34:09.800
[Guest 1]: It's extremely useful to know, you know, what's on the deck, right?

01:34:09.800 --> 01:34:11.980
[Guest 1]: What's on the table.

01:34:11.980 --> 01:34:16.520
[Guest 1]: And there are techniques which people can use, you know, memory palaces, and so forth,

01:34:16.520 --> 01:34:22.720
[Guest 1]: to vastly increase their ability to learn and retain material.

01:34:22.720 --> 01:34:27.360
[Guest 1]: And yet nowhere is this kind of stuff taught, or fast math, right?

01:34:27.360 --> 01:34:33.520
[Guest 1]: There are techniques to quickly multiply numbers and so forth, which can be taught.

01:34:33.520 --> 01:34:35.880
[Guest 1]: But schools don't teach this stuff.

01:34:35.880 --> 01:34:36.920
[Guest 1]: And like, why?

01:34:36.920 --> 01:34:43.600
[Guest 1]: Why isn't there even just a few places which, you know, take a radically different approach?

01:34:43.600 --> 01:34:45.960
[Guest 1]: It's very puzzling to me.

01:34:45.960 --> 01:34:50.280
[Guest 1]: Part of it, I think, is that we say schooling is about education.

01:34:50.280 --> 01:34:55.560
[Guest 1]: But what we see is, obviously, it's actually a lot of it is about warehousing, right?

01:34:55.560 --> 01:34:58.880
[Guest 1]: The parents don't want to look after the kids, right?

01:34:58.880 --> 01:35:02.000
[Guest 1]: And we see a lot of complaints about that right now, right?

01:35:02.000 --> 01:35:05.040
[Guest 1]: People are complaining, you know, I can't go to work.

01:35:05.040 --> 01:35:07.680
[Guest 1]: This is much more difficult for me, you know.

01:35:07.680 --> 01:35:09.560
[Guest 1]: And I'm not discounting those complaints.

01:35:09.560 --> 01:35:12.380
[Guest 1]: It is difficult to have kids at home all the time.

01:35:12.380 --> 01:35:17.040
[Guest 1]: But a lot of what schooling does is just take the kids off the parents' hands for a while.

01:35:17.040 --> 01:35:21.680
[Guest 1]: So the demanders are not as much interested in education as you might imagine.

01:35:21.680 --> 01:35:28.840
[Guest 1]: But still, it is puzzling to me, Amit, why we don't see more radical experimentation

01:35:28.840 --> 01:35:32.600
[Guest 1]: and innovation in teaching and education.

01:35:32.600 --> 01:35:38.960
[Guest 2]: You know, speaking of learning useless things, I got an incredible education, I mean, compared

01:35:38.960 --> 01:35:42.800
[Guest 2]: to 99% of Indians or maybe even more, right?

01:35:42.800 --> 01:35:47.240
[Guest 2]: But I went to an all-girls, you know, Catholic-run, missionary-run school.

01:35:47.240 --> 01:35:48.880
[Guest 2]: And I know how to knit.

01:35:48.880 --> 01:35:49.960
[Guest 2]: I know how to sew.

01:35:49.960 --> 01:35:51.160
[Guest 2]: I know how to crochet.

01:35:51.160 --> 01:35:53.040
[Guest 2]: I know how to bake, right?

01:35:53.040 --> 01:35:58.280
[Guest 2]: I could have sewn my own masks if the price was high enough and, you know, didn't surpass

01:35:58.280 --> 01:36:00.480
[Guest 2]: my wages as an economist.

01:36:00.480 --> 01:36:03.120
[Guest 2]: But I don't know how to code.

01:36:03.120 --> 01:36:08.040
[Guest 2]: Because they were, you know, teaching us how to fold napkins and knit and turning us into

01:36:08.040 --> 01:36:13.120
[Guest 2]: very well-educated, upper-class, elite housewives at some level, right?

01:36:13.120 --> 01:36:16.080
[Guest 2]: So my job was to raise kids and knit their mittens.

01:36:16.080 --> 01:36:20.320
[Guest 2]: It was not to know coding so that one day I can use Python to make graphs.

01:36:20.320 --> 01:36:21.640
[Guest 2]: I still don't know how to do that.

01:36:21.640 --> 01:36:24.840
[Guest 2]: I asked my research assistants to do it for me, right?

01:36:24.840 --> 01:36:28.760
[Guest 2]: These young kids who just knew, who grew up coding, who just like do things 10 times faster

01:36:28.760 --> 01:36:30.440
[Guest 2]: than I do them.

01:36:30.440 --> 01:36:36.200
[Guest 2]: So there is, and I'm not that old, boys who are my counterparts in my generation were

01:36:36.200 --> 01:36:38.360
[Guest 2]: taught how to code, right?

01:36:38.360 --> 01:36:44.160
[Guest 2]: So first, I think there is this sense of, you know, this version of what kind of education

01:36:44.160 --> 01:36:46.120
[Guest 2]: anyone needs, right?

01:36:46.120 --> 01:36:50.400
[Guest 2]: There's this one size fits all, very centralized model.

01:36:50.400 --> 01:36:52.960
[Guest 2]: If you're rich, you must need this kind of an education.

01:36:52.960 --> 01:36:56.360
[Guest 2]: If you're female, you must be educated in this way, right?

01:36:56.360 --> 01:36:58.640
[Guest 2]: If you want a great job, you must be educated in English.

01:36:58.640 --> 01:37:02.920
[Guest 2]: And, you know, we have all these, you know, very standard methods of thinking about it.

01:37:02.920 --> 01:37:07.160
[Guest 2]: So in India, the problem is complicated by the fact that we have like complete state

01:37:07.160 --> 01:37:09.360
[Guest 2]: capture on curriculum, right?

01:37:09.360 --> 01:37:13.840
[Guest 2]: So if in a marketplace, we might have had a little bit more, you know, experimentation

01:37:13.840 --> 01:37:16.480
[Guest 2]: in the state, it's just, you know, dead, right?

01:37:16.480 --> 01:37:21.240
[Guest 2]: They can barely master teaching kids, you know, numeracy and literacy, let alone experiment

01:37:21.240 --> 01:37:24.800
[Guest 2]: in any way possible on other margins.

01:37:24.800 --> 01:37:28.920
[Guest 2]: So I think one part of it is centralization, you know, one is, of course, centralization

01:37:28.920 --> 01:37:30.160
[Guest 2]: by the state.

01:37:30.160 --> 01:37:34.160
[Guest 2]: But there's also like this kind of group think in society, you know, they want all schools

01:37:34.160 --> 01:37:36.480
[Guest 2]: to teach the same thing, right?

01:37:36.480 --> 01:37:40.440
[Guest 2]: Because they think that's fair, it'll be all kids will get the same stuff.

01:37:40.440 --> 01:37:43.560
[Guest 2]: Of course, they're not going to get the same stuff, right?

01:37:43.560 --> 01:37:48.040
[Guest 2]: Economics are going to determine, right, IQ and parents income are going to determine

01:37:48.040 --> 01:37:53.480
[Guest 2]: 90% of their lifetime and future outcomes, believe, you know, as unfair as that sounds.

01:37:53.480 --> 01:37:57.200
[Guest 2]: So the birth lottery is why I do everything that I do, right?

01:37:57.200 --> 01:38:02.480
[Guest 2]: The reasons I can't do some of the things that I learned how to knit, instead of code.

01:38:02.480 --> 01:38:03.920
[Guest 2]: So I think there's that problem.

01:38:03.920 --> 01:38:09.180
[Guest 2]: And we haven't quite figured out that we don't need this overly centralized system either

01:38:09.180 --> 01:38:12.120
[Guest 2]: imposed socially, or imposed by the government.

01:38:12.120 --> 01:38:18.160
[Guest 2]: And America is not that much different, you know, in one sense, our colleague, Judy, and

01:38:18.160 --> 01:38:23.600
[Guest 1]: I know our friend, Brian Kaplan, has he been on the podcast?

01:38:23.600 --> 01:38:24.600
[Amit Varma]: Not yet.

01:38:24.600 --> 01:38:28.240
[Amit Varma]: But he should have inviting him because he has these incredible counterintuitive insights,

01:38:28.240 --> 01:38:32.760
[Guest 1]: which always make me kind of sit back and think, yeah, yeah, he's very good.

01:38:32.760 --> 01:38:36.680
[Guest 1]: He has two twins who are extremely studious.

01:38:36.680 --> 01:38:42.120
[Guest 1]: Oh, yeah, and not so much interested in sports or things like this.

01:38:42.120 --> 01:38:47.200
[Guest 1]: And he went around to a bunch of private schools and said, you know, here, my kids, look, they

01:38:47.200 --> 01:38:48.200
[Guest 1]: don't want to do art.

01:38:48.200 --> 01:38:49.200
[Guest 1]: They don't like it.

01:38:49.200 --> 01:38:50.200
[Guest 1]: They don't want to do sports.

01:38:50.200 --> 01:38:51.720
[Guest 1]: They don't like it.

01:38:51.720 --> 01:38:54.360
[Guest 1]: Can you just teach them some more mathematics?

01:38:54.360 --> 01:38:58.320
[Guest 1]: And the private schools were, oh, oh, no, no, no, no, no, no.

01:38:58.320 --> 01:39:02.400
[Guest 1]: We teach the whole kid, you know, we are holistic.

01:39:02.400 --> 01:39:03.800
[Guest 1]: We could never do that.

01:39:03.800 --> 01:39:08.640
[Guest 1]: You know, it's very important that we round them out, blah, blah, blah, blah, blah, blah.

01:39:08.640 --> 01:39:13.120
[Guest 1]: So we ended up homeschooling them, actually home office schooling them.

01:39:13.120 --> 01:39:18.040
[Guest 1]: They were schooled literally in the office across the hall from me.

01:39:18.040 --> 01:39:21.120
[Guest 2]: And they're well-rounded, they're intellectually well-rounded.

01:39:21.120 --> 01:39:26.920
[Guest 2]: They may not know how to run, you know, whatever your PT exercises or some nonsense like that.

01:39:26.920 --> 01:39:28.960
[Guest 2]: But they are very well-rounded kids.

01:39:28.960 --> 01:39:29.960
[Guest 2]: I've seen them.

01:39:29.960 --> 01:39:32.120
[Guest 2]: I mean, they were pretty young when I was in graduate school.

01:39:32.120 --> 01:39:33.120
[Guest 2]: They must have been middle school.

01:39:33.120 --> 01:39:35.800
[Guest 2]: But then they were pretty well-rounded then.

01:39:35.800 --> 01:39:41.280
[Guest 1]: They have their first publication already as 18-year-olds.

01:39:41.280 --> 01:39:42.280
[Guest 1]: Wow.

01:39:42.280 --> 01:39:43.280
[Guest 1]: Yeah.

01:39:43.280 --> 01:39:44.280
[Guest 1]: Anyway, it's great.

01:39:44.280 --> 01:39:51.280
[Guest 1]: But my point is that even in this private marketplace, he could not get a deviation

01:39:51.280 --> 01:39:55.600
[Guest 1]: from even, you know, even a simple one, even when he was willing to pay.

01:39:55.600 --> 01:39:56.600
[Guest 1]: Right.

01:39:56.600 --> 01:39:57.600
[Guest 1]: I mean, private schools are not cheap.

01:39:57.600 --> 01:40:03.520
[Guest 1]: So here he is willing to give a private school, you know, tens of thousands of dollars, right,

01:40:03.520 --> 01:40:05.440
[Guest 1]: to educate his kids.

01:40:05.440 --> 01:40:08.640
[Guest 1]: And they could not deviate from the lesson plan.

01:40:08.640 --> 01:40:15.080
[Guest 1]: So there's something about education, which is just, I don't understand it, actually.

01:40:15.080 --> 01:40:22.680
[Guest 1]: But it's just very difficult to innovate and to break into the social, to change the social

01:40:22.680 --> 01:40:23.680
[Guest 1]: dynamic.

01:40:23.680 --> 01:40:30.280
[Guest 1]: And let alone, of course, we have all the problems with state intervention and not having

01:40:30.280 --> 01:40:31.280
[Guest 1]: a market.

01:40:31.280 --> 01:40:33.320
[Guest 1]: But even in the market, it's less than I would have expected.

01:40:33.320 --> 01:40:35.520
[Guest 2]: You know, one personal anecdote here.

01:40:35.520 --> 01:40:41.560
[Guest 2]: When I was about eight years old, my dad had to go on a fellowship to the Netherlands.

01:40:41.560 --> 01:40:42.560
[Guest 2]: Right.

01:40:42.560 --> 01:40:43.720
[Guest 2]: And this was something related to work.

01:40:43.720 --> 01:40:46.260
[Guest 2]: He had to spend seven or eight months in Netherlands.

01:40:46.260 --> 01:40:51.200
[Guest 2]: My mother, who's a musician, was simultaneously invited to give a number of concerts, you know,

01:40:51.200 --> 01:40:53.000
[Guest 2]: all across Europe.

01:40:53.000 --> 01:40:54.820
[Guest 2]: And my parents were like, amazing.

01:40:54.820 --> 01:40:55.820
[Guest 2]: They were troopers.

01:40:55.820 --> 01:40:58.240
[Guest 2]: My mother at that time was about the age I am right now.

01:40:58.240 --> 01:41:04.040
[Guest 2]: So, you know, more credit to her at this age, I'm able to appreciate her decision so much

01:41:04.040 --> 01:41:05.040
[Guest 2]: more.

01:41:05.040 --> 01:41:08.400
[Guest 2]: They could have left their kids with the grandparents and just taken off and spent eight months in

01:41:08.400 --> 01:41:09.400
[Guest 2]: Europe.

01:41:09.400 --> 01:41:10.400
[Guest 2]: And they said, no, we'll take the kids.

01:41:10.400 --> 01:41:12.040
[Guest 2]: I have no idea why.

01:41:12.040 --> 01:41:14.100
[Guest 2]: And they just yanked me and my sister out of school.

01:41:14.100 --> 01:41:16.720
[Guest 2]: My sister was 11 at the time.

01:41:16.720 --> 01:41:19.320
[Guest 2]: And we thought we were going to go to school in the Netherlands.

01:41:19.320 --> 01:41:20.320
[Guest 2]: Right.

01:41:20.320 --> 01:41:23.800
[Guest 2]: And we were so excited about it because they don't have school uniforms.

01:41:23.800 --> 01:41:27.560
[Guest 2]: They have cafeterias and lockers, you know, it looks like a school out of Archie Comics

01:41:27.560 --> 01:41:28.560
[Guest 2]: or something like that.

01:41:28.560 --> 01:41:33.480
[Guest 2]: And my sister and I were like over the moon that we might get to go to school there.

01:41:33.480 --> 01:41:35.880
[Guest 2]: And my parents said, why do you want to go to go to school?

01:41:35.880 --> 01:41:38.860
[Guest 2]: You learn more traveling across Europe with us.

01:41:38.860 --> 01:41:40.320
[Guest 2]: And we thought they're insane.

01:41:40.320 --> 01:41:41.320
[Guest 2]: Everyone.

01:41:41.320 --> 01:41:46.440
[Guest 2]: My parents thought they were insane, yanking kids out of school for eight months.

01:41:46.440 --> 01:41:48.640
[Guest 2]: We just toured with my mom.

01:41:48.640 --> 01:41:49.640
[Guest 2]: That's it.

01:41:49.640 --> 01:41:52.800
[Guest 2]: You know, I've toured like all over Western Europe.

01:41:52.800 --> 01:41:53.800
[Guest 2]: We just went.

01:41:53.800 --> 01:41:58.240
[Guest 2]: My mother was the opening act for a big, you know, Rupert follow up act.

01:41:58.240 --> 01:42:00.040
[Guest 2]: And I've toured France for 31 days.

01:42:00.040 --> 01:42:01.560
[Guest 2]: I've been to villages in France.

01:42:01.560 --> 01:42:03.160
[Guest 2]: Normal people haven't been to.

01:42:03.160 --> 01:42:07.080
[Guest 2]: But the education I got as an eight year old was the Vienna Symphony is different from

01:42:07.080 --> 01:42:08.080
[Guest 2]: the Lund Philharmonic.

01:42:08.080 --> 01:42:09.080
[Guest 2]: Right.

01:42:09.080 --> 01:42:12.080
[Guest 2]: That's it's a different kind of education, but it's the kind of education you get when

01:42:12.080 --> 01:42:14.920
[Guest 2]: you travel and you see the world and you're with your parents.

01:42:14.920 --> 01:42:19.800
[Guest 2]: And we came back and my parents just hired a tutor for us to like quickly pass the final

01:42:19.800 --> 01:42:20.800
[Guest 2]: exams.

01:42:20.800 --> 01:42:22.600
[Guest 2]: And we went on to the next grade.

01:42:22.600 --> 01:42:24.760
[Guest 2]: And that was the end of that.

01:42:24.760 --> 01:42:29.200
[Guest 2]: And nobody, you know, if my parents had been in India and they had yanked us out of school

01:42:29.200 --> 01:42:32.800
[Guest 2]: to maybe travel across India, like that, that would have been the end of it.

01:42:32.800 --> 01:42:34.760
[Guest 2]: Like, I think there would have been a family intervention.

01:42:34.760 --> 01:42:37.760
[Guest 2]: They would have come and told my parents that we're taking your kids away.

01:42:37.760 --> 01:42:39.440
[Guest 2]: You're terrible parents.

01:42:39.440 --> 01:42:41.640
[Guest 2]: You have no idea what you're doing.

01:42:41.640 --> 01:42:45.880
[Guest 2]: You're going to ruin their lives because they didn't learn like 12 times table or whatever.

01:42:45.880 --> 01:42:50.600
[Guest 2]: And it's the amount of social pressure to get a particular kind of schooling for all

01:42:50.600 --> 01:42:54.040
[Guest 2]: kids to get, you know, you know, all the typical right.

01:42:54.040 --> 01:42:56.880
[Guest 2]: In addition to schooling, you should learn a musical instrument.

01:42:56.880 --> 01:42:57.880
[Guest 2]: You should learn karate.

01:42:57.880 --> 01:42:58.880
[Guest 2]: You should learn a foreign language.

01:42:58.880 --> 01:43:04.640
[Guest 2]: I mean, these kids who learn the foreign language can't even order like food in French.

01:43:04.640 --> 01:43:05.640
[Guest 2]: Right.

01:43:05.640 --> 01:43:08.000
[Guest 2]: It's just completely useless information.

01:43:08.000 --> 01:43:11.400
[Guest 2]: My foreign language was Sanskrit, which is still foreign to me.

01:43:11.400 --> 01:43:14.480
[Guest 2]: So it's just like there's some system we've come up with.

01:43:14.480 --> 01:43:18.240
[Guest 2]: I have no idea when it might have ever been useful.

01:43:18.240 --> 01:43:20.200
[Guest 2]: It's certainly not useful today.

01:43:20.200 --> 01:43:24.320
[Guest 2]: And not only do we not have experimentation, anyone willing to experiment like Brian or

01:43:24.320 --> 01:43:27.160
[Guest 2]: my parents, they are punished for it.

01:43:27.160 --> 01:43:30.520
[Guest 2]: You know, like there is just outrageous amount of social sanction.

01:43:30.520 --> 01:43:35.320
[Guest 2]: I, I don't imagine a lot of people outside of, you know, Carroll Hall support Brian's

01:43:35.320 --> 01:43:40.800
[Guest 2]: choice to homeschool the kids or someone who knows the kids well, who know the twins well,

01:43:40.800 --> 01:43:41.960
[Guest 2]: they might support that choice.

01:43:41.960 --> 01:43:45.320
[Guest 2]: But everyone else will just think like these are insane parents.

01:43:45.320 --> 01:43:48.840
[Guest 2]: And homeschoolers in the United States are typically vilified.

01:43:48.840 --> 01:43:49.840
[Guest 2]: Right.

01:43:49.840 --> 01:43:53.520
[Guest 2]: They say you want to homeschool your kids because of religious education or something,

01:43:53.520 --> 01:43:54.520
[Guest 2]: something like that.

01:43:54.520 --> 01:43:55.520
[Guest 2]: Right.

01:43:55.520 --> 01:43:59.480
[Guest 2]: Because you don't want them to read Darwin or whatever the latest thing, political thing

01:43:59.480 --> 01:44:00.480
[Guest 2]: is.

01:44:00.480 --> 01:44:02.400
[Guest 2]: So it's mired in a lot of these things.

01:44:02.400 --> 01:44:05.800
[Guest 2]: I have no answers on how to break out of it.

01:44:05.800 --> 01:44:10.960
[Guest 2]: I thought the big MOOCs, you know, the Khan Academy and things like MRU, of course, which

01:44:10.960 --> 01:44:12.800
[Guest 2]: is very much more niche.

01:44:12.800 --> 01:44:18.400
[Guest 2]: I thought that might have picked up a bigger movement in homeschooling because it used

01:44:18.400 --> 01:44:24.360
[Guest 2]: to be so costly to exit the state, you know, so on that margin, a lot of the costs of exiting

01:44:24.360 --> 01:44:28.320
[Guest 2]: the state school system or the social schooling system have reduced.

01:44:28.320 --> 01:44:32.160
[Guest 2]: And I imagined a bigger exodus than what actually happened.

01:44:32.160 --> 01:44:37.840
[Guest 2]: But my sense is it's because of what Alex said, which is schools are acting like warehouses,

01:44:37.840 --> 01:44:40.640
[Guest 2]: you know, where you put your kids for six hours so that you can get your work done because

01:44:40.640 --> 01:44:44.360
[Guest 2]: we can't afford nannies and we don't have grandparents in the United States and, you

01:44:44.360 --> 01:44:45.920
[Guest 2]: know, those kinds of things.

01:44:45.920 --> 01:44:47.560
[Guest 2]: I was also raised by my grandparents.

01:44:47.560 --> 01:44:51.200
[Guest 2]: So, you know, I mean, if Khan Academy was better, I can imagine my parents just putting

01:44:51.200 --> 01:44:55.160
[Guest 2]: me in front of Khan Academy and doing whatever they needed to do.

01:44:55.160 --> 01:44:56.520
[Guest 2]: They might have been experimental.

01:44:56.520 --> 01:45:00.400
[Guest 2]: So I think there are multiple things going on.

01:45:00.400 --> 01:45:02.240
[Guest 2]: Immigration can solve the warehousing problem.

01:45:02.240 --> 01:45:05.560
[Guest 2]: We're very bad on immigration in the United States.

01:45:05.560 --> 01:45:06.560
[Guest 2]: Right.

01:45:06.560 --> 01:45:12.360
[Guest 2]: You could have a lot of people from poorer countries who know how to raise kids really

01:45:12.360 --> 01:45:13.360
[Guest 2]: well.

01:45:13.360 --> 01:45:14.360
[Guest 2]: Right.

01:45:14.360 --> 01:45:17.480
[Guest 2]: Happy, well-rounded kids who are kind, good people.

01:45:17.480 --> 01:45:23.000
[Guest 2]: They could be helping you raise your kids instead of warehousing them in a jail, a centralized

01:45:23.000 --> 01:45:25.920
[Guest 2]: jail system wearing masks right now.

01:45:25.920 --> 01:45:29.480
[Guest 2]: But that's not an option on the table because of bad immigration laws.

01:45:29.480 --> 01:45:32.000
[Guest 2]: So it's not, I think, one thing that solves it.

01:45:32.000 --> 01:45:33.720
[Guest 2]: It's not just the politics of education.

01:45:33.720 --> 01:45:36.960
[Guest 2]: I think it's so many things about education.

01:45:36.960 --> 01:45:38.360
[Guest 2]: It's our notion of fairness.

01:45:38.360 --> 01:45:41.480
[Guest 2]: It's our notion of how children must be raised, where they must go.

01:45:41.480 --> 01:45:42.840
[Guest 2]: No one should be left out.

01:45:42.840 --> 01:45:43.840
[Guest 2]: No one should be left behind.

01:45:43.840 --> 01:45:47.000
[Guest 2]: You know, all of those things mired in one.

01:45:47.000 --> 01:45:50.920
[Amit Varma]: And I guess, you know, the fact that so many people homeschool at all tells you that the

01:45:50.920 --> 01:45:55.000
[Amit Varma]: system is broken because homeschooling doesn't really make rational sense from a comparative

01:45:55.000 --> 01:45:56.480
[Amit Varma]: advantage point of view.

01:45:56.480 --> 01:46:00.020
[Amit Varma]: You're better off outsourcing that and just focusing on what you do.

01:46:00.020 --> 01:46:03.920
[Amit Varma]: But the fact that so many parents who obviously care about the kids feel the need to do that

01:46:03.920 --> 01:46:05.400
[Amit Varma]: is itself indicative.

01:46:05.400 --> 01:46:09.440
[Amit Varma]: And I've often, you know, amused at putting, you know, with other people, putting together

01:46:09.440 --> 01:46:13.400
[Amit Varma]: a sort of a course called life lessons, which teaches you all the basic things we should

01:46:13.400 --> 01:46:18.720
[Amit Varma]: be taught in education, but aren't taught, for example, econ 101, you know, probabilistic

01:46:18.720 --> 01:46:25.580
[Amit Varma]: thinking, how the brain works, communication, how to code, you know, like Alex said, memorization

01:46:25.580 --> 01:46:28.960
[Amit Varma]: techniques or knowledge management, all of those things.

01:46:28.960 --> 01:46:29.960
[Amit Varma]: Financial literacy.

01:46:29.960 --> 01:46:30.960
[Guest 2]: Yeah.

01:46:30.960 --> 01:46:31.960
[Guest 2]: Financial literacy.

01:46:31.960 --> 01:46:33.040
[Guest 2]: We are terrible at in the United States.

01:46:33.040 --> 01:46:35.840
[Guest 2]: I have college kids who don't know how to balance a checkbook.

01:46:35.840 --> 01:46:40.640
[Guest 2]: I mean, they don't know what that means, you know, to have to manage their own money and

01:46:40.640 --> 01:46:45.760
[Guest 2]: how compound interest works when they are, there's a massive amount of student debt because

01:46:45.760 --> 01:46:49.000
[Guest 2]: they have no conception of how big this is going to get.

01:46:49.000 --> 01:46:50.000
[Guest 2]: Right.

01:46:50.000 --> 01:46:54.080
[Guest 2]: So compound interest is magical when you're an investor, right?

01:46:54.080 --> 01:46:56.960
[Guest 2]: It's the devil for when you're a student in debt.

01:46:56.960 --> 01:47:01.640
[Guest 2]: So just explaining those numbers to them, I mean, they need to even putting it in the

01:47:01.640 --> 01:47:03.000
[Guest 2]: compound interest calculator.

01:47:03.000 --> 01:47:08.600
[Guest 2]: It doesn't quite process until they see the, you know, the exponential curve of how much

01:47:08.600 --> 01:47:11.440
[Guest 2]: they're going to have to pay the longer they have this going.

01:47:11.440 --> 01:47:12.440
[Guest 2]: It's really hard.

01:47:12.440 --> 01:47:16.440
[Guest 2]: The financial literacy part is one of the reasons we have such terrible levels of student

01:47:16.440 --> 01:47:17.440
[Guest 2]: debt.

01:47:17.440 --> 01:47:21.080
[Amit Varma]: Let's move on now to Alex's third lesson of the day.

01:47:21.080 --> 01:47:22.080
[Guest 1]: Okay.

01:47:22.080 --> 01:47:27.920
[Guest 1]: So, you know, I'm going to now sort of contradict myself a little better because, you know,

01:47:27.920 --> 01:47:33.680
[Guest 1]: you had Shruti and I on earlier and we talked about state capacity and India kind of as

01:47:33.680 --> 01:47:36.500
[Guest 1]: a flailing state.

01:47:36.500 --> 01:47:40.640
[Guest 1]: And I've changed my mind a little bit in the following sense is that at the beginning of

01:47:40.640 --> 01:47:46.780
[Guest 1]: the pandemic, I thought the U.S. will, it'll be bad, but it'll probably be okay.

01:47:46.780 --> 01:47:54.040
[Guest 1]: But I was very worried about India because already lots of pollution, lots of comorbidities,

01:47:54.040 --> 01:47:58.600
[Guest 1]: I didn't, flailing state, you know, I was very, very concerned with India.

01:47:58.600 --> 01:48:03.880
[Guest 1]: And in fact, what we know is that it's been much worse in the United States than in India.

01:48:03.880 --> 01:48:06.640
[Guest 1]: India has done, has made mistakes, a lot of mistakes.

01:48:06.640 --> 01:48:08.120
[Guest 1]: We can talk about that.

01:48:08.120 --> 01:48:13.000
[Guest 1]: But India certainly has not done worse than the United States.

01:48:13.000 --> 01:48:17.680
[Guest 1]: And so I'm less focused now on state capacity.

01:48:17.680 --> 01:48:22.080
[Guest 1]: And then on what my colleague, Brian Kaplan, who was always somewhat skeptical about state

01:48:22.080 --> 01:48:26.240
[Guest 1]: capacity, he calls state will, right?

01:48:26.240 --> 01:48:34.640
[Guest 1]: And states have a lot of untapped power, which they can use, and sometimes they do, and sometimes

01:48:34.640 --> 01:48:36.180
[Guest 1]: they choose not to.

01:48:36.180 --> 01:48:42.040
[Guest 1]: So a lot of what happened in the United States, you could say it's low state capacity, but

01:48:42.040 --> 01:48:45.320
[Guest 1]: actually it's probably just low state will.

01:48:45.320 --> 01:48:51.280
[Guest 1]: The Trump administration in particular, but for a whole variety of reasons of complacency

01:48:51.280 --> 01:48:57.000
[Guest 1]: and regulation and so forth, we just did not have the will.

01:48:57.000 --> 01:49:03.440
[Guest 1]: You know, we just did not summon the will to do radical things, to make big, big steps,

01:49:03.440 --> 01:49:05.440
[Guest 1]: to make big changes.

01:49:05.440 --> 01:49:07.240
[Guest 1]: And India did.

01:49:07.240 --> 01:49:12.200
[Guest 1]: So, you know, again, I'm not supportive of this, but India had the, you know, the biggest

01:49:12.200 --> 01:49:13.200
[Guest 1]: lockdown.

01:49:13.200 --> 01:49:17.760
[Guest 1]: India had capacity, India showed will, India made big moves.

01:49:17.760 --> 01:49:22.560
[Guest 1]: So this idea of state capacity, I've sort of downgraded it a little bit in favor of

01:49:22.560 --> 01:49:23.560
[Guest 1]: kind of state will.

01:49:23.560 --> 01:49:29.680
[Guest 1]: And I don't always understand why some states, they have the will to make these big moves,

01:49:29.680 --> 01:49:30.920
[Guest 1]: make these big changes.

01:49:30.920 --> 01:49:35.600
[Guest 1]: China, for example, you know, has vaccinated more than a million people.

01:49:35.600 --> 01:49:40.800
[Guest 1]: China did what you would think the United States would have done, you know, 50 years

01:49:40.800 --> 01:49:41.800
[Guest 1]: ago.

01:49:41.800 --> 01:49:44.800
[Guest 1]: They said, well, we're going to create a vaccine and we're going to start giving it out to

01:49:44.800 --> 01:49:48.720
[Guest 1]: people even before we've gone through all the trials.

01:49:48.720 --> 01:49:54.320
[Guest 1]: So China did a lot, a lot of capacity, a lot of action, but also a lot of will.

01:49:54.320 --> 01:49:59.400
[Guest 1]: And the United States, you know, I spoke with people in Congress and they would just, well,

01:49:59.400 --> 01:50:02.560
[Guest 1]: it's the next, we have to wait till the next session.

01:50:02.560 --> 01:50:03.560
[Guest 1]: Things are slow.

01:50:03.560 --> 01:50:07.680
[Guest 1]: We have to get agreement and, you know, there just wasn't the will there.

01:50:07.680 --> 01:50:16.280
[Guest 1]: And it's odd because when we were attacked on 9-11, massive willpower, right?

01:50:16.280 --> 01:50:21.960
[Guest 1]: I mean, there was no question that we were going to fight back and we were going to attack

01:50:21.960 --> 01:50:24.960
[Guest 1]: whoever, the wrong people.

01:50:24.960 --> 01:50:33.240
[Guest 1]: But yeah, I mean, but we had troops in Afghanistan, we had troops in Iraq, and we had just a massive,

01:50:33.240 --> 01:50:36.120
[Guest 1]: massive, we'd spent trillions of dollars, okay?

01:50:36.120 --> 01:50:40.640
[Guest 1]: We're still spending huge amounts of money fighting these crazy wars.

01:50:40.640 --> 01:50:44.520
[Guest 1]: I mean, it was, we did the wrong thing, but there was no question when we were attacked

01:50:44.520 --> 01:50:48.440
[Guest 1]: on 9-11 that the United States would respond, okay?

01:50:48.440 --> 01:50:54.320
[Guest 1]: And yet today we have a 9-11 every single day, every single day right now, more people

01:50:54.320 --> 01:51:01.960
[Guest 1]: are dying than in 9-11 and people, there's no action in government and there's no even

01:51:01.960 --> 01:51:04.080
[Guest 1]: action among the people, right?

01:51:04.080 --> 01:51:09.480
[Guest 1]: You know, I'm concerned, Shruti is concerned, but like where are the people rising in the

01:51:09.480 --> 01:51:16.600
[Guest 1]: streets demanding that people stop dying in nursing homes?

01:51:16.600 --> 01:51:20.880
[Guest 1]: We are nine months, ten months into the crisis and the nursing homes are still where people

01:51:20.880 --> 01:51:23.160
[Guest 1]: are dying and we're not protecting them.

01:51:23.160 --> 01:51:27.760
[Guest 1]: You know, in World War II, people sent their kids to the countryside.

01:51:27.760 --> 01:51:33.920
[Guest 1]: You know, my father-in-law was sent from Holland, he was sent to England, you know, as a young

01:51:33.920 --> 01:51:35.000
[Guest 1]: child.

01:51:35.000 --> 01:51:39.000
[Guest 1]: His parents said, it's too dangerous here, we're going to send you, we have no idea exactly

01:51:39.000 --> 01:51:41.040
[Guest 1]: where you're going, right?

01:51:41.040 --> 01:51:46.720
[Guest 1]: We're going to send you off to the countryside in England to kind of protect you, right?

01:51:46.720 --> 01:51:50.520
[Guest 1]: And yet today we cannot protect people in our nursing homes.

01:51:50.520 --> 01:51:56.080
[Guest 1]: And I don't understand why, I don't understand why in some cases this triggers some part

01:51:56.080 --> 01:51:59.040
[Guest 1]: of our brain, oh, we've been attacked, we must fight back.

01:51:59.040 --> 01:52:02.800
[Guest 1]: And yet when the virus attacks us, we don't fight back.

01:52:02.800 --> 01:52:04.280
[Guest 1]: This is puzzling to me.

01:52:04.280 --> 01:52:09.440
[Guest 1]: And it's to do with this, it also has this question of state capacity versus state will.

01:52:09.440 --> 01:52:14.600
[Guest 1]: And I think state will seems to be more powerful than I had thought previously.

01:52:14.600 --> 01:52:18.160
[Amit Varma]: So a couple of thoughts, which are also kind of questions.

01:52:18.160 --> 01:52:22.240
[Amit Varma]: One is, could it be the case that, you know, in terms of 9-11, what's happening is much

01:52:22.240 --> 01:52:23.360
[Amit Varma]: more visible.

01:52:23.360 --> 01:52:27.480
[Amit Varma]: You watch it on television and you see those flaming towers and, you know, it's much more

01:52:27.480 --> 01:52:30.520
[Amit Varma]: visible and therefore the reaction is much more visceral.

01:52:30.520 --> 01:52:36.040
[Amit Varma]: And also the enemy is identifiable, you know, it is that bunch of specific people who have

01:52:36.040 --> 01:52:41.080
[Amit Varma]: photographs and all that, the virus in that sense is kind of much more abstract.

01:52:41.080 --> 01:52:45.500
[Amit Varma]: And as far as, you know, state will is concerned as against state capacity, and I'm just thinking

01:52:45.500 --> 01:52:51.400
[Amit Varma]: aloud here, would it be the case that for a politician, action will always carry more

01:52:51.400 --> 01:52:56.560
[Amit Varma]: costs than inaction, because when you do something, you can cause something bad to happen.

01:52:56.560 --> 01:53:00.200
[Amit Varma]: But if you just stay with the status quo, when you don't do anything, at least you didn't

01:53:00.200 --> 01:53:02.560
[Amit Varma]: cause the bad thing to happen, you know.

01:53:02.560 --> 01:53:08.840
[Amit Varma]: So is that therefore inherently a bias towards inaction built in for politicians and the

01:53:08.840 --> 01:53:09.840
[Guest 1]: state?

01:53:09.840 --> 01:53:10.840
[Guest 1]: You would have thought that.

01:53:10.840 --> 01:53:15.560
[Guest 1]: And yet, you know, we sent troops to, as I said, to Afghanistan and Iraq, which is mired

01:53:15.560 --> 01:53:19.560
[Guest 1]: us in now the longest war in US history.

01:53:19.560 --> 01:53:22.120
[Guest 1]: And so there the bias was towards action, right?

01:53:22.120 --> 01:53:27.120
[Guest 1]: And sometimes, so I don't always understand, like, why is it in some cases we are very

01:53:27.120 --> 01:53:34.280
[Guest 1]: quick to act, even foolishly quick, and, you know, demonetization in India and also, you

01:53:34.280 --> 01:53:37.240
[Guest 1]: know, sending everybody in India back to the villages, right?

01:53:37.240 --> 01:53:41.280
[Guest 1]: So that was a huge action, right?

01:53:41.280 --> 01:53:47.680
[Guest 1]: And probably mistaken action, but they had the will to do it and they did it, they did

01:53:47.680 --> 01:53:49.320
[Guest 1]: it, right?

01:53:49.320 --> 01:53:54.600
[Guest 1]: So it is, I think this is one of the big questions in social science is when is there a bias

01:53:54.600 --> 01:53:58.760
[Guest 1]: towards action and when is there is a bias towards the status quo?

01:53:58.760 --> 01:54:02.200
[Guest 1]: And to try and understand this, I think is very puzzling.

01:54:02.200 --> 01:54:06.600
[Guest 2]: You know, this is also related to one of my lessons, but I'll get to that in a minute.

01:54:06.600 --> 01:54:10.600
[Guest 2]: But first to respond to what Amit said, Amit, I would have agreed with you if you had talked

01:54:10.600 --> 01:54:15.840
[Guest 2]: about, say, the contrast between 9-11 and diabetes, right?

01:54:15.840 --> 01:54:18.740
[Guest 2]: Diabetes is the slow killer, you know, people have it.

01:54:18.740 --> 01:54:23.000
[Guest 2]: You can kind of survive with it for a while, even though your standard of living is poorer

01:54:23.000 --> 01:54:24.000
[Guest 2]: or whatever.

01:54:24.000 --> 01:54:28.600
[Guest 2]: But, you know, the 9-11 is this visceral event, it plays in your head over and over again,

01:54:28.600 --> 01:54:29.600
[Guest 2]: and it's terrifying.

01:54:29.600 --> 01:54:34.400
[Guest 2]: And, you know, there's a certain fantastical element about it that doesn't leave your mind.

01:54:34.400 --> 01:54:37.280
[Guest 2]: But I do think COVID is like that.

01:54:37.280 --> 01:54:43.800
[Guest 2]: We are trapped in our homes in some bizarre, like social biological experiment.

01:54:43.800 --> 01:54:45.960
[Guest 2]: Our friends are in hospitals.

01:54:45.960 --> 01:54:49.800
[Guest 2]: You know, we know people, we've all had friends, family members.

01:54:49.800 --> 01:54:54.560
[Guest 2]: I have family members right now who are COVID positive, right, who are complaining about

01:54:54.560 --> 01:54:58.520
[Guest 2]: losing their sense of smell and taste, and I can't talk to them because they are coughing

01:54:58.520 --> 01:55:00.640
[Guest 2]: up a storm, right?

01:55:00.640 --> 01:55:04.920
[Guest 2]: We all know people who've lost parents, who've lost grandparents.

01:55:04.920 --> 01:55:07.840
[Guest 2]: The death count is what, about 300,000 right now?

01:55:07.840 --> 01:55:10.360
[Guest 2]: So this is no longer a tiny tragedy, right?

01:55:10.360 --> 01:55:11.360
[Guest 2]: And nor is it...

01:55:11.360 --> 01:55:13.800
[Guest 2]: And you go out, everyone's wearing a mask, right?

01:55:13.800 --> 01:55:15.160
[Guest 2]: So this is bizarre, right?

01:55:15.160 --> 01:55:16.160
[Guest 2]: What a bizarre world.

01:55:16.160 --> 01:55:17.520
[Guest 2]: You can't enter places.

01:55:17.520 --> 01:55:22.580
[Guest 2]: You can't go and access half the places in the same way one would have.

01:55:22.580 --> 01:55:24.120
[Guest 2]: It's winter right now here, right?

01:55:24.120 --> 01:55:27.680
[Guest 2]: We have below zero Celsius temperatures all the time.

01:55:27.680 --> 01:55:31.400
[Guest 2]: So we can't exactly get together outdoors and, you know, have a cup of coffee and pretend

01:55:31.400 --> 01:55:33.400
[Guest 2]: like things are okay for a moment.

01:55:33.400 --> 01:55:34.400
[Guest 2]: It's really hard.

01:55:34.400 --> 01:55:39.120
[Guest 2]: Like, you know, none of us is going to get together for Christmas, for instance, right?

01:55:39.120 --> 01:55:41.920
[Guest 2]: These are not low cost events.

01:55:41.920 --> 01:55:43.200
[Guest 2]: They're very visible.

01:55:43.200 --> 01:55:45.200
[Guest 2]: They're not like diabetes.

01:55:45.200 --> 01:55:51.160
[Guest 2]: They're not like, you know, driving or drowning or vending machine deaths, you know, all those

01:55:51.160 --> 01:55:53.820
[Guest 2]: other things we normally compare to 9-11.

01:55:53.820 --> 01:55:55.960
[Guest 2]: This is really big.

01:55:55.960 --> 01:56:01.120
[Guest 2]: And somehow, I don't know if it's the human ability to adapt, but people seem to have

01:56:01.120 --> 01:56:04.300
[Guest 2]: adjusted to these numbers as the new normal.

01:56:04.300 --> 01:56:06.160
[Guest 2]: No one seems to be outraged.

01:56:06.160 --> 01:56:08.680
[Guest 2]: No one has a sense of urgency.

01:56:08.680 --> 01:56:14.640
[Guest 2]: I know a few economists like Alex or, you know, Paul Romer, John Cochran, who constantly,

01:56:14.640 --> 01:56:19.560
[Guest 2]: you know, writing and posting with a sense of urgency and panic of, you know, what the

01:56:19.560 --> 01:56:20.760
[Guest 2]: hell are we doing?

01:56:20.760 --> 01:56:25.240
[Guest 2]: But most people are pretty calm about it in the narrative, which is something that's really

01:56:25.240 --> 01:56:26.240
[Guest 2]: worrying.

01:56:26.240 --> 01:56:29.320
[Guest 2]: Like, you know, this is not a situation to be calm.

01:56:29.320 --> 01:56:33.240
[Guest 2]: The lesson that I learned, which is a little bit related to what Alex said, but slightly

01:56:33.240 --> 01:56:38.760
[Guest 2]: different, is I am deeply disappointed in self-interested politicians.

01:56:38.760 --> 01:56:39.760
[Guest 2]: Right.

01:56:39.760 --> 01:56:47.680
[Guest 2]: I mean, there are some massive low hanging fruits which you could just go for, like,

01:56:47.680 --> 01:56:52.960
[Guest 2]: you know, in this emergency situation, you could really go up the situation to your benefit.

01:56:52.960 --> 01:56:58.200
[Guest 2]: You know, you could be Winston Churchill who furthered every single agenda of his while

01:56:58.200 --> 01:57:00.920
[Guest 2]: also furthering British interests in the war.

01:57:00.920 --> 01:57:01.920
[Guest 2]: Right.

01:57:01.920 --> 01:57:06.760
[Guest 2]: For instance, Prime Minister Modi was interested in, like, you know, India's health care and

01:57:06.760 --> 01:57:09.360
[Guest 2]: providing some kind of health insurance and things like that.

01:57:09.360 --> 01:57:14.320
[Guest 2]: Even before the pandemic, they announced a half hearted plan, a huge plan, you know,

01:57:14.320 --> 01:57:17.160
[Guest 2]: in the budget for last year and the year before that.

01:57:17.160 --> 01:57:19.720
[Guest 2]: This is the moment to seize.

01:57:19.720 --> 01:57:20.720
[Guest 2]: Right.

01:57:20.720 --> 01:57:22.120
[Guest 2]: And say, you know what?

01:57:22.120 --> 01:57:27.600
[Guest 2]: I will be the person like Nehru who built Bhakranagar dam or the IITs or something.

01:57:27.600 --> 01:57:33.600
[Guest 2]: I'm the person who will make this massive, you know, investment or intervention in health

01:57:33.600 --> 01:57:34.800
[Guest 2]: care policy.

01:57:34.800 --> 01:57:35.800
[Guest 2]: He might get it right.

01:57:35.800 --> 01:57:36.800
[Guest 2]: He might get it wrong.

01:57:36.800 --> 01:57:43.760
[Guest 2]: But this was sort of like the perfect opportunity to brand something Indians really care about,

01:57:43.760 --> 01:57:49.080
[Guest 2]: you know, co-opt all the finances at a war footing towards that particular agenda.

01:57:49.080 --> 01:57:50.800
[Guest 2]: And he already had this agenda.

01:57:50.800 --> 01:57:51.800
[Guest 2]: Right.

01:57:51.800 --> 01:57:56.320
[Guest 2]: And they are still nowhere on the plan to do this.

01:57:56.320 --> 01:57:57.320
[Guest 2]: Right.

01:57:57.320 --> 01:58:02.160
[Guest 2]: Why do we see Prime Minister Modi come and say, you know, ICMR is very slow when it comes

01:58:02.160 --> 01:58:03.600
[Guest 2]: to approving testing.

01:58:03.600 --> 01:58:08.160
[Guest 2]: I'm going to scale up India's testing, you know, 800 fold.

01:58:08.160 --> 01:58:09.160
[Guest 2]: Right.

01:58:09.160 --> 01:58:10.800
[Guest 2]: Where is that announcement?

01:58:10.800 --> 01:58:11.800
[Guest 2]: Right.

01:58:11.800 --> 01:58:13.840
[Guest 2]: So it's not just like political will.

01:58:13.840 --> 01:58:17.760
[Guest 2]: I'm also like, are these politicians not genuinely self-interested?

01:58:17.760 --> 01:58:19.400
[Guest 2]: Do they not care about PR?

01:58:19.400 --> 01:58:21.880
[Guest 2]: Do they not care about maximizing their budget?

01:58:21.880 --> 01:58:26.600
[Guest 2]: You know, all the things Gordon Tullock would have taught us, they're failing on every single

01:58:26.600 --> 01:58:27.600
[Guest 2]: one of them.

01:58:27.600 --> 01:58:30.240
[Guest 2]: They're not even good self-interested politicians.

01:58:30.240 --> 01:58:33.640
[Guest 2]: They are bad politicians, not in the usual sense.

01:58:33.640 --> 01:58:35.720
[Guest 2]: So I am very disappointed on that margin.

01:58:35.720 --> 01:58:40.240
[Guest 2]: I expected at least one Winston Churchill to come, you know, awful as he was.

01:58:40.240 --> 01:58:41.240
[Guest 2]: Right.

01:58:41.240 --> 01:58:46.280
[Guest 2]: But I expected one leader like that somewhere in the world to, you know, make like crazy

01:58:46.280 --> 01:58:51.400
[Guest 2]: outrageous statements and completely co-opt this tragedy to their benefit.

01:58:51.400 --> 01:58:53.520
[Guest 2]: And also, you know, maybe some good would have come out of it.

01:58:53.520 --> 01:58:55.200
[Guest 1]: But I just haven't seen it.

01:58:55.200 --> 01:58:56.720
[Guest 1]: Come in in the United States.

01:58:56.720 --> 01:59:03.760
[Guest 1]: I mean, Donald Trump could easily have won reelection, right, had he just displayed competence

01:59:03.760 --> 01:59:07.720
[Guest 1]: in even just one area of handling the pandemic.

01:59:07.720 --> 01:59:12.040
[Guest 1]: It's very peculiar because he did Operation Warp Speed.

01:59:12.040 --> 01:59:15.300
[Guest 1]: And but why wasn't there a similar program for testing?

01:59:15.300 --> 01:59:20.520
[Guest 1]: You know, there was a plan actually using the post office to send out masks to every

01:59:20.520 --> 01:59:24.080
[Guest 1]: single household in the United States.

01:59:24.080 --> 01:59:28.160
[Guest 1]: And, you know, taking action like that, I think Donald Trump would have won, would have

01:59:28.160 --> 01:59:29.320
[Guest 1]: won reelection easily.

01:59:29.320 --> 01:59:31.720
[Guest 1]: I mean, most incumbents win.

01:59:31.720 --> 01:59:34.240
[Guest 1]: He came extremely, extremely close.

01:59:34.240 --> 01:59:40.040
[Guest 1]: And yet just taking these very basic actions, he didn't even want to stimulate the economy

01:59:40.040 --> 01:59:44.680
[Guest 1]: until, you know, very late, even though that was totally in his interest.

01:59:44.680 --> 01:59:47.200
[Guest 1]: So very, very puzzling to me.

01:59:47.200 --> 01:59:48.200
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

01:59:48.200 --> 01:59:52.080
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, one of the things that we often talk about and worry about is that during

01:59:52.080 --> 01:59:57.560
[Amit Varma]: a crisis, leaders will take the opportunity to kind of consolidate state power.

01:59:57.560 --> 01:59:59.480
[Amit Varma]: And that's only a bad thing in the long run.

01:59:59.480 --> 02:00:03.680
[Amit Varma]: And my response to that in the context of India is that, listen, our state is too incompetent

02:00:03.680 --> 02:00:04.680
[Amit Varma]: to do that properly.

02:00:04.680 --> 02:00:09.080
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, so in a sense, it's a damn good thing that these people haven't shown that

02:00:09.080 --> 02:00:13.320
[Amit Varma]: kind of leadership because it would have manifested in the wrong kinds of things.

02:00:13.320 --> 02:00:14.720
[Amit Varma]: So is that the big lesson here?

02:00:14.720 --> 02:00:18.560
[Amit Varma]: Like is your fourth lesson, Shruti, really that really about the incompetence of the

02:00:18.560 --> 02:00:19.560
[Guest 2]: state?

02:00:19.560 --> 02:00:27.000
[Guest 2]: My fourth lesson is my priors about politicians have had to really change, right?

02:00:27.000 --> 02:00:29.600
[Guest 2]: As a public choice economist, right?

02:00:29.600 --> 02:00:34.080
[Guest 2]: The constant thing we are thinking about is politicians are rational, self-interested

02:00:34.080 --> 02:00:35.080
[Guest 2]: people.

02:00:35.080 --> 02:00:36.480
[Guest 2]: They can't be trusted with power.

02:00:36.480 --> 02:00:40.940
[Guest 2]: We must keep checking their power, even if it is at the, you know, tradeoff of slowing

02:00:40.940 --> 02:00:43.640
[Guest 2]: things down or making things incompetent.

02:00:43.640 --> 02:00:48.040
[Guest 2]: Only in extreme emergencies like war and a global pandemic must we give them even a little

02:00:48.040 --> 02:00:49.040
[Guest 2]: bit of leeway.

02:00:49.040 --> 02:00:52.840
[Guest 2]: And I'm like, frankly, they have all the leeway, they're just not doing anything with it.

02:00:52.840 --> 02:01:00.760
[Guest 2]: My lesson is I have had to seriously think about and revise my priors about self-interested

02:01:00.760 --> 02:01:03.680
[Guest 2]: politicians and how they behave, right?

02:01:03.680 --> 02:01:08.440
[Guest 2]: Somehow inaction in a pandemic doesn't seem to hurt their prospects very much, or even

02:01:08.440 --> 02:01:11.840
[Guest 2]: if it will hurt their prospects, they don't want to be seen doing very much.

02:01:11.840 --> 02:01:13.560
[Guest 2]: And I can't figure out why.

02:01:13.560 --> 02:01:19.280
[Guest 2]: I just can't figure out why they wouldn't co-opt this, you know, in their peculiar way.

02:01:19.280 --> 02:01:24.400
[Guest 2]: Like, for instance, if I were doing vaccine research right now, I would completely co-opt

02:01:24.400 --> 02:01:29.600
[Guest 2]: this emergency, even if the research I was doing was not on coronavirus, right?

02:01:29.600 --> 02:01:36.440
[Guest 2]: I'd be like, oh, my God, see, the world comes to a standstill if you don't have one vaccine.

02:01:36.440 --> 02:01:40.840
[Guest 2]: You want to spend lots of money on vaccines and, you know, start this whole rent-seeking.

02:01:40.840 --> 02:01:42.400
[Guest 2]: I don't see any of that happening.

02:01:42.400 --> 02:01:47.160
[Guest 2]: So the way I would have thought, like, your classic Gordon Tullock politician would have

02:01:47.160 --> 02:01:52.040
[Guest 2]: reacted, they just, I can't find a single example of anyone reacting like that.

02:01:52.040 --> 02:01:56.720
[Guest 2]: And I don't know enough about, you know, more specific Chinese politics.

02:01:56.720 --> 02:01:59.920
[Guest 2]: If there were, in fact, more local leaders who might have done something like that in

02:01:59.920 --> 02:02:04.480
[Guest 2]: the Communist Party, but outside in the Western world and in India, I just don't see it.

02:02:04.480 --> 02:02:07.720
[Amit Varma]: They're not making dictators like they used to.

02:02:07.720 --> 02:02:09.320
[Amit Varma]: They're not making dictators like they used to.

02:02:09.320 --> 02:02:13.600
[Amit Varma]: And I guess it's a blessing that, you know, they're not acting rationally to consolidate

02:02:13.600 --> 02:02:16.760
[Amit Varma]: power as, you know, a theory predicts they should.

02:02:16.760 --> 02:02:18.000
[Amit Varma]: And I guess that's a blessing for us.

02:02:18.000 --> 02:02:23.560
[Amit Varma]: But I would at this point coin a new axiom, which I will call Verma's razor, never attribute

02:02:23.560 --> 02:02:26.440
[Amit Varma]: to virtue what can be adequately explained by stupidity.

02:02:26.440 --> 02:02:29.960
[Guest 2]: No, but it's not virtuous either.

02:02:29.960 --> 02:02:36.040
[Guest 2]: It is, I believe it might be a misunderstanding of the low hanging fruit and self-interest.

02:02:36.040 --> 02:02:39.400
[Guest 2]: Either they are misunderstanding it or I'm misunderstanding it.

02:02:39.400 --> 02:02:40.400
[Guest 2]: Right.

02:02:40.400 --> 02:02:44.080
[Guest 2]: My understanding would have been there's a huge coalition to support investments in health

02:02:44.080 --> 02:02:46.040
[Guest 2]: care in India.

02:02:46.040 --> 02:02:47.320
[Guest 2]: Maybe I'm wrong.

02:02:47.320 --> 02:02:48.880
[Guest 2]: Maybe that coalition doesn't exist.

02:02:48.880 --> 02:02:50.960
[Guest 2]: And that's why they didn't capitalize on it.

02:02:50.960 --> 02:02:54.680
[Guest 2]: But the low hanging fruit, according to me, nobody went for.

02:02:54.680 --> 02:02:55.680
[Guest 1]: Yeah.

02:02:55.680 --> 02:02:56.680
[Guest 1]: And same in the US.

02:02:56.680 --> 02:03:00.920
[Guest 1]: Like, you know, we talked a lot about Trump, but in Congress, you know, either in the Senate

02:03:00.920 --> 02:03:03.880
[Guest 1]: or they're the ones who are supposed to be passing the law.

02:03:03.880 --> 02:03:04.880
[Guest 1]: Right.

02:03:04.880 --> 02:03:11.680
[Guest 1]: And so where here is an incredible opportunity for a politician like somebody like an AOC,

02:03:11.680 --> 02:03:19.960
[Guest 1]: for example, to brand this as her issue and to put forward a plan and to rise in the national,

02:03:19.960 --> 02:03:24.400
[Guest 1]: you know, rankings as the anti-Trump or something like that.

02:03:24.400 --> 02:03:26.000
[Guest 1]: And that never happened.

02:03:26.000 --> 02:03:27.000
[Guest 1]: That never happened.

02:03:27.000 --> 02:03:29.040
[Guest 1]: There's no like Biden.

02:03:29.040 --> 02:03:35.280
[Guest 1]: He's not really even it's not I mean, he won because people voted against Trump.

02:03:35.280 --> 02:03:36.280
[Guest 1]: Right.

02:03:36.280 --> 02:03:37.280
[Guest 1]: They voted against Trump.

02:03:37.280 --> 02:03:42.280
[Guest 1]: But Biden was never the anti-Trump in, you know, in any sense.

02:03:42.280 --> 02:03:48.360
[Guest 1]: And, you know, he came he won, I think, because he was, again, actually the candidate who

02:03:48.360 --> 02:03:51.920
[Guest 1]: was least interested in big change.

02:03:51.920 --> 02:03:57.520
[Guest 1]: And in one sense, I'm grateful for that, you know, because the change that the other candidates

02:03:57.520 --> 02:03:59.980
[Guest 1]: were interested in was almost all bad.

02:03:59.980 --> 02:04:06.200
[Guest 1]: So I'm grateful that the Democrats chose a candidate whom, you know, I could support

02:04:06.200 --> 02:04:11.360
[Guest 1]: because he was sort of the more rational, conservative candidate.

02:04:11.360 --> 02:04:18.720
[Guest 1]: So it was very peculiar that there was no coalition or no coalescence around a alternative

02:04:18.720 --> 02:04:20.520
[Guest 1]: plan to Trump.

02:04:20.520 --> 02:04:21.520
[Guest 1]: Right.

02:04:21.520 --> 02:04:25.160
[Guest 1]: So if this is something an AOC or somebody like that could have taken up, here is the

02:04:25.160 --> 02:04:28.040
[Guest 1]: plan that we're going to deal with the pandemic.

02:04:28.040 --> 02:04:29.040
[Guest 1]: And here are the law.

02:04:29.040 --> 02:04:30.040
[Guest 1]: Let's pass the law.

02:04:30.040 --> 02:04:33.360
[Guest 1]: I mean, Congress is supposed to be the ones to be passing the law.

02:04:33.360 --> 02:04:34.360
[Guest 1]: And yet that never happened.

02:04:34.360 --> 02:04:39.800
[Guest 1]: There was still the focus of everybody, everyone who wanted big changes.

02:04:39.800 --> 02:04:45.080
[Guest 1]: The focus was on all on these cultural issues, all on, you know, raising the minimum wage

02:04:45.080 --> 02:04:50.040
[Guest 1]: or, you know, something fixing national health care or something like that.

02:04:50.040 --> 02:04:53.120
[Guest 1]: There was no big plan on the pandemic.

02:04:53.120 --> 02:04:57.600
[Guest 1]: And again, it just seems very peculiar to me, like in a war, right?

02:04:57.600 --> 02:05:02.880
[Guest 1]: You know, if the war isn't going well, you expect the opposition party to have a different

02:05:02.880 --> 02:05:09.320
[Guest 1]: plan for the war, not to run on raising the minimum wage while we're losing the war.

02:05:09.320 --> 02:05:10.760
[Guest 1]: And yet that's exactly what happened.

02:05:10.760 --> 02:05:17.960
[Guest 1]: It was like the Democrats were running on all of these cultural issues and, you know,

02:05:17.960 --> 02:05:24.280
[Guest 1]: economic distribution, redistribution issues while we're losing the war against the pandemic.

02:05:24.280 --> 02:05:31.120
[Guest 1]: And so why that didn't become the national issue, again, very strange to me.

02:05:31.120 --> 02:05:32.120
[Amit Varma]: Right.

02:05:32.120 --> 02:05:36.840
[Amit Varma]: So I'll move on to my fourth lesson now, because that's again about politics and kind of a

02:05:36.840 --> 02:05:41.760
[Amit Varma]: natural segue from this, which is that, again, it's not something that is a new and it's

02:05:41.760 --> 02:05:45.300
[Amit Varma]: something that's been commented upon before this, even by me.

02:05:45.300 --> 02:05:50.900
[Amit Varma]: But I think this year kind of really brought it home in terms of number one, of course,

02:05:50.900 --> 02:05:55.280
[Amit Varma]: you know, there is a banal fact that politics has become more and more polarized, partly,

02:05:55.280 --> 02:05:56.800
[Amit Varma]: you know, driven by social media.

02:05:56.800 --> 02:06:01.520
[Amit Varma]: Alex, you earlier spoke of what Cass Sunstein called group polarization, that, you know,

02:06:01.520 --> 02:06:05.920
[Amit Varma]: once you form your little tribe or your little echo chamber, you become more shrill and you

02:06:05.920 --> 02:06:07.900
[Amit Varma]: go more towards the extremes.

02:06:07.900 --> 02:06:10.820
[Amit Varma]: And we have indeed reverted to that kind of tribalism.

02:06:10.820 --> 02:06:17.520
[Amit Varma]: But what is also kind of worrying here is that politics, I'm increasingly beginning

02:06:17.520 --> 02:06:24.260
[Amit Varma]: to realize, is not just driven mainly by tribalism, but possibly only by tribalism in the sense

02:06:24.260 --> 02:06:27.760
[Amit Varma]: that if you look at, for example, over the last four years, how the Republican Party

02:06:27.760 --> 02:06:32.400
[Amit Varma]: was basically completely demolished by Trump and just became something other than what

02:06:32.400 --> 02:06:37.000
[Amit Varma]: it was, where it was earlier the party which would stand up for free trade and all of that.

02:06:37.000 --> 02:06:38.920
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, look what happened to it.

02:06:38.920 --> 02:06:42.840
[Amit Varma]: It was that just it was a will to power that mattered and not the principles you stood

02:06:42.840 --> 02:06:43.840
[Amit Varma]: for.

02:06:43.840 --> 02:06:47.280
[Amit Varma]: And politicians everywhere, of course, we know that when you enter politics is the art

02:06:47.280 --> 02:06:48.280
[Amit Varma]: of compromise.

02:06:48.280 --> 02:06:52.900
[Amit Varma]: You want to get to power and it does corrode character and whatever principles you may

02:06:52.900 --> 02:06:55.080
[Amit Varma]: have started out with means nothing.

02:06:55.080 --> 02:06:59.320
[Amit Varma]: But at the same time, you imagine that parties stood for something and all of that.

02:06:59.320 --> 02:07:03.040
[Amit Varma]: And in India, of course, on the spectrum, all parties are pretty much the same.

02:07:03.040 --> 02:07:07.660
[Amit Varma]: They are, you know, illiberal on economics, illiberal on social issues.

02:07:07.660 --> 02:07:11.280
[Amit Varma]: And it's just a question of degree and nuances and details.

02:07:11.280 --> 02:07:14.620
[Amit Varma]: But what I have also seen is that this is not just true of politicians.

02:07:14.620 --> 02:07:18.360
[Amit Varma]: This is also true of voters who support political parties.

02:07:18.360 --> 02:07:24.080
[Amit Varma]: Like, if you just see people's different reactions to the lockdown in the US, Trump was against

02:07:24.080 --> 02:07:25.080
[Amit Varma]: a lockdown.

02:07:25.080 --> 02:07:29.360
[Amit Varma]: So people who are on the left, therefore, you know, would naturally be for it.

02:07:29.360 --> 02:07:32.720
[Amit Varma]: And in India, it was the other way around that Modi called for a lockdown.

02:07:32.720 --> 02:07:36.000
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, it kind of goes the other way, which is bizarre, because typically before

02:07:36.000 --> 02:07:39.480
[Amit Varma]: that you have, you know, Modi supporters also being Trump supporters.

02:07:39.480 --> 02:07:45.680
[Amit Varma]: Similarly, you know, as someone who has written about policy, edited a magazine on policy,

02:07:45.680 --> 02:07:49.700
[Amit Varma]: my sense always was that you have to evaluate a policy on its own terms.

02:07:49.700 --> 02:07:52.000
[Amit Varma]: It doesn't matter who's bringing it out.

02:07:52.000 --> 02:07:57.560
[Amit Varma]: And yet, after, you know, decades of, you know, all parties agreeing at an intellectual

02:07:57.560 --> 02:08:02.320
[Amit Varma]: level that our labor laws need to be reformed, that agriculture needs to be reformed, when

02:08:02.320 --> 02:08:06.520
[Amit Varma]: some kind of reforms, even if they were flawed in a limited sense, but broadly a move in

02:08:06.520 --> 02:08:11.080
[Amit Varma]: the right direction, when some kind of reforms are brought out by governments, which, you

02:08:11.080 --> 02:08:15.600
[Amit Varma]: know, people like us otherwise oppose, you had a lot of people reflexively opposing those

02:08:15.600 --> 02:08:19.060
[Amit Varma]: policies only because they are against a party in question.

02:08:19.060 --> 02:08:23.200
[Amit Varma]: And for example, in the farm bills, you know, the Congress has had very similar measures

02:08:23.200 --> 02:08:28.440
[Amit Varma]: on their manifesto, when AAP ran a previous state election, they had very similar things

02:08:28.440 --> 02:08:30.060
[Amit Varma]: on their manifesto.

02:08:30.060 --> 02:08:34.060
[Amit Varma]: You know, all experts in the field before this have all unanimously agreed that these

02:08:34.060 --> 02:08:35.620
[Amit Varma]: are the reforms we need.

02:08:35.620 --> 02:08:40.240
[Amit Varma]: We need to empower farmers with choice, remove the monopoly of these middlemen, so on and

02:08:40.240 --> 02:08:41.400
[Amit Varma]: so forth.

02:08:41.400 --> 02:08:47.120
[Amit Varma]: And yet now, because of the politics of it, you completely ignore, you know, and it's

02:08:47.120 --> 02:08:51.240
[Amit Varma]: so predictable now that when I talk about politics with someone, you know, if they are

02:08:51.240 --> 02:08:57.340
[Amit Varma]: against party A and for party B, they will not be able to tell me one good thing that

02:08:57.340 --> 02:09:01.720
[Amit Varma]: party A has done, because they're against the party, or one bad thing that the politician

02:09:01.720 --> 02:09:03.360
[Amit Varma]: they admire has done.

02:09:03.360 --> 02:09:09.320
[Amit Varma]: Because again, you know, so A, it's tribal, and it almost takes on sort of a religious

02:09:09.320 --> 02:09:11.320
[Amit Varma]: level of belief.

02:09:11.320 --> 02:09:16.000
[Amit Varma]: And if this is the case, if all our stands and our positions are going to be determined

02:09:16.000 --> 02:09:21.520
[Amit Varma]: by this kind of reflexive tribalism, then where is the open debate, where is the discourse

02:09:21.520 --> 02:09:22.520
[Amit Varma]: going?

02:09:22.520 --> 02:09:27.640
[Amit Varma]: And this kind of has, in a sense, 2020, of course, has made people lose hope in many

02:09:27.640 --> 02:09:29.080
[Amit Varma]: other dimensions.

02:09:29.080 --> 02:09:34.280
[Amit Varma]: But I have lost hope of our politics ever really being reformed or, you know, because

02:09:34.280 --> 02:09:39.000
[Amit Varma]: it's not just the politicians who don't care about principles, it's everybody else as well.

02:09:39.000 --> 02:09:40.000
[Guest 1]: That's tribal.

02:09:40.000 --> 02:09:45.660
[Guest 1]: And there's also this massive gaslighting, which goes on, in that people act like whatever

02:09:45.660 --> 02:09:49.320
[Guest 1]: we're doing at this very moment has always been this way.

02:09:49.320 --> 02:09:56.100
[Guest 1]: So this bizarre thing happened in the United States, where at the beginning of the crisis,

02:09:56.100 --> 02:09:59.880
[Guest 1]: it was the liberals who were saying, don't worry about it.

02:09:59.880 --> 02:10:04.200
[Guest 1]: This is just like the flu, okay, there's not going to be any problems.

02:10:04.200 --> 02:10:07.000
[Guest 1]: We don't need a travel, you know, shutdown.

02:10:07.000 --> 02:10:12.200
[Guest 1]: And it was the conservatives who were saying, no, we need a shutdown from China, we need

02:10:12.200 --> 02:10:14.920
[Guest 1]: to have a travel shutdown, as Trump did.

02:10:14.920 --> 02:10:20.240
[Guest 1]: And it was the conservatives on Twitter, you know, there were some libertarian types and

02:10:20.240 --> 02:10:26.520
[Guest 1]: some radical types who actually had this early on, like Balaji Srinivasan.

02:10:26.520 --> 02:10:29.120
[Guest 1]: And these guys were ahead of the curve.

02:10:29.120 --> 02:10:37.000
[Guest 1]: And then within a matter of weeks, it really bizarrely just suddenly shifted while the

02:10:37.000 --> 02:10:42.840
[Guest 1]: conservatives who had been warning about this, it suddenly became, oh, no, no, no, no, that's

02:10:42.840 --> 02:10:44.040
[Guest 1]: not our tribe.

02:10:44.040 --> 02:10:50.440
[Guest 1]: Our tribe has decided, Trump has decided that our tribe is going to be anti-mask, is going

02:10:50.440 --> 02:10:54.320
[Guest 1]: to be anti-virus, is going to pretend that this isn't happening.

02:10:54.320 --> 02:10:55.600
[Guest 1]: And they all switched.

02:10:55.600 --> 02:10:57.080
[Guest 1]: And same with the liberals.

02:10:57.080 --> 02:11:02.460
[Guest 1]: So like the liberals right now, like on Twitter, like right now, you know, you know, going

02:11:02.460 --> 02:11:07.520
[Guest 1]: on about the CDC, all kinds of stuff, I won't get into it.

02:11:07.520 --> 02:11:11.680
[Guest 1]: It's completely the opposite of what they were saying, you know, eight months ago, right?

02:11:11.680 --> 02:11:14.320
[Guest 1]: They've completely changed from eight months ago.

02:11:14.320 --> 02:11:19.640
[Guest 1]: And what is more, there's a gaslighting in that there's never any acknowledgement that,

02:11:19.640 --> 02:11:25.280
[Guest 1]: hey, you, eight months ago, were saying this is not going to be a big deal, that we don't

02:11:25.280 --> 02:11:30.920
[Guest 1]: need, we shouldn't overreact, that Trump is using this, you know, to gain political power.

02:11:30.920 --> 02:11:35.040
[Guest 1]: That's what you were saying eight months ago, Mr. Epidemiologist, you know, Mr. Scientific

02:11:35.040 --> 02:11:36.040
[Guest 1]: Expert.

02:11:36.040 --> 02:11:38.800
[Guest 1]: This is what you were telling us, this is what you were advising the public.

02:11:38.800 --> 02:11:41.760
[Guest 1]: You were telling the public eight months ago, don't worry about masks.

02:11:41.760 --> 02:11:44.120
[Guest 1]: You don't need masks, okay?

02:11:44.120 --> 02:11:45.480
[Guest 1]: Masks are just for doctors.

02:11:45.480 --> 02:11:46.640
[Guest 1]: You don't need them.

02:11:46.640 --> 02:11:48.380
[Guest 1]: It's not going to be a problem.

02:11:48.380 --> 02:11:52.320
[Guest 1]: You know, it's not where the flu kills 30,000 people a year.

02:11:52.320 --> 02:11:54.080
[Guest 1]: So don't worry about this.

02:11:54.080 --> 02:11:57.680
[Guest 1]: It's only going to be like, you know, 100 people, you know, like, well, that's what

02:11:57.680 --> 02:11:59.120
[Guest 1]: you were saying eight months ago.

02:11:59.120 --> 02:12:01.080
[Guest 1]: And now you're all blah, blah, blah.

02:12:01.080 --> 02:12:02.640
[Guest 1]: And there's, and I don't mind that.

02:12:02.640 --> 02:12:04.840
[Guest 1]: Look, look, people should change their mind, right?

02:12:04.840 --> 02:12:05.840
[Guest 1]: Okay.

02:12:05.840 --> 02:12:07.680
[Guest 1]: You know, we should be Bayesians.

02:12:07.680 --> 02:12:10.280
[Guest 1]: People should change their mind when the evidence changes.

02:12:10.280 --> 02:12:14.060
[Guest 1]: So I'm not criticizing them for changing their mind.

02:12:14.060 --> 02:12:21.120
[Guest 1]: What I am criticizing is that they now think that to hold the opposite view is like evil.

02:12:21.120 --> 02:12:24.880
[Guest 1]: And that's the view they had just eight months ago.

02:12:24.880 --> 02:12:28.280
[Guest 1]: You know, you must be stupid or evil to have this.

02:12:28.280 --> 02:12:32.680
[Guest 1]: And there's no recognition that they themselves have completely changed their mind and reversed

02:12:32.680 --> 02:12:34.300
[Guest 1]: course.

02:12:34.300 --> 02:12:38.480
[Guest 1]: And it's just a massive gaslighting, which goes on in both sides.

02:12:38.480 --> 02:12:39.480
[Guest 1]: Both sides do it, right?

02:12:39.480 --> 02:12:44.400
[Guest 1]: There's no, you know, Trump at the same time wants to say, you know, we shut down against

02:12:44.400 --> 02:12:47.880
[Guest 1]: China because we knew the pandemic was going to be important.

02:12:47.880 --> 02:12:52.000
[Guest 1]: And at the same time, so it's not important, you know, just go back to work, right?

02:12:52.000 --> 02:12:59.680
[Guest 1]: I mean, so these cultural things, as exactly as you say, they're tribal and the speed at

02:12:59.680 --> 02:13:01.960
[Guest 1]: which the tribe can shift.

02:13:01.960 --> 02:13:08.760
[Guest 1]: It's like those birds, the murmuration, right, you know, they're flying one way and they're

02:13:08.760 --> 02:13:10.640
[Guest 1]: going the other way.

02:13:10.640 --> 02:13:18.440
[Guest 1]: And woe, you know, and if you don't follow your tribe, you know, woe to you, right?

02:13:18.440 --> 02:13:23.560
[Guest 1]: Because if you're the one bird which doesn't know to turn when every other bird turns,

02:13:23.560 --> 02:13:28.520
[Guest 1]: you know, then you are going to become evil and you're going to be attacked by your tribe.

02:13:28.520 --> 02:13:33.200
[Guest 1]: And they're going to say that you're stupid, you're evil, you're, you know, how could you

02:13:33.200 --> 02:13:35.040
[Guest 1]: possibly think this?

02:13:35.040 --> 02:13:39.120
[Guest 1]: And if you don't stick with your tribe, you're crushed, you're crushed.

02:13:39.120 --> 02:13:40.640
[Guest 2]: And that's the craziness of it all.

02:13:40.640 --> 02:13:42.360
[Guest 2]: You know, there's another aspect to it.

02:13:42.360 --> 02:13:46.920
[Guest 2]: So this is in particular, I don't want to name names, but some of it might be clear.

02:13:46.920 --> 02:13:53.440
[Guest 2]: We've had, like you said, you know, economists, experts who supported the farm bills when

02:13:53.440 --> 02:13:57.800
[Guest 2]: it was a previous government who no longer supported or were at least hedging, you know,

02:13:57.800 --> 02:14:00.920
[Guest 2]: and saying, oh, but it's this issue of contract enforcement or something, you know, there's

02:14:00.920 --> 02:14:02.440
[Guest 2]: all this stuff that keeps coming up.

02:14:02.440 --> 02:14:04.760
[Guest 2]: They're very good economists, right?

02:14:04.760 --> 02:14:09.120
[Guest 2]: I cannot imagine them saying this in the classroom, right?

02:14:09.120 --> 02:14:16.720
[Guest 2]: But I think everyone does somewhere have to worry about, you know, where their next gig

02:14:16.720 --> 02:14:18.560
[Guest 2]: comes from, right?

02:14:18.560 --> 02:14:23.440
[Guest 2]: And you know, this goes back to an earlier point that Alex said about this whole collectivization

02:14:23.440 --> 02:14:24.920
[Guest 2]: of all decision making, right?

02:14:24.920 --> 02:14:28.200
[Guest 2]: Now, if you collectivize all decision making and everything is political and everything

02:14:28.200 --> 02:14:32.520
[Guest 2]: is democratic, it also means everything is partisan, right?

02:14:32.520 --> 02:14:35.440
[Guest 2]: Because that's how we are choosing in politics, right?

02:14:35.440 --> 02:14:38.280
[Guest 2]: In the United States, it's a particularly acute version.

02:14:38.280 --> 02:14:39.880
[Guest 2]: It's a duopoly, right?

02:14:39.880 --> 02:14:43.320
[Guest 2]: In other parts of the world, it's a little less so.

02:14:43.320 --> 02:14:45.320
[Guest 2]: Maybe there are a few more parties involved.

02:14:45.320 --> 02:14:49.960
[Guest 2]: But the moment you collectivize decisions, it will become partisan and it will become

02:14:49.960 --> 02:14:50.960
[Guest 2]: tribal.

02:14:50.960 --> 02:14:57.200
[Guest 2]: Now, I can support labor law, even if it is coming from the stables of Yogi Adityanath,

02:14:57.200 --> 02:15:04.200
[Guest 2]: who I otherwise abhor, because my bills are paid thanks to the Mercatus Center, right?

02:15:04.200 --> 02:15:10.720
[Guest 2]: I don't have to worry about the BJP or the Congress or up hiring me in any position in

02:15:10.720 --> 02:15:12.480
[Guest 2]: any way, right?

02:15:12.480 --> 02:15:14.880
[Guest 2]: And my next meal is not contingent on them.

02:15:14.880 --> 02:15:16.920
[Guest 2]: And I can be completely independent.

02:15:16.920 --> 02:15:20.160
[Guest 2]: I also don't live in India, which means I know that the mob is not going to come and

02:15:20.160 --> 02:15:23.320
[Guest 2]: break my windows, you know, the way they do with Siddharth Bhairavarajan or something

02:15:23.320 --> 02:15:24.320
[Guest 2]: like that.

02:15:24.320 --> 02:15:27.360
[Guest 2]: So there's a reason, right?

02:15:27.360 --> 02:15:28.360
[Guest 2]: It is academics.

02:15:28.360 --> 02:15:34.240
[Guest 2]: It is people in tenured positions, Michael Kramer, John Cochran, Paul Romer, Alex Tabarrok,

02:15:34.240 --> 02:15:36.560
[Guest 2]: who are saying these things, right?

02:15:36.560 --> 02:15:42.280
[Guest 2]: They don't have to rely on the government as experts for their next paycheck or, you

02:15:42.280 --> 02:15:47.360
[Guest 2]: know, rely on the Republican Party to appoint them to whatever nonsense post that there

02:15:47.360 --> 02:15:49.400
[Guest 2]: is within their government.

02:15:49.400 --> 02:15:52.000
[Guest 2]: Most other pundits do, right?

02:15:52.000 --> 02:15:55.760
[Guest 2]: And even if they're not directly working for the government, they are pundits in the sense

02:15:55.760 --> 02:15:59.280
[Guest 2]: that, you know, they're going to be invited by MSNBC or Fox, right?

02:15:59.280 --> 02:16:03.060
[Guest 2]: So to get your next gig, you have to do what you have to do.

02:16:03.060 --> 02:16:08.960
[Guest 2]: So I think this might be more deeply entwined to just the way we think of decision making

02:16:08.960 --> 02:16:13.280
[Guest 2]: than like this current moment of, I don't, what I mean is I don't think it's related

02:16:13.280 --> 02:16:14.560
[Guest 2]: to the pandemic.

02:16:14.560 --> 02:16:17.520
[Guest 2]: I think this is true of the war, right?

02:16:17.520 --> 02:16:22.720
[Guest 2]: Nobody on the liberal side said anything when Obama was killing thousands of civilians with

02:16:22.720 --> 02:16:24.440
[Guest 2]: drones, right?

02:16:24.440 --> 02:16:29.880
[Guest 2]: I just read Obama's, you know, the autobiography, and I thought it's going to have like this

02:16:29.880 --> 02:16:36.420
[Guest 2]: big thoughtful chapter on, you know, I really spent sleepless nights over all those civilians

02:16:36.420 --> 02:16:37.480
[Guest 2]: who were bombed.

02:16:37.480 --> 02:16:40.920
[Guest 2]: But you know, this is what I was thinking at the time, nothing, right?

02:16:40.920 --> 02:16:46.400
[Guest 2]: Like I mean, not nothing, it's acknowledged, but there's no nuanced articulation of that's

02:16:46.400 --> 02:16:47.520
[Guest 2]: what I thought at the time.

02:16:47.520 --> 02:16:51.520
[Guest 2]: I've changed my mind, or maybe I haven't changed my mind, nothing, right?

02:16:51.520 --> 02:16:58.680
[Guest 2]: And nobody seems to think that Obama has a bad record on war, right?

02:16:58.680 --> 02:17:03.040
[Guest 2]: Because in their tribal world, Bush is bad record on war.

02:17:03.040 --> 02:17:06.640
[Guest 2]: The other side, our side, good record on war, right?

02:17:06.640 --> 02:17:10.860
[Guest 2]: So my problem with Obama is not healthcare, all the usual stuff conservatives are going

02:17:10.860 --> 02:17:11.860
[Guest 2]: on about.

02:17:11.860 --> 02:17:16.600
[Guest 2]: Obama has been terrible on foreign policy when it comes to killing civilians, just sheer

02:17:16.600 --> 02:17:17.600
[Guest 2]: numbers.

02:17:17.600 --> 02:17:21.040
[Guest 2]: But again, like, you know, so the gaslighting, I don't think it's COVID related.

02:17:21.040 --> 02:17:23.280
[Guest 2]: I don't even think it's 2020 related.

02:17:23.280 --> 02:17:27.520
[Guest 2]: But it's very stark right now, because we are trapped at home.

02:17:27.520 --> 02:17:36.000
[Guest 2]: And the social media version of the movement of the birds, it's really something like,

02:17:36.000 --> 02:17:39.280
[Guest 2]: you wake up one morning and up is down and down is up.

02:17:39.280 --> 02:17:41.640
[Guest 2]: And now everything is different, right?

02:17:41.640 --> 02:17:46.560
[Guest 2]: This has happened with the defunding the police and unbundling the police or support for the

02:17:46.560 --> 02:17:47.880
[Guest 2]: police, right?

02:17:47.880 --> 02:17:54.740
[Guest 2]: I mean, the Democrats support police unions in a really big way, right?

02:17:54.740 --> 02:17:57.240
[Guest 2]: Not just the Republicans.

02:17:57.240 --> 02:17:59.480
[Guest 2]: The Democrats are union people.

02:17:59.480 --> 02:18:03.200
[Guest 2]: That's the party and built its bones on unions, right?

02:18:03.200 --> 02:18:11.680
[Guest 2]: Our current vice president, right, or vice president elect made her bones supporting

02:18:11.680 --> 02:18:12.760
[Guest 2]: police unions.

02:18:12.760 --> 02:18:17.280
[Guest 2]: So now suddenly that side becomes the face of like, you know, we must defund the police

02:18:17.280 --> 02:18:19.500
[Guest 2]: and we're anti police brutality.

02:18:19.500 --> 02:18:21.280
[Guest 2]: It's all it's everything.

02:18:21.280 --> 02:18:22.920
[Guest 2]: It's the pandemic.

02:18:22.920 --> 02:18:28.040
[Guest 2]: It's every single major issue from war to education, to police brutality in the United

02:18:28.040 --> 02:18:29.040
[Guest 2]: States.

02:18:29.040 --> 02:18:30.720
[Guest 2]: And I don't see any way out of it.

02:18:30.720 --> 02:18:32.760
[Guest 2]: And I don't see any way out of it in India either.

02:18:32.760 --> 02:18:36.240
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, this mass movement of the birds is quite hilarious.

02:18:36.240 --> 02:18:39.760
[Amit Varma]: And what Alex just said about the gaslighting in the sense that if you have a different

02:18:39.760 --> 02:18:42.120
[Amit Varma]: opinion, you are evil, period.

02:18:42.120 --> 02:18:43.520
[Amit Varma]: That's the end of the matter.

02:18:43.520 --> 02:18:47.040
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, you're scared of, you know, sometimes I'll think twice about saying something

02:18:47.040 --> 02:18:49.800
[Amit Varma]: on Twitter, because everyone's kind of going to just jump.

02:18:49.800 --> 02:18:54.200
[Amit Varma]: And luckily, the kind of people who listen to the podcast are much more nuanced and reasonable.

02:18:54.200 --> 02:18:59.140
[Amit Varma]: So I guess there's a sort of a selection effect inherent in that, which is quite delightful.

02:18:59.140 --> 02:19:01.800
[Amit Varma]: So we have four more lessons to go through.

02:19:01.800 --> 02:19:04.760
[Amit Varma]: So Alex, it's time for your fourth lesson.

02:19:04.760 --> 02:19:06.920
[Guest 1]: Let me go with a positive one.

02:19:06.920 --> 02:19:09.400
[Guest 1]: And that is the Internet.

02:19:09.400 --> 02:19:14.560
[Guest 1]: It's even better and greater and more fantastic than I thought.

02:19:14.560 --> 02:19:17.240
[Guest 1]: I'm shocked that it is actually held up.

02:19:17.240 --> 02:19:21.660
[Guest 1]: So I thought or I wouldn't have been surprised with everybody at home, you know, watching

02:19:21.660 --> 02:19:27.940
[Guest 1]: Netflix and working from home, I would not have been at all surprised if we had been

02:19:27.940 --> 02:19:34.120
[Guest 1]: faced with Internet, you know, bugginess and collapsing all the time and shortages and

02:19:34.120 --> 02:19:38.240
[Guest 1]: like the, you know, trying to use too much electricity, brownouts or the equivalent of

02:19:38.240 --> 02:19:41.040
[Guest 1]: that slagginess slowing down.

02:19:41.040 --> 02:19:44.040
[Guest 1]: And yet the Internet has been like rock solid.

02:19:44.040 --> 02:19:49.480
[Guest 1]: You know, everyone's watching movies and I haven't had a single, you know, major, major

02:19:49.480 --> 02:19:50.480
[Guest 1]: problem.

02:19:50.480 --> 02:19:52.560
[Guest 1]: The Internet has been like totally rock solid.

02:19:52.560 --> 02:19:59.200
[Guest 1]: I've been enjoying, you know, my Netflix and the chess thing and all that kind of stuff.

02:19:59.200 --> 02:20:00.640
[Guest 1]: So it's been great.

02:20:00.640 --> 02:20:03.280
[Guest 1]: And we have been able to work from home.

02:20:03.280 --> 02:20:08.560
[Guest 1]: And a lot of us, I mean, not everyone, of course, but the ability to do that.

02:20:08.560 --> 02:20:13.880
[Guest 1]: And I'm sort of reminded there's kind of a famous study of which looked at people's commuting

02:20:13.880 --> 02:20:18.820
[Guest 1]: decisions in London and how they got to work.

02:20:18.820 --> 02:20:24.160
[Guest 1]: And then for a while, because of a terrorist attack, some of the tube stations in London

02:20:24.160 --> 02:20:29.120
[Guest 1]: were closed down and people had to find a new way to get to work.

02:20:29.120 --> 02:20:31.380
[Guest 1]: And then the stations were opened up again.

02:20:31.380 --> 02:20:37.600
[Guest 1]: And what they discovered is that a significant minority of people, like 25 percent, they

02:20:37.600 --> 02:20:42.660
[Guest 1]: did not go back to the old commuting route that they had taken before.

02:20:42.660 --> 02:20:44.600
[Guest 1]: And instead they stuck with the new route.

02:20:44.600 --> 02:20:49.660
[Guest 1]: So that indicates that they needed this big shock to try something new and that the new

02:20:49.660 --> 02:20:54.600
[Guest 1]: route was actually better, you know, save them some time or something like that.

02:20:54.600 --> 02:21:00.560
[Guest 1]: And so I think that work from home, we're not all going to, you know, return back to,

02:21:00.560 --> 02:21:01.560
[Guest 1]: you know, working at the office.

02:21:01.560 --> 02:21:05.400
[Guest 1]: Some of us are going to stay working at home because it's worked better than we expected.

02:21:05.400 --> 02:21:09.080
[Guest 1]: You know, it is by no means, you know, Zoom is a problem, blah, blah, blah, blah, blah.

02:21:09.080 --> 02:21:12.880
[Guest 1]: We can go on about all Zoom fatigue, et cetera, et cetera, et cetera.

02:21:12.880 --> 02:21:19.040
[Guest 1]: But it has worked better than I think anyone would have expected in advance.

02:21:19.040 --> 02:21:27.380
[Guest 1]: So for example, this now is the season of interviewing job market candidates for economists.

02:21:27.380 --> 02:21:33.880
[Guest 1]: And we all used to travel to like Atlanta or Chicago and go into hotels and people would

02:21:33.880 --> 02:21:34.880
[Guest 1]: come.

02:21:34.880 --> 02:21:39.560
[Guest 1]: You spend all day in a stinking hotel room and, you know, your job market candidates

02:21:39.560 --> 02:21:44.400
[Guest 1]: would come one at a time, half an hour each, and you'd interview 10 of them or 20 of them

02:21:44.400 --> 02:21:46.640
[Guest 1]: at the AEA, the annual AEA meetings.

02:21:46.640 --> 02:21:48.360
[Guest 1]: I'm never doing that again.

02:21:48.360 --> 02:21:50.320
[Guest 1]: The Zoom works just fine.

02:21:50.320 --> 02:21:53.560
[Guest 1]: You know, we can interview job market candidates online.

02:21:53.560 --> 02:21:55.160
[Guest 1]: I'm never going back.

02:21:55.160 --> 02:21:59.800
[Guest 1]: And I think a lot of people are going to be in a similar kind of situation.

02:21:59.800 --> 02:22:03.260
[Guest 1]: We needed this big push, but it has worked better than expected.

02:22:03.260 --> 02:22:05.680
[Guest 1]: It's more solid than expected.

02:22:05.680 --> 02:22:09.160
[Guest 1]: And we're going to even see bigger changes than you might have thought.

02:22:09.160 --> 02:22:10.160
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

02:22:10.160 --> 02:22:13.720
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, that's a bonus lesson that I didn't put into my five, but that was among

02:22:13.720 --> 02:22:18.840
[Amit Varma]: the contenders is that we are almost in a sense lucky that this pandemic happened in

02:22:18.840 --> 02:22:24.760
[Amit Varma]: 2020 and not say 2005 because technology now allows so much like I'm being able to do so

02:22:24.760 --> 02:22:27.600
[Amit Varma]: much of my remote podcasting without a hitch.

02:22:27.600 --> 02:22:32.080
[Amit Varma]: And what I, you know, tell the students of my podcasting course also is that, you know,

02:22:32.080 --> 02:22:37.160
[Amit Varma]: the basic budget equipment that you need to start podcasting is what would have been considered

02:22:37.160 --> 02:22:39.320
[Amit Varma]: studio quality 20 years ago.

02:22:39.320 --> 02:22:45.320
[Amit Varma]: You can get professional quality output, whether it is an audio or even video without investing

02:22:45.320 --> 02:22:46.320
[Amit Varma]: too much.

02:22:46.320 --> 02:22:49.080
[Amit Varma]: I mean, there are films being shot with the iPhone for God's sake, of course, the iPhone

02:22:49.080 --> 02:22:51.840
[Amit Varma]: is hardly cheap and I don't have one either.

02:22:51.840 --> 02:22:55.440
[Amit Varma]: And of course, you know, the three of us are incredibly privileged that we can work from

02:22:55.440 --> 02:22:57.960
[Amit Varma]: home productively and we are extremely lucky that way.

02:22:57.960 --> 02:23:02.360
[Amit Varma]: And so many people don't have that choice, but it is something to note that the technology

02:23:02.360 --> 02:23:06.800
[Amit Varma]: has come to this point that many of us are realizing that we don't need to go back to

02:23:06.800 --> 02:23:07.800
[Amit Varma]: the old way of life.

02:23:07.800 --> 02:23:10.800
[Amit Varma]: We can be much more efficient, I guess, just being at home.

02:23:10.800 --> 02:23:14.200
[Amit Varma]: Like I was thinking, maybe, you know, I was telling Shruti the other day that next year

02:23:14.200 --> 02:23:18.400
[Amit Varma]: I want to try out streaming and just kind of throw things at the wall and see what happens.

02:23:18.400 --> 02:23:21.640
[Amit Varma]: And I've realized while researching it that it's really cheap.

02:23:21.640 --> 02:23:23.400
[Amit Varma]: You know, I don't need a television studio.

02:23:23.400 --> 02:23:25.240
[Amit Varma]: I don't need a production house.

02:23:25.240 --> 02:23:30.240
[Amit Varma]: It's literally doable on my own if I, you know, kind of show the will, which a state

02:23:30.240 --> 02:23:31.240
[Amit Varma]: doesn't.

02:23:31.240 --> 02:23:32.240
[Amit Varma]: But thankfully, I'm not the state.

02:23:32.240 --> 02:23:33.240
[Amit Varma]: I'm an individual.

02:23:33.240 --> 02:23:35.800
[Amit Varma]: So, yeah, but that's been a revelation indeed.

02:23:35.800 --> 02:23:41.960
[Guest 2]: I think it's also like Nandu, my husband, who both of you know, was joking with me the

02:23:41.960 --> 02:23:42.960
[Guest 2]: other day.

02:23:42.960 --> 02:23:47.600
[Guest 2]: And he said, I think you are a little too well-adjusted for pandemic life, like in terms

02:23:47.600 --> 02:23:51.240
[Guest 2]: of choice of job and luck and temperament and everything.

02:23:51.240 --> 02:23:55.040
[Guest 2]: He's actually worried about me rejoining normal society.

02:23:55.040 --> 02:23:58.880
[Guest 2]: He says, what are you going to do then?

02:23:58.880 --> 02:24:02.400
[Guest 2]: And I mean, some of this has an element of privilege, but it's also luck, right?

02:24:02.400 --> 02:24:06.320
[Guest 2]: I mean, doctors are incredibly privileged, but they find themselves on the front lines

02:24:06.320 --> 02:24:07.320
[Guest 2]: right now.

02:24:07.320 --> 02:24:08.320
[Guest 2]: Right.

02:24:08.320 --> 02:24:11.720
[Guest 2]: I mean, the New York Philharmonic musicians are incredibly privileged, but they are out

02:24:11.720 --> 02:24:13.000
[Guest 2]: of a job right now.

02:24:13.000 --> 02:24:18.720
[Guest 2]: So I think, I mean, the pandemic has also hurt the privileged and the elite, not just

02:24:18.720 --> 02:24:25.680
[Guest 2]: poor people, but it's just pure chance that I happen to be a professional economist in

02:24:25.680 --> 02:24:29.400
[Guest 2]: 2020, you know, and this happened to me right now.

02:24:29.400 --> 02:24:35.640
[Guest 2]: It's just luck, dumb luck, you know, and it's very hard to counter dumb luck like that.

02:24:35.640 --> 02:24:40.520
[Guest 2]: I mean, the next thing could affect my age group, it could affect my gender, it could

02:24:40.520 --> 02:24:41.520
[Guest 2]: affect South Asians.

02:24:41.520 --> 02:24:45.500
[Guest 2]: Like, we just don't know how the next pandemic will hit people.

02:24:45.500 --> 02:24:48.600
[Guest 2]: It's not going to be an equal distribution.

02:24:48.600 --> 02:24:50.520
[Amit Varma]: So some of it is just luck.

02:24:50.520 --> 02:24:53.280
[Amit Varma]: The next thing could be a virus that makes economists stupid.

02:24:53.280 --> 02:24:55.440
[Amit Varma]: Oh, wait, we already have that.

02:24:55.440 --> 02:24:56.440
[Amit Varma]: There's politics.

02:24:56.440 --> 02:25:00.440
[Amit Varma]: Shruti, shall we, shall we move on to your final lesson now?

02:25:00.440 --> 02:25:02.800
[Guest 2]: Yeah, you know, I've been thinking about this a lot.

02:25:02.800 --> 02:25:08.400
[Guest 2]: So of course, once again, like as an economist, especially public choice trained economist,

02:25:08.400 --> 02:25:11.840
[Guest 2]: I'm constantly thinking about market failure and government failure, right?

02:25:11.840 --> 02:25:16.400
[Guest 2]: And the classic public choice lesson is that we focus in neoclassical too much on market

02:25:16.400 --> 02:25:17.640
[Guest 2]: failure.

02:25:17.640 --> 02:25:21.760
[Guest 2]: And the solutions we give to counter market failure are typically rife with government

02:25:21.760 --> 02:25:22.760
[Guest 2]: failure, right?

02:25:22.760 --> 02:25:27.420
[Guest 2]: So once we take the political incentives into account, then we realize that, you know, maybe

02:25:27.420 --> 02:25:31.160
[Guest 2]: there are solutions to market failure and maybe government intervention is not the best

02:25:31.160 --> 02:25:32.160
[Guest 2]: way to go.

02:25:32.160 --> 02:25:36.840
[Guest 2]: So this is the the Cliff Notes version of, you know, so much of public choice economics.

02:25:36.840 --> 02:25:38.880
[Guest 2]: And I've been thinking about it.

02:25:38.880 --> 02:25:48.320
[Guest 2]: And I have frankly been surprised by the amount of, you know, sort of like private voluntary

02:25:48.320 --> 02:25:52.120
[Guest 2]: action by private citizens and their failures, right?

02:25:52.120 --> 02:25:54.760
[Guest 2]: And I've been trying to put this in perspective in one sense.

02:25:54.760 --> 02:25:57.160
[Guest 2]: So the state has, of course, failed spectacularly.

02:25:57.160 --> 02:26:00.680
[Guest 2]: We've talked about it for almost two hours on the margins on which the state has failed

02:26:00.680 --> 02:26:02.560
[Guest 2]: spectacularly.

02:26:02.560 --> 02:26:11.400
[Guest 2]: But I don't see 10 months into the pandemic, private individuals, civil society groups

02:26:11.400 --> 02:26:13.560
[Guest 2]: doing that much better.

02:26:13.560 --> 02:26:20.120
[Guest 2]: You know, I don't see private movements for wearing masks or getting tested or movements

02:26:20.120 --> 02:26:21.800
[Guest 2]: to speed up testing.

02:26:21.800 --> 02:26:25.800
[Guest 2]: I don't even see private movements to say, hey, this is how we can make Christmas better

02:26:25.800 --> 02:26:29.840
[Guest 2]: without getting in a room with each other, right, or make Thanksgiving better.

02:26:29.840 --> 02:26:34.160
[Guest 2]: I don't see any movements among young people saying, hey, we are not going to be so affected

02:26:34.160 --> 02:26:38.320
[Guest 2]: by this, but maybe we should say grandma or whatever, like, you know, where am I?

02:26:38.320 --> 02:26:40.400
[Guest 2]: So I live in a fairly urban area.

02:26:40.400 --> 02:26:46.960
[Guest 2]: And when I walk past, you know, when I'm walking the dogs, every single sports bar is completely

02:26:46.960 --> 02:26:51.400
[Guest 2]: packed full, right, on evenings and on weekends.

02:26:51.400 --> 02:26:53.560
[Guest 2]: Those sorts of things genuinely surprised me.

02:26:53.560 --> 02:26:56.120
[Guest 2]: I thought it might have been OK initially.

02:26:56.120 --> 02:27:01.400
[Guest 2]: Ten months into the pandemic, at 3000 plus deaths per day, it's pretty shocking that

02:27:01.400 --> 02:27:02.800
[Guest 2]: people are behaving like this.

02:27:02.800 --> 02:27:06.200
[Guest 2]: And I've been trying to think why this is the case, right?

02:27:06.200 --> 02:27:09.400
[Guest 2]: And this is, I think, going back to the Adam Smith lesson, right?

02:27:09.400 --> 02:27:15.520
[Guest 2]: The entire goal for us in society is to find institutions that will align self-interest

02:27:15.520 --> 02:27:17.960
[Guest 2]: with social interest, right?

02:27:17.960 --> 02:27:21.920
[Guest 2]: So of course, people don't want to sacrifice and they're, you know, if you're 20 something

02:27:21.920 --> 02:27:25.000
[Guest 2]: and you're not going to be that severely affected, of course, you want to go out and you want

02:27:25.000 --> 02:27:29.280
[Guest 2]: to be with your friends and you want to have Christmas, all of the usual things.

02:27:29.280 --> 02:27:32.840
[Guest 2]: But what could have, you know, changed that?

02:27:32.840 --> 02:27:34.240
[Guest 2]: What could have aligned that better?

02:27:34.240 --> 02:27:37.720
[Guest 2]: And I think that's mass rapid testing, right?

02:27:37.720 --> 02:27:44.800
[Guest 2]: If we had gotten our testing act together in March and April and just gone whole hog,

02:27:44.800 --> 02:27:50.160
[Guest 2]: built up testing capacity, approved all kinds of different tests, you know, and and just

02:27:50.160 --> 02:27:56.040
[Guest 2]: encouraged people to test frequently, test all the time, return tests quickly and get

02:27:56.040 --> 02:28:01.300
[Guest 2]: back to society, we would have had some remarkably different outcomes.

02:28:01.300 --> 02:28:06.280
[Guest 2]: Because I, you know, 20 somethings are self-interested, but they're not like serial killers, right?

02:28:06.280 --> 02:28:07.280
[Guest 2]: I mean, they're not good.

02:28:07.280 --> 02:28:11.240
[Guest 2]: Most, I mean, America is very pro-social, at least my experience with Americans.

02:28:11.240 --> 02:28:12.240
[Guest 2]: They're very pro-social.

02:28:12.240 --> 02:28:14.640
[Guest 2]: They're very engaged in civil society.

02:28:14.640 --> 02:28:16.320
[Guest 2]: There's high level of trust.

02:28:16.320 --> 02:28:20.640
[Guest 2]: You know, people are not going to fake their COVID tests and go and infect a whole bunch

02:28:20.640 --> 02:28:24.080
[Guest 2]: of people just to watch their favorite football game or something.

02:28:24.080 --> 02:28:25.840
[Guest 2]: People tend to be responsible.

02:28:25.840 --> 02:28:31.800
[Guest 2]: And the big problem was that we did not inform them about their own situation and how much

02:28:31.800 --> 02:28:33.300
[Guest 2]: risk they might cause.

02:28:33.300 --> 02:28:38.280
[Guest 2]: And we imposed all sorts of bizarre costs on them, whether or not they can infect other

02:28:38.280 --> 02:28:39.280
[Guest 2]: people.

02:28:39.280 --> 02:28:40.280
[Guest 2]: Right.

02:28:40.280 --> 02:28:43.880
[Guest 2]: And that's sort of like the worst combination in terms of aligning, you know, self and social

02:28:43.880 --> 02:28:44.880
[Guest 2]: interest.

02:28:44.880 --> 02:28:50.380
[Guest 2]: So I think the failure or like, you know, what we would traditionally call like an externality

02:28:50.380 --> 02:28:55.760
[Guest 2]: kind of failure, which has happened in COVID, I think that's just because, to my mind, that's

02:28:55.760 --> 02:28:56.760
[Guest 2]: because of testing.

02:28:56.760 --> 02:28:57.760
[Guest 2]: Right.

02:28:57.760 --> 02:29:01.440
[Guest 2]: And 10 months in, it still takes three days to get your test back.

02:29:01.440 --> 02:29:02.440
[Guest 2]: Right.

02:29:02.440 --> 02:29:05.480
[Guest 2]: We know right now there's a lot of holiday travel over Christmas.

02:29:05.480 --> 02:29:10.160
[Guest 2]: Most people who need to take an airline, you know, they need to show a negative COVID test

02:29:10.160 --> 02:29:14.200
[Guest 2]: in the last 72 hours or 96 hours or whatever the airline rules are.

02:29:14.200 --> 02:29:16.280
[Guest 2]: It takes three days to get your test back.

02:29:16.280 --> 02:29:19.720
[Guest 2]: Even now, they're not giving us test results on weekends in many of the labs.

02:29:19.720 --> 02:29:28.560
[Guest 2]: I mean, 10 months in, this is just shocking in a country as well resourced and as rich

02:29:28.560 --> 02:29:29.560
[Guest 2]: as America.

02:29:29.560 --> 02:29:30.560
[Guest 2]: Right.

02:29:30.560 --> 02:29:35.580
[Guest 2]: Given the cost of the pandemic, so many people would have been willing to spend a fair bit

02:29:35.580 --> 02:29:40.160
[Guest 2]: of money frequently to keep getting tested so that they could engage in all the activities

02:29:40.160 --> 02:29:41.400
[Guest 2]: that they wanted to.

02:29:41.400 --> 02:29:43.760
[Guest 2]: So I think that has been the big lesson for me.

02:29:43.760 --> 02:29:47.300
[Guest 2]: And I think this is an important lesson even going forward.

02:29:47.300 --> 02:29:54.240
[Guest 2]: So my sense in the early, when I when I supported the original version of the Indian lockdown,

02:29:54.240 --> 02:29:58.000
[Guest 2]: right, which was just supposed to be three weeks, it was supposed to flatten the curve

02:29:58.000 --> 02:30:01.640
[Guest 2]: and, you know, ramp up testing capacity.

02:30:01.640 --> 02:30:04.320
[Guest 2]: We never ramped up testing capacity that much in India.

02:30:04.320 --> 02:30:05.320
[Guest 2]: I mean, we did.

02:30:05.320 --> 02:30:10.560
[Guest 2]: It is better than it was before, but never enough to actually, you know, deal with the

02:30:10.560 --> 02:30:13.680
[Guest 2]: pandemic, neither in India nor in the United States.

02:30:13.680 --> 02:30:17.720
[Guest 2]: And the second thing about that was just, and here I come to the government failure

02:30:17.720 --> 02:30:21.800
[Guest 2]: and maybe even social failure, which is just the drift, right?

02:30:21.800 --> 02:30:26.880
[Guest 2]: We were all talking about testing capacity in March and April.

02:30:26.880 --> 02:30:32.960
[Guest 2]: Nobody is talking about testing capacity except like Paul Romer right now, right?

02:30:32.960 --> 02:30:35.880
[Guest 2]: Everyone has forgotten, everyone has moved on.

02:30:35.880 --> 02:30:40.560
[Guest 2]: Then it became shelter in place and lockdowns and masks and Trump elections.

02:30:40.560 --> 02:30:45.320
[Guest 2]: Now it is vaccine and who gets the vaccine first and how unfair that is.

02:30:45.320 --> 02:30:50.400
[Guest 2]: We never really solved the original problem and no one pointed out the failure in that

02:30:50.400 --> 02:30:51.400
[Guest 2]: original.

02:30:51.400 --> 02:30:55.720
[Guest 2]: So I think just information, you know, it would have really aligned self and social

02:30:55.720 --> 02:30:56.720
[Guest 2]: interest.

02:30:56.720 --> 02:31:00.960
[Guest 2]: And we failed globally in that in a big way, other than places like South Korea and Vietnam

02:31:00.960 --> 02:31:02.940
[Guest 2]: and you know, those are the countries.

02:31:02.940 --> 02:31:07.720
[Guest 2]: If you look at the success stories, they all did very, you know, they really ramped up

02:31:07.720 --> 02:31:13.080
[Guest 2]: testing capacity and their citizens behaved sensibly and their death numbers are very,

02:31:13.080 --> 02:31:14.080
[Guest 2]: very low.

02:31:14.080 --> 02:31:16.040
[Amit Varma]: Uh, so there is a lesson there.

02:31:16.040 --> 02:31:17.640
[Amit Varma]: I'll both agree and disagree with you.

02:31:17.640 --> 02:31:21.920
[Amit Varma]: I mean, uh, and the reason I'll both agree and disagree with you is that society contains

02:31:21.920 --> 02:31:27.220
[Amit Varma]: multitudes to, uh, you know, invent a version of my old cliche and therefore people react

02:31:27.220 --> 02:31:28.220
[Amit Varma]: in different ways.

02:31:28.220 --> 02:31:32.200
[Amit Varma]: So yes, many people have been irresponsible and crowding the bars and the restaurants,

02:31:32.200 --> 02:31:37.240
[Amit Varma]: but equally, what I have seen in India is that it is civil society that really stepped

02:31:37.240 --> 02:31:39.080
[Amit Varma]: up when the state failed.

02:31:39.080 --> 02:31:43.040
[Amit Varma]: For example, look at the migrant crisis that was just horrendous in Delhi.

02:31:43.040 --> 02:31:46.000
[Amit Varma]: It is civil society groups who actually fed them in Bombay.

02:31:46.000 --> 02:31:47.000
[Amit Varma]: It is in Mumbai.

02:31:47.000 --> 02:31:51.060
[Amit Varma]: It is, you know, civil society, which, uh, you know, Sonu Sood organized all these buses

02:31:51.060 --> 02:31:53.240
[Amit Varma]: to help them out.

02:31:53.240 --> 02:31:56.300
[Amit Varma]: There's this wonderful organization called Khana Chahiye.

02:31:56.300 --> 02:32:00.040
[Amit Varma]: And in fact, you know, one of the founders is a friend of mine called Ruben Mascarenas

02:32:00.040 --> 02:32:04.440
[Amit Varma]: and we've been talking about him coming on the show at some point and he got COVID himself

02:32:04.440 --> 02:32:07.200
[Amit Varma]: once and thankfully recovered and is fine now.

02:32:07.200 --> 02:32:12.080
[Amit Varma]: And what those guys literally fed hundreds of thousands of people in the streets of Bombay

02:32:12.080 --> 02:32:17.120
[Amit Varma]: and that was civil society doing something you typically expect the state to do.

02:32:17.120 --> 02:32:21.880
[Amit Varma]: So I would simply say here that, you know, that yes, it, you know, it wasn't perfect,

02:32:21.880 --> 02:32:24.220
[Amit Varma]: but in many senses it was better than the state.

02:32:24.220 --> 02:32:29.160
[Amit Varma]: And while, you know, state failure, government failure is ubiquitous, especially in India.

02:32:29.160 --> 02:32:35.040
[Amit Varma]: I think market failure is, you know, occasional and temporary and, uh, you know, so it's a,

02:32:35.040 --> 02:32:37.200
[Amit Varma]: so let's not give civil society a bad rap.

02:32:37.200 --> 02:32:40.600
[Guest 2]: No, I'm not giving civil society a bad rap on everything.

02:32:40.600 --> 02:32:41.880
[Guest 2]: Of course they do wonderful things.

02:32:41.880 --> 02:32:45.000
[Guest 2]: I mean, even in the United States, there are church groups that actually, you know, they

02:32:45.000 --> 02:32:47.160
[Guest 2]: were sewing masks and giving to people.

02:32:47.160 --> 02:32:48.160
[Guest 2]: That's not what I meant at all.

02:32:48.160 --> 02:32:54.680
[Guest 2]: I meant civil society has not had a good solution to this limited point of the externality aspect

02:32:54.680 --> 02:32:55.680
[Guest 2]: of COVID.

02:32:55.680 --> 02:32:56.680
[Guest 2]: Right.

02:32:56.680 --> 02:33:01.840
[Guest 2]: And we don't see that element being solved by, you know, voluntary action.

02:33:01.840 --> 02:33:03.720
[Guest 2]: Of course, civil society does wonderful things.

02:33:03.720 --> 02:33:09.760
[Guest 2]: I mean, how else would we solve half the government problems in most places in the world?

02:33:09.760 --> 02:33:12.600
[Guest 1]: I do think they've underperformed relative to expectations.

02:33:12.600 --> 02:33:17.640
[Guest 1]: Uh, again, in the United States, I think about, you know, who is overperformed and it's the

02:33:17.640 --> 02:33:19.720
[Guest 1]: NBA, right.

02:33:19.720 --> 02:33:22.960
[Guest 1]: And like some of the universities, University of Illinois, University of Virginia, what

02:33:22.960 --> 02:33:28.760
[Guest 1]: you see, well, you know, and, and it is because of, of testing, you know, they ramped up testing

02:33:28.760 --> 02:33:30.880
[Guest 1]: and kept their people safe.

02:33:30.880 --> 02:33:35.680
[Guest 1]: But there are not many, you know, fast grants, my colleague Tyler Cowen.

02:33:35.680 --> 02:33:40.280
[Guest 1]: But there are not many institutions which have, uh, overperformed in this crisis.

02:33:40.280 --> 02:33:41.280
[Guest 1]: Right.

02:33:41.280 --> 02:33:45.960
[Amit Varma]: So Alex, let's move on now to your fifth and final lesson, though, of course we, I'm sure

02:33:45.960 --> 02:33:50.300
[Amit Varma]: we have unlimited lessons, but your fifth and final lesson for this episode.

02:33:50.300 --> 02:33:54.440
[Guest 1]: So my fifth and final lesson is that I'm more worried about viruses than before.

02:33:54.440 --> 02:33:57.880
[Guest 1]: Now you might think, well, that's bloody obvious, isn't it, Alex?

02:33:57.880 --> 02:34:00.200
[Guest 1]: But I want to talk about computer viruses.

02:34:00.200 --> 02:34:01.200
[Guest 1]: Okay.

02:34:01.200 --> 02:34:06.680
[Guest 1]: So the next crisis, the next pandemic, I worry that our computer systems will go down and

02:34:06.680 --> 02:34:14.120
[Guest 1]: we'll all be forced to go outside and interact with people again, you know, we'll all be

02:34:14.120 --> 02:34:19.080
[Guest 1]: forced to go, oh no, I got to spend more time with my family, you know, now I've been kicked

02:34:19.080 --> 02:34:21.680
[Guest 1]: off the internet.

02:34:21.680 --> 02:34:29.240
[Guest 1]: But yeah, it does, I mean, you know, viruses do share some similarities, computer viruses

02:34:29.240 --> 02:34:34.800
[Guest 1]: and people viruses, you know, the robots could be infected with the virus.

02:34:34.800 --> 02:34:40.200
[Guest 1]: We've seen, you know, we're being hacked by the Russians or perhaps by the Chinese, depending

02:34:40.200 --> 02:34:42.440
[Guest 1]: upon who you believe.

02:34:42.440 --> 02:34:50.600
[Guest 1]: But so much our systems, including our nuclear power, our electric grid, are under the control

02:34:50.600 --> 02:34:55.840
[Guest 1]: of computers and artificial intelligences, our financial system.

02:34:55.840 --> 02:34:59.920
[Guest 1]: Most of the trades on Wall Street now are done by AIs, okay?

02:34:59.920 --> 02:35:04.400
[Guest 1]: Most of the trades are not by human beings, they're by AIs.

02:35:04.400 --> 02:35:14.040
[Guest 1]: And so creating vaccines for computers and insulating some computers from the internet,

02:35:14.040 --> 02:35:15.640
[Guest 1]: all of this seems much more important.

02:35:15.640 --> 02:35:20.400
[Guest 1]: Partly this goes back to the tail risks that we were talking about earlier.

02:35:20.400 --> 02:35:25.960
[Guest 1]: So one of the risks is from, you know, solar storms and things like that, natural risks,

02:35:25.960 --> 02:35:30.180
[Guest 1]: things like that, which can in fact are, which could bring down our computer systems and

02:35:30.180 --> 02:35:31.920
[Guest 1]: our electrical grid.

02:35:31.920 --> 02:35:34.680
[Guest 1]: And malicious actors are another one.

02:35:34.680 --> 02:35:40.200
[Guest 1]: And I don't think we have seen, you know, the big one, we haven't had the big one.

02:35:40.200 --> 02:35:45.960
[Guest 1]: And the big one is coming, you know, even just shutting down the internet, you know,

02:35:45.960 --> 02:35:50.520
[Guest 1]: for a few hours, you know, Gmail and, you know, something like that, which has occasionally

02:35:50.520 --> 02:35:51.520
[Guest 1]: happened.

02:35:51.520 --> 02:35:55.920
[Guest 1]: That's a big hiccup, you know, that's a big cost to GDP and so forth.

02:35:55.920 --> 02:36:03.080
[Guest 1]: And I don't think we've seen the big one and so much of this technology is becoming decentralized.

02:36:03.080 --> 02:36:11.000
[Guest 1]: So it doesn't take a state actor even to make some deadly computer viruses or even some,

02:36:11.000 --> 02:36:18.120
[Guest 1]: you know, biological viruses, non-state actors, even high school kids can create a virus nowadays,

02:36:18.120 --> 02:36:21.500
[Guest 1]: both biological and computer.

02:36:21.500 --> 02:36:28.320
[Guest 1]: So I think my, the weight that I now put on, the value that I now put on, you know, Norton

02:36:28.320 --> 02:36:32.680
[Guest 1]: antivirus, but more generally on, also on the U.S.

02:36:32.680 --> 02:36:39.800
[Guest 1]: The U.S. has a anti-hacking, anti-viral system, which tries to keep control of our electric

02:36:39.800 --> 02:36:41.240
[Guest 1]: grid and so forth.

02:36:41.240 --> 02:36:43.960
[Guest 1]: And I just think we need to be investing much more.

02:36:43.960 --> 02:36:47.400
[Guest 1]: And we need to do it, obviously, before the big one happens.

02:36:47.400 --> 02:36:50.240
[Guest 1]: Let's try not to be caught this time, okay?

02:36:50.240 --> 02:36:53.360
[Guest 1]: You know, this should be like a big warning bell, okay?

02:36:53.360 --> 02:36:57.800
[Guest 1]: Like how obvious does it have to be that a virus is bad?

02:36:57.800 --> 02:36:58.800
[Guest 1]: Okay.

02:36:58.800 --> 02:36:59.800
[Guest 1]: Now let's just change that.

02:36:59.800 --> 02:37:01.200
[Guest 1]: Oh, a computer virus.

02:37:01.200 --> 02:37:02.200
[Guest 1]: Okay.

02:37:02.200 --> 02:37:03.680
[Guest 1]: So we've been given the warning.

02:37:03.680 --> 02:37:06.520
[Guest 1]: Nobody can say that we were not warned.

02:37:06.520 --> 02:37:07.520
[Guest 1]: We were warned.

02:37:07.520 --> 02:37:11.760
[Guest 1]: And of course, we were warned about the biological virus too, many, many times.

02:37:11.760 --> 02:37:15.860
[Guest 1]: But now we're being warned about computer viruses, and I think we ought to pay attention.

02:37:15.860 --> 02:37:19.480
[Amit Varma]: You heard it here first from Alex Stabadour.

02:37:19.480 --> 02:37:23.120
[Amit Varma]: You know, and it strikes me that if such a virus does strike us, and everyone in India

02:37:23.120 --> 02:37:28.040
[Amit Varma]: loses the internet for a day or two, we might finally begin to empathize with the people

02:37:28.040 --> 02:37:31.000
[Amit Varma]: of Kashmir, because that's exactly what has been done to them.

02:37:31.000 --> 02:37:32.920
[Amit Varma]: They haven't had the internet for a year.

02:37:32.920 --> 02:37:35.440
[Amit Varma]: And I think most of us just take it so much for granted.

02:37:35.440 --> 02:37:39.560
[Amit Varma]: Like 30 years ago, the internet would have seemed absolute freaking magic.

02:37:39.560 --> 02:37:43.480
[Amit Varma]: You know, we are stunted without it in all the things that we do and the ways we communicate,

02:37:43.480 --> 02:37:47.640
[Amit Varma]: and even the ways we find comfort and solace sometimes.

02:37:47.640 --> 02:37:51.840
[Amit Varma]: So, so yeah, maybe, maybe, maybe we deserve that.

02:37:51.840 --> 02:37:54.360
[Amit Varma]: I'm just being facetious here.

02:37:54.360 --> 02:37:55.360
[Guest 2]: Yeah.

02:37:55.360 --> 02:37:57.680
[Guest 2]: And, you know, so here's the thing, right?

02:37:57.680 --> 02:38:02.760
[Guest 2]: I mean, when we say that we've been warned, right, of course, we've been warned.

02:38:02.760 --> 02:38:04.320
[Guest 2]: And we were also warned about this pandemic.

02:38:04.320 --> 02:38:08.680
[Guest 2]: And of course, I mean, my granddad is 104, and he survived the Spanish flu.

02:38:08.680 --> 02:38:13.920
[Guest 2]: So we also have like living life examples of being warned in one sense.

02:38:13.920 --> 02:38:18.120
[Guest 2]: I don't think they'll pay attention precisely for the reasons we talked about at the head

02:38:18.120 --> 02:38:20.040
[Guest 2]: of the conversation, which is stale risk, right?

02:38:20.040 --> 02:38:26.680
[Guest 2]: I don't think I mean, we have a better chance of Microsoft killing the hackers or holding

02:38:26.680 --> 02:38:32.720
[Guest 2]: them at bay, as we saw just in the last two days, then we have at, you know, some kind

02:38:32.720 --> 02:38:36.560
[Guest 2]: of concerted global action to make sure these sorts of things don't happen.

02:38:36.560 --> 02:38:41.640
[Guest 2]: So I have very little faith that they are listening, you know, so I think the best thing

02:38:41.640 --> 02:38:46.560
[Guest 2]: we could probably get out of this is maybe some really smart people who are all sitting

02:38:46.560 --> 02:38:50.360
[Guest 2]: in different parts of the world are alerted to this and start working with each other

02:38:50.360 --> 02:38:55.240
[Guest 2]: in a decentralized way, the way we saw with the vaccine sequencing, you know, something

02:38:55.240 --> 02:38:56.440
[Guest 2]: like that.

02:38:56.440 --> 02:39:01.520
[Guest 2]: But I don't, you know, really believe that people are going to pay when I say people,

02:39:01.520 --> 02:39:05.680
[Guest 2]: I mean, those in power will pay attention to this, you know, unless it's a military

02:39:05.680 --> 02:39:10.760
[Guest 2]: problem in the United States government, people don't pay attention to tail risks, right?

02:39:10.760 --> 02:39:15.880
[Guest 2]: So if we can convert this and say, you know, hacking a computer virus is like a nuclear

02:39:15.880 --> 02:39:21.200
[Guest 2]: attack because they can hack into your nuclear prowess, then maybe they will they will pay

02:39:21.200 --> 02:39:22.200
[Guest 2]: attention to this.

02:39:22.200 --> 02:39:24.480
[Guest 2]: But other than that, you know, it's it's pretty sad.

02:39:24.480 --> 02:39:25.480
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

02:39:25.480 --> 02:39:28.200
[Amit Varma]: And in the case of something like this one, when you say we have been warned, we are actually

02:39:28.200 --> 02:39:29.200
[Guest 2]: warned of so many.

02:39:29.200 --> 02:39:33.880
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, no one there are economists who predicted seven of the last two recessions, you know,

02:39:33.880 --> 02:39:37.600
[Amit Varma]: so it's what what warning do you even take seriously?

02:39:37.600 --> 02:39:41.360
[Amit Varma]: And even if you think intellectually that, yeah, this is a problem, you're good.

02:39:41.360 --> 02:39:44.800
[Amit Varma]: The free rider effect kicks in, you'll wait for someone else to do something to solve

02:39:44.800 --> 02:39:45.800
[Amit Varma]: it.

02:39:45.800 --> 02:39:46.800
[Amit Varma]: And you're like, what can I do?

02:39:46.800 --> 02:39:52.280
[Amit Varma]: We'll kind of as we are coming close to running out of time, we'll move on to my fifth and

02:39:52.280 --> 02:39:55.840
[Amit Varma]: final lesson, which is kind of more about the human condition in the sense that, you

02:39:55.840 --> 02:40:00.200
[Amit Varma]: know, Alex just joked about how if the internet goes, we'll actually have to talk to real

02:40:00.200 --> 02:40:02.560
[Amit Varma]: people again and spend time with the family.

02:40:02.560 --> 02:40:06.720
[Amit Varma]: And it strikes me that in 2020, that's literally what happened because people weren't going

02:40:06.720 --> 02:40:07.720
[Amit Varma]: to work.

02:40:07.720 --> 02:40:13.360
[Amit Varma]: You know, families were forced to sort of stick together for long periods of time.

02:40:13.360 --> 02:40:19.960
[Amit Varma]: And what this does is it kind of reveals the real way in which people relate to each other.

02:40:19.960 --> 02:40:25.640
[Amit Varma]: Like I think in a lot of interpersonal relationships, there is this slight delusional aspect of

02:40:25.640 --> 02:40:28.600
[Amit Varma]: what it is as a kind of inertia, which keeps it going.

02:40:28.600 --> 02:40:33.020
[Amit Varma]: And what we have seen during the pandemic is that, you know, incidents of domestic violence

02:40:33.020 --> 02:40:34.020
[Amit Varma]: have gone up.

02:40:34.020 --> 02:40:36.760
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, I think someone in England was making an argument that the reason there

02:40:36.760 --> 02:40:40.680
[Amit Varma]: should be no lockdown is all the kids who are being killed by abusive parents.

02:40:40.680 --> 02:40:42.120
[Amit Varma]: You're counting those lives.

02:40:42.120 --> 02:40:45.020
[Amit Varma]: So those are, again, kind of unseen effects.

02:40:45.020 --> 02:40:49.360
[Amit Varma]: And I think that there's been this, perhaps this increased scrutiny.

02:40:49.360 --> 02:40:55.040
[Amit Varma]: And I don't know how many people are introspective about this on personal relationships and what

02:40:55.040 --> 02:40:56.040
[Amit Varma]: they mean.

02:40:56.040 --> 02:41:00.480
[Amit Varma]: Like one of the things that I sometimes think about is, you know, Gant's warning about not

02:41:00.480 --> 02:41:03.820
[Amit Varma]: using people as a means to an end, but as an end in themselves.

02:41:03.820 --> 02:41:08.600
[Amit Varma]: And I wonder how many of us do that in our personal lives, where everyone is a character

02:41:08.600 --> 02:41:12.120
[Amit Varma]: in a drama where we have the lead role, and they're just means to an end in a sense.

02:41:12.120 --> 02:41:16.080
[Amit Varma]: And obviously, we will rationalize it and, you know, and all of that.

02:41:16.080 --> 02:41:21.680
[Amit Varma]: But I wonder how much of the, you know, that facade would have broken down in this period

02:41:21.680 --> 02:41:25.240
[Amit Varma]: of people, you know, forced to kind of be together.

02:41:25.240 --> 02:41:29.600
[Amit Varma]: I mean, I know at a personal level, all three of us obviously very lucky in this regard.

02:41:29.600 --> 02:41:32.980
[Amit Varma]: But many people aren't and many people don't have a choice.

02:41:32.980 --> 02:41:36.800
[Amit Varma]: And it also strikes me that, you know, again, at an intellectual level, and I don't want

02:41:36.800 --> 02:41:41.660
[Amit Varma]: to get too philosophical about this, but all of us wear a mask or a variety of masks.

02:41:41.660 --> 02:41:46.060
[Amit Varma]: And sometimes as you know, Vinay Sitapati pointed out in a recent episode in the context

02:41:46.060 --> 02:41:51.080
[Amit Varma]: of the BJP, that if you wear a mask long enough, the mask becomes a face, which clearly hasn't

02:41:51.080 --> 02:41:55.480
[Amit Varma]: happened with the BJP, which wore the Vajpayee mask for a while.

02:41:55.480 --> 02:42:00.760
[Amit Varma]: But it strikes me that when the mask doesn't become the face that it can sort of melt away

02:42:00.760 --> 02:42:03.040
[Amit Varma]: under scrutiny.

02:42:03.040 --> 02:42:06.560
[Amit Varma]: And you know, and I'm not being very articulate about this, but I think what lockdown did

02:42:06.560 --> 02:42:12.800
[Amit Varma]: was that it forced people to actually, you know, be in forced proximity with each other

02:42:12.800 --> 02:42:18.120
[Amit Varma]: for long periods of time, where you could no longer, you know, warehouse your family

02:42:18.120 --> 02:42:22.820
[Amit Varma]: away, but you actually had to deal with them on a daily basis and perhaps deal with yourself

02:42:22.820 --> 02:42:23.820
[Amit Varma]: as well.

02:42:23.820 --> 02:42:27.680
[Amit Varma]: So sort of an abstract point, I don't really know what the lesson in this is.

02:42:27.680 --> 02:42:33.400
[Amit Varma]: But I think this is one of the possible consequences of, you know, all the stuff that's gone down

02:42:33.400 --> 02:42:34.400
[Amit Varma]: this year.

02:42:34.400 --> 02:42:36.440
[Guest 2]: I'll point out the contra to this.

02:42:36.440 --> 02:42:39.080
[Guest 2]: I was talking to Alex about this the other day.

02:42:39.080 --> 02:42:44.360
[Guest 2]: So one of the things I realized during the lockdown that has probably shaped me the most

02:42:44.360 --> 02:42:49.480
[Guest 2]: in a way that I hadn't figured out before is that I'm an immigrant, right?

02:42:49.480 --> 02:42:54.040
[Guest 2]: And that means that I don't live in the country where I was born, it's a small minority of

02:42:54.040 --> 02:42:55.320
[Guest 2]: people in the world.

02:42:55.320 --> 02:43:00.400
[Guest 2]: My parents live very far away, everyone I grew up with lives very far away.

02:43:00.400 --> 02:43:06.080
[Guest 2]: Over the last, say, 10 or 15 years, I have been very lucky in that my closest friends

02:43:06.080 --> 02:43:08.800
[Guest 2]: are not the people I see every day, right?

02:43:08.800 --> 02:43:13.560
[Guest 2]: So I've already coped to pandemic life over 12 years, in a sense, that all my closest

02:43:13.560 --> 02:43:17.800
[Guest 2]: friends are only reachable by Zoom, I have been wishing them on their birthday and toasting

02:43:17.800 --> 02:43:21.200
[Guest 2]: champagne at different time zones and things like that.

02:43:21.200 --> 02:43:23.100
[Guest 2]: So this has been my life for a very long time.

02:43:23.100 --> 02:43:25.960
[Guest 2]: So that part doesn't feel different, right?

02:43:25.960 --> 02:43:32.160
[Guest 2]: But the part that does feel that that's very stark is there was this comfort that you can

02:43:32.160 --> 02:43:38.880
[Guest 2]: always reach people that you need to reach in a happy moment or an emergency or whatever.

02:43:38.880 --> 02:43:42.560
[Guest 2]: And that has been taken away from me during the pandemic.

02:43:42.560 --> 02:43:46.760
[Guest 2]: And that makes suddenly being far away and being an immigrant quite difficult in a way

02:43:46.760 --> 02:43:48.080
[Guest 2]: that it wasn't before.

02:43:48.080 --> 02:43:53.600
[Guest 2]: So I've had very close friends lose their parents, and I cannot give them a hug, right?

02:43:53.600 --> 02:43:57.640
[Guest 2]: Something that I would have just immediately traveled to see them at a funeral or a memorial,

02:43:57.640 --> 02:43:58.640
[Guest 2]: right?

02:43:58.640 --> 02:44:02.800
[Guest 2]: I can't, if anything happens to my parents or my granddad, who's quite old, right?

02:44:02.800 --> 02:44:03.800
[Guest 2]: Close friends.

02:44:03.800 --> 02:44:08.600
[Guest 2]: I can't quickly travel to India if I can travel at all, given all the COVID restrictions.

02:44:08.600 --> 02:44:14.200
[Guest 2]: So I always spent a lot of time far away from the world I grew up in, in the comfort that

02:44:14.200 --> 02:44:17.080
[Guest 2]: I can access it anytime I want.

02:44:17.080 --> 02:44:19.760
[Guest 2]: It's just a matter of throwing money at the problem.

02:44:19.760 --> 02:44:21.800
[Guest 2]: And now that is not so true anymore.

02:44:21.800 --> 02:44:25.640
[Guest 2]: So I've both had a lot of training for this moment.

02:44:25.640 --> 02:44:29.440
[Guest 2]: But all my safety nets and backups have collapsed during COVID.

02:44:29.440 --> 02:44:31.520
[Guest 2]: So that makes this very difficult.

02:44:31.520 --> 02:44:32.520
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

02:44:32.520 --> 02:44:37.000
[Amit Varma]: And you know, another flip side of it is that perhaps we stop taking friendships and relationships

02:44:37.000 --> 02:44:38.000
[Amit Varma]: for granted.

02:44:38.000 --> 02:44:39.000
[Amit Varma]: We appreciate it a little more.

02:44:39.000 --> 02:44:43.000
[Amit Varma]: Like I was certainly thinking the other day that has been so long since I got together

02:44:43.000 --> 02:44:45.760
[Amit Varma]: with you know, many of my friends in the flesh.

02:44:45.760 --> 02:44:49.960
[Amit Varma]: So you know, maybe that's one good thing that comes out of it, that we have a heightened

02:44:49.960 --> 02:44:55.480
[Amit Varma]: appreciation of all the actual person to person relationships we are blessed with.

02:44:55.480 --> 02:45:00.120
[Amit Varma]: And of course, I used a redundant phrase there, because what is a relationship, but person

02:45:00.120 --> 02:45:01.120
[Amit Varma]: to person?

02:45:01.120 --> 02:45:07.280
[Guest 2]: Hey, dogs, please, the most important relationships in my life, aside from my immediate family

02:45:07.280 --> 02:45:08.280
[Guest 2]: are my dogs.

02:45:08.280 --> 02:45:10.680
[Guest 2]: They're actually what got me through the pandemic.

02:45:10.680 --> 02:45:13.040
[Guest 2]: They are the happiest things in the world.

02:45:13.040 --> 02:45:16.920
[Guest 2]: They live in the moment, which is exactly the lesson we all need.

02:45:16.920 --> 02:45:21.720
[Guest 2]: Alex has dogs, but he's not quite obsessed with his dogs as I am with mine.

02:45:21.720 --> 02:45:23.080
[Guest 2]: But they're joyous, right?

02:45:23.080 --> 02:45:24.320
[Guest 2]: They brighten your day.

02:45:24.320 --> 02:45:25.960
[Guest 2]: They're so happy to see you.

02:45:25.960 --> 02:45:31.640
[Guest 2]: They are so happy you're trapped at home, 24 seven, and you will never ever leave.

02:45:31.640 --> 02:45:34.280
[Guest 1]: Like they're like, this is amazing.

02:45:34.280 --> 02:45:37.320
[Guest 1]: And by the way, the price of puppies has gone way up.

02:45:37.320 --> 02:45:38.320
[Guest 1]: Yes.

02:45:38.320 --> 02:45:41.360
[Guest 1]: So I'm going to be an economist and tell you the price.

02:45:41.360 --> 02:45:42.360
[Guest 2]: No, it's true.

02:45:42.360 --> 02:45:46.480
[Guest 2]: So we thought we would, you know, get one of the rescue shelter puppies and be like,

02:45:46.480 --> 02:45:48.040
[Guest 2]: you know, do gooders or whatever.

02:45:48.040 --> 02:45:51.920
[Guest 2]: We were on the waitlist for four months, and then we finally got a puppy from the same

02:45:51.920 --> 02:45:57.080
[Guest 2]: family we got our first dog from and actually paid like cash for him.

02:45:57.080 --> 02:46:01.200
[Guest 2]: But so I disagree that relationships are person to person.

02:46:01.200 --> 02:46:06.200
[Amit Varma]: I think one of the nicest lessons that has emerged from this is the one from your dogs

02:46:06.200 --> 02:46:09.640
[Amit Varma]: live in the moment, which is indeed a beautiful lesson.

02:46:09.640 --> 02:46:11.200
[Amit Varma]: Take happiness in the small things.

02:46:11.200 --> 02:46:12.560
[Amit Varma]: Nobody throws a ball out of love.

02:46:12.560 --> 02:46:13.560
[Amit Varma]: Go and fetch it.

02:46:13.560 --> 02:46:18.480
[Amit Varma]: And on that note, you know, thanks so much, Shruti and Alex, for coming on this show.

02:46:18.480 --> 02:46:20.040
[Amit Varma]: This has been a delightful conversation.

02:46:20.040 --> 02:46:21.200
[Guest 2]: Thanks, Amit.

02:46:21.200 --> 02:46:22.920
[Amit Varma]: It's always lovely to speak with you.

02:46:22.920 --> 02:46:25.720
[Amit Varma]: Thank you.

